In terms of my medical history, there have been no significant issues. I work as an office secretary, and I have noticed that my job has been particularly stressful lately. During my visit, my vital signs were recorded: my temperature was 98.6°F, my respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute, my pulse was 67 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 122/98 mm Hg. My body mass index (BMI) was noted to be 34.

During the physical examination, the doctor observed conjunctival pallor and mild tenderness in my epigastric region. This combination of symptoms and findings led to further discussion regarding potential diagnoses for my condition.
options: A. Acute cholecystitis B. Choledocholithiasis C. Pancreatitis D. Duodenal peptic ulcer E. Gallbladder cancer

question:
I am a 55-year-old man who visited the emergency department due to an enlarged mass on my elbow that I noticed this morning. This was the first time I had seen this mass. I have a medical history of diabetes and a significant smoking history of 35 pack-years. Recently, I started boxing as a way to get into shape. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were within normal limits. During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted the mass on my elbow. It was described as rubbery and non-tender. I am now awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely diagnosis of this unexpected condition.
options: A. Abscess B. Hematoma C. Leiomyoma D. Lipoma E. Sebaceous cyst

question:
I am a 68-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to weakness in my left leg. About four hours prior to my visit, I was out walking my dog when I suddenly experienced weakness in my left leg. There were no warning signs or prior symptoms; I simply found that I could not move my left leg as I normally would. This weakness persisted for roughly three hours before I began to feel normal again while I was in the car on my way to the hospital.

At the emergency department, I underwent a thorough physical and neurological examination, which did not reveal any abnormalities. I was able to move all my limbs without issue, exhibiting full strength in both my upper and lower extremities. My medical history includes a 20-year history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia. During my assessment, my heart rate was measured at 80 beats per minute, my blood pressure was recorded at 148 over 92, and my respiratory rate was 14 breaths per minute. I had a noncontrast CT scan of my head performed as part of the evaluation.
options: A. Acute limb ischemia B. Intracerebral hemorrhagic stroke C. Ischemic stroke D. Subarachnoid hemorrhage E. Transient ischemic attack

question:
I am a 24-year-old graduate student, and for the past week, I have been experiencing a fever, cough, and fatigue. These symptoms have been quite disruptive to my responsibilities as a student. Along with the cough, I've noticed a decrease in my appetite and some muscle aches, but I have not had a sore throat, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or constipation.

I visited my primary care provider to discuss my symptoms. During the examination, my temperature was recorded at 100.8°F. My blood pressure was measured at 123/84 mmHg, my pulse was 96 beats per minute, and my respiration rate was 18 breaths per minute. The doctor inspected my throat, which showed no signs of redness or spots, and there was no swelling in my neck.

I have been in a relationship with my girlfriend for the past two months, and I am unsure if that has any relevance to my current condition. After the examination, the provider noted some laboratory results, indicating an elevated white blood cell count and liver enzyme levels. While I am still awaiting a definitive diagnosis, I am hopeful to understand the cause of my symptoms soon.
options: A. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia B. Acute retroviral syndrome C. Cytomegalovirus infection D. Epstein-barr virus infection E. Disseminated gonococcemia

question:
I am a 78-year-old man, and I was brought to the emergency department by my daughter after experiencing a diffuse headache for one day. Along with the headache, I noticed that I was having difficulty understanding speech. I have no history of head trauma, and I typically drink one to two beers daily, occasionally more on weekends. 

Upon arrival, my vital signs were taken and found to be within normal limits. During the mental status examination, I was able to speak fluently; however, my speech did not make sense, and I struggled to repeat sentences. 

To further investigate my condition, a noncontrast CT scan of my head was performed. The results indicated an acute hemorrhage in the left temporal lobe, along with several small, older hemorrhages in both occipital lobes. 

The medical team is now evaluating these findings to determine the underlying cause of my neurological symptoms.
options: A. Vascular lipohyalinosis B. Ruptured vascular malformation C. Hypertensive encephalopathy D. Intracerebral malignancy E. Cardiac embolism F. Amyloid angiopathy

question:
I am a 23-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to a severe headache. I described to the medical staff that I experience sudden, intense pain across my face whenever anything touches it. This includes activities as simple as shaving or applying lotion. I characterized the pain as electric, noting that it worsens with any form of contact. At the time of my visit, I was pain-free, but the prospect of touch caused significant anxiety.

During my assessment, my vital signs were recorded: my temperature was 98.1°F, blood pressure measured 127/81 mmHg, my pulse was 87 beats per minute, my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was at 98% while breathing room air. The neurological examination appeared normal; however, I experienced severe pain when the doctor performed light palpation of my face. I requested morphine for my pain, hoping for relief from the discomfort I was experiencing. The medical team discussed my symptoms in detail to determine a potential diagnosis based on the information I provided.
options: A. Cluster headache B. Malingering C. Migraine headache D. Tension headache E. Trigeminal neuralgia

question:
I am a 27-year-old woman and recently experienced significant weakness in my legs, which progressed to the point where I could no longer stand. I work as a school teacher in Alaska and enjoy hiking and camping. Not long ago, I returned from a camping trip where I hiked through tall brush and drank from mountain streams. 

Two days prior to my hospital visit, I was involved in a motor vehicle accident but did not seek treatment at that time. My medical history has been unremarkable, and I take multivitamins. Aside from a recent episode of diarrhea, I generally consider myself healthy. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was slightly elevated at 99.5°F, and my blood pressure, pulse, and respiratory rate were within normal limits. However, I was anxious and exhibited very weak strength in my lower extremities, rated at 1/5, and 2/5 in my trunk muscles, along with diminished sensation. 

I also began to experience difficulty breathing, which prompted further evaluation. As my condition progressed, I was intubated and transferred to the Medical Intensive Care Unit (MICU) for closer monitoring and treatment.
options: A. Female sex living in a Northern latitude B. Hiking in tick-infested woods C. Consuming meats cooked over a campfire D. Pelvic trauma E. Central cervical spine trauma

question:
I am a 62-year-old woman who had been taking amoxicillin for acute sinusitis for 12 days. During this time, I developed a macular rash on my neck, back, and torso. As a result, my doctor switched my medication to cephalexin for another week. The rash resolved after this change; however, I soon began experiencing fatigue, flank pain, and a fever that persisted even after the sinusitis had cleared. 

I have a medical history that includes essential hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and gastric reflux, for which I have been consistently taking lisinopril, simvastatin, and omeprazole. During my most recent visit, my vital signs were taken, and my temperature was recorded at 37.9°C (100.2°F). My blood pressure was 145/90 mm Hg, with a regular pulse of 75 beats per minute and respirations at 16 per minute. 

The physical examination did not reveal any significant abnormalities. However, lab tests showed elevated levels of serum urea and creatinine, and my urinalysis indicated leukocyturia, although the urine bacterial culture returned negative results. A urine cytospin stained with Hansel's solution showed 3% binucleated cells with eosinophilic, granular cytoplasm.
options: A. Acute interstitial nephritis B. Acute glomerulonephritis C. Acute tubular necrosis D. Acute vascular injury E. IgA nephropathy

question:
I was brought to the emergency room by my mother because I was experiencing altered mental status. Over the past month, I had been struggling with my high school exams, and my mother noticed a decline in my attention and memory. She had to repeat conversations that we had just had hours before. This morning, I woke up feeling confused and disoriented, unsure of where I was. My mother mentioned that I am usually a bright student, enrolled in all honors classes.

My medical history includes being on a delayed vaccine schedule as a child, during which I contracted measles at age 6. Apart from that, I have been healthy, with no chronic conditions, and I only take a daily multivitamin. My maternal grandfather has Huntington disease. When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was measured at 99°F, blood pressure was 110/82 mmHg, and my pulse was 86 beats per minute. During the examination, I was disoriented to time and place, and my mental status exam scored 16 out of 30.

Two months prior, I had told my mother that I was attracted to men, though she wasn't certain if I was sexually active. I had not traveled recently but had started volunteering at a local hospital three weeks ago, where I received a flu vaccination. After a few days in the hospital, I began to experience unilateral, slow-myoclonic jerks.
options: A. Alcohol withdrawal B. Guillain-Barre syndrome C. Human immunodeficiency virus D. Huntington disease E. Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis

question:
I am a 35-year-old man who has been experiencing episodes of difficulty swallowing for the past three months. When I eat solid food, I often feel it getting stuck in my chest, just behind my sternum. Interestingly, I do not have any issues when drinking liquids, and I have not experienced any coughing or nasal regurgitation. There has been no hoarseness or weight loss accompanying these symptoms. 

For the past two years, I have been dealing with heartburn, which has not improved despite taking high doses of omeprazole. My medical history includes asthma and eczema, but I currently take no medications other than omeprazole. During my recent visit to the physician, my vital signs were within normal limits, and the physical examination revealed no abnormal findings. 

I am seeking to understand what might be causing these swallowing difficulties and the ongoing heartburn, especially since my current treatment does not seem effective.
options: A. Achalasia B. Diffuse esophageal spasm C. Eosinophilic esophagitis D. Esophageal reflux disease E. Schatzki’s ring

question:
I am a 56-year-old woman who was brought to the emergency department by my husband due to experiencing slurred speech and a droop on the left side of my face for about 30 minutes. During this time, I also felt numbness on the left side of my face. I had never encountered such an episode before. My medical history includes hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Recently, my father passed away from lung cancer, which has been difficult for me. 

I have been a smoker for 30 years, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily, and I typically drink one glass of wine each day. My current medications include metformin, sitagliptin, enalapril, and atorvastatin. I am 168 cm tall and weigh 86 kg, which gives me a BMI of 30.5 kg/m². Upon examination in the emergency department, I was oriented to time, place, and person. My temperature was measured at 37°C, my pulse was 97 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 140/90 mm Hg. 

The examination revealed drooping on the left side of my face, but my speech was clear, and I had full muscle strength. My deep tendon reflexes were normal, and I passed the finger-nose test as well as walked normally. A cardiopulmonary examination showed a right-sided carotid bruit. A noncontrast CT scan of my brain did not show any abnormalities. On the way back from the scan, my symptoms resolved.
options: A. Conversion disorder B. Partial seizure C. Embolic stroke D. Bell palsy E. Transient ischemic attack F. Multiple sclerosis

question:
I am a 44-year-old man who recently visited the family medicine clinic due to some small bumps I noticed on my left thigh. These lesions have been present for the last three weeks and are non-pruritic, meaning they do not itch. Over the past few months, I have experienced fatigue and a general feeling of malaise. 

I do not have any known medical problems and am not taking any medications. I smoke about one pack of cigarettes a day and also use intravenous street drugs. During my visit, my heart rate was recorded at 82 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 14 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 36.7°C (98.1°F). My blood pressure was measured at 126/80 mm Hg. 

The doctor listened to my heart and noted there were no murmurs, and my lungs were clear when they were auscultated. Upon examination, three dome-shaped, hardened papules measuring 2-3 mm each were observed on my left thigh, each with a central umbilication. Additionally, there was non-tender swelling in my cervical lymph nodes. The physician then considered the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Kaposi sarcoma B. Bed bug bite C. Molluscum contagiosum D. Atopic dermatitis E. Acute urticaria

question:
I am a 70-year-old man who recently experienced severe back pain that started while I was lifting a box about an hour ago. In addition to this acute pain, I have been dealing with increasingly severe pain in my right hip for the past two years. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, the medical staff conducted a physical examination. They noted tenderness in my lower spine and observed some redness on the skin over my right hip. During the neurologic examination, I mentioned a decrease in hearing in my left ear, which the staff assessed using the Weber test, confirming localization to the left side. 

As part of my evaluation, the doctors ordered serum studies, which indicated an elevated alkaline phosphatase level and a high parathyroid hormone level. Additionally, they performed an x-ray of my spine, which revealed a fracture in the L4 vertebra. 

Given these findings, the medical team began discussing potential diagnoses related to my symptoms and test results.
options: A. Osteitis fibrosa cystica B. Osteoporosis C. Osteomalacia D. Osteitis deformans E. Osteonecrosis F. Osteopetrosis

question:
I am a 63-year-old African American man who recently visited the emergency department due to swelling on my face and difficulty breathing. My medical history includes hypertension and dyslipidemia. A few weeks ago, I started taking lisinopril and atorvastatin to manage these conditions. 

In my family history, my father passed away at the age of 80 from complications related to a stroke, while my mother currently resides in a nursing home. During the examination, my blood pressure was recorded at 135/92 mm Hg, my heart rate was 101 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 21 breaths per minute. My temperature was normal at 98.6°F.

The medical team conducted several tests, and the results indicated that my C1 esterase inhibitor level was normal. I sought medical help due to my symptoms, which were concerning and required immediate attention.
options: A. Scleredema B. Erysipelas C. Facial lymphedema D. Drug-induced angioedema E. Contact dermatitis

question:
I am a 52-year-old man and recently experienced sudden pain in my right loin, which was accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Concerned about my symptoms, I went to the emergency department. For the past three years, I have been managing essential hypertension with bisoprolol. I have a history of intravenous drug use, though it is not recent.

Upon arrival, my temperature was measured at 36.9°C (98.4°F), and my blood pressure was recorded at 137/92 mm Hg, with a pulse of 95 beats per minute. During the physical examination, the physician noted tenderness in my right flank and observed edema in both of my legs, which extended up to my knees.

To further investigate my condition, a Doppler ultrasonography was performed. The results indicated that my right kidney was enlarged and echogenic, with an absent venous signal. Following these findings, my healthcare team began to assess the underlying cause of my condition. They noted the presence of protein in my urine and a significant number of red blood cells upon analysis.
options: A. Acute pyelonephritis B. Kidney stones C. Hypertensive kidney disease D. Membranous nephropathy E. Penile cancer

question:
I am a 26-year-old woman and I recently visited the emergency department due to experiencing vaginal bleeding and lower abdominal pain for the past 10 hours. In addition, I had been feeling nauseous and fatigued for the last four weeks. My last menstrual period was 9 weeks ago, and I do not have any history of medical illness.

Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were checked, and they were within normal limits. A pelvic examination was performed, which indicated that my uterus was consistent in size with a 9-week gestation. I took a urine pregnancy test, which came back positive.

To further evaluate my condition, a transvaginal ultrasound was conducted. The results showed unclear, amorphous fetal parts along with a large placenta that had multiple cystic spaces. I was informed that these findings needed to be assessed to determine the cause of my symptoms and the overall situation regarding my pregnancy.
options: A. Complete molar pregnancy B. Inevitable abortion C. Choriocarcinoma D. Partial molar pregnancy E. Placental abruption

question:
I am a 14-year-old boy with sickle cell disease, and I was brought to the emergency department after experiencing fatigue for the past two days. During this time, I also had occasional palpitations and shortness of breath. When I arrived at the hospital, I felt quite fatigued.

The medical staff took my vital signs, which showed a temperature of 38.3°C (100.9°F) and a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute. My respiration rate was 24 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure measured 112/74 mm Hg. Upon examination, the doctors noted that my conjunctivae appeared pale. They also found a midsystolic ejection murmur during the cardiac examination.

I am currently taking hydroxyurea and folic acid as part of my treatment for sickle cell disease. The medical team performed several laboratory studies, which revealed a hemoglobin level of 6.4 g/dL. They also checked my leukocyte count, platelet count, mean corpuscular volume, and reticulocyte count. Given my symptoms and these findings, the doctors discussed potential underlying causes related to my condition.
options: A. Parvovirus B19 B. Medication-induced hemolysis C. Defect in erythrocyte membrane proteins D. Splenic vaso-occlusion E. Hemolytic crisis

question:
I am a 23-year-old woman who recently went to the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain. Initially, the pain was dull and gradually became worse, but it intensified suddenly while I was exercising. My medical history includes depression, anxiety, and a previous case of gonococcal urethritis, which was treated appropriately. I am sexually active and do not use condoms. Additionally, I consume at least five standard alcoholic drinks daily. Recently, I lost a significant amount of weight in preparation for a fitness show I planned to enter.

Currently, I take several medications, including oral contraceptives, fluoxetine, alprazolam, ibuprofen, acetaminophen, and folate. During the physical examination, I was noted to have an athletic build, with broad shoulders and a thick neck, along with acne on my forehead and back. The abdominal examination revealed diffuse tenderness, with the pain in my right upper quadrant rated at 10 out of 10. My vital signs showed low blood pressure at 80/40 mmHg, a pulse of 110 beats per minute, a temperature of 99.5°F, and normal respiratory rate and oxygen saturation.

Intravenous fluids were initiated, and laboratory tests were ordered, including a urinary ß-hCG. I await further evaluation to determine the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Obstruction of the common bile duct by radio-opaque stones B. Obstruction of blood flow through the hepatic vein C. Vascular ectasia within the liver D. Ectopic implantation of a blastocyst E. Inflammation of the pancreas

question:
I am a 25-year-old man who visited the emergency department due to back pain that began yesterday. The discomfort has progressively worsened over time. I noticed that moving or lifting aggravates the pain, while resting and taking ibuprofen seem to provide some relief. 

I have a history of smoking and IV drug use, with my last use occurring two days ago. I suspect that my back pain may be connected to lifting a heavy box. During my visit, my temperature was measured at 99.3°F, and my blood pressure was recorded at 122/88 mmHg. My pulse was 77 beats per minute, and my respirations were at 14 breaths per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 99% on room air.

The physical examination revealed focal pain on the left side of my back, lateral to my spine, though there was no tenderness in the midline. Other aspects of the examination did not show any significant findings. I also have noticeable scars in the antecubital fossae on both arms. 

Overall, my symptoms and medical history were taken into account during the assessment.
options: A. Compression fracture B. Epidural abscess C. Epidural hematoma D. Herniated nucleus pulposus E. Muscle strain

question:
I am a 25-year-old woman who was admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) after experiencing hematemesis and shock. Five days prior, I had developed a high fever that reached 40.0℃ (104.0℉), accompanied by retro-orbital pain, nausea, and muscle aches. While the fever subsided over a few days, I started to experience severe abdominal pain and noticed bleeding from my gums. I had one episode of vomiting blood before my admission to the ICU.

I frequently travel to Latin America during the winter, and two weeks ago, I spent time in Brazil, mostly outdoors. Upon arriving at the ICU, I was feeling restless. My temperature was recorded at 38.0℃ (100.4℉), with a pulse of 110 beats per minute, a respiration rate of 33 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure measured at 90/70 mm Hg. The medical staff noted conjunctival suffusion, cold extremities, and a maculopapular rash on my trunk and limbs. There were also ecchymoses present on my lower extremities. A physical examination revealed dullness at the lung bases, and my abdomen was distended, with the liver edge palpable.

This series of symptoms and clinical findings led to my admission to the ICU for further evaluation and management.
options: A. Chikungunya virus infection B. Dengue fever C. Chagas disease D. Yellow fever E. Zika virus infection

question:
I am a 16-year-old who had an impacted tooth removed recently. After the procedure, I experienced persistent bleeding from my gums. Despite having multiple gauze packs applied, the bleeding continued with minimal effect. I have a history of easy bruising, which has been a concern for me. 

In my family, my medical history is mostly unremarkable, but I do have a maternal uncle who also had issues with easy bruising and joint swelling. I was taken to the emergency department due to my ongoing bleeding. 

The medical team assessed my condition, noting my symptoms and history. They conducted several evaluations to understand the situation better. Throughout this experience, the focus has been on addressing the bleeding and identifying any underlying issues that might be contributing to my tendency to bruise easily.
options: A. Von Willebrand disease B. Glanzmann thrombasthenia C. Hemophilia D. Disseminated intravascular coagulation E. Immune thrombocytopenia F. Bernard-Soulier syndrome

question:
I arrived at the emergency department experiencing severe pain in my head, which had started about an hour after rugby practice. Normally, I manage bad headaches with a special medication, but this time I took two doses and felt no relief. I could recall that I was currently taking sumatriptan and naproxen. Recently, I had been admitted to the hospital several times due to panic attacks and suicide attempts.

During my assessment, the medical staff noted my temperature was 99.2°F, my blood pressure was 129/65 mmHg, my pulse was 90 beats per minute, my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while on room air. To treat my headache, I was given dihydroergotamine, IV fluids, and started on 100% oxygen.

After about two hours, I began to notice slurring in my speech. The medical team observed drooping on the left side of my mouth, and they assessed that I had only 2/5 strength in my left upper extremity. A head CT scan was ordered to investigate my symptoms further.
options: A. Hemorrhagic stroke B. Ischemic stroke secondary to a thrombus C. Medication reaction D. Psychogenic symptoms E. Subarachnoid hemorrhage

question:
I am a 27-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by ambulance after an incident at a welfare appointment. During the appointment, I began to act unusually after being denied welfare. Shortly after that, I stopped responding to questions and stared blankly into space. I was motionless except for some odd lip-smacking behavior. 

A few minutes later, I regained some responsiveness but felt confused. I couldn’t clearly recall what had just happened. My medical history includes drug abuse and periods of homelessness, and I am not currently taking any medications. 

When examined, my vital signs showed a temperature of 98.9°F, blood pressure of 124/78 mmHg, a pulse of 90 beats per minute, and respirations at 14 per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 99% on room air. The physical examination revealed that my cranial nerves II-XII were grossly intact, and I had full strength in both my upper and lower extremities, with a stable gait. However, I struggled to answer questions and had difficulty remembering the episode.
options: A. Absence seizure B. Complex partial seizure C. Generalized seizure D. Malingering E. Transient ischemic attack

question:
I was brought to the emergency department by police after being found intoxicated at a local bar. I was combative and had a strong smell of alcohol on me. My past medical history includes alcoholism, IV drug use, and schizophrenia. I was receiving medications, including IM haloperidol and ibuprofen. At the time, I was homeless and had visited the emergency department multiple times for similar issues.

When I arrived, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was 97.0°F, blood pressure was 130/87 mmHg, pulse was 100 beats per minute, respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 96% on room air. The physical exam was not conducted due to my non-compliance. I was started on intravenous fluids and given ketorolac to help manage a headache I was experiencing. Shortly after, I began to vomit into a basin. The nursing staff called for help when my vomit appeared to be grossly bloody.
options: A. Dilated submucosal esophageal veins B. Gastric mucosal erosion C. Mucosal tear at the gastroesophageal junction D. Transmural distal esophagus tear E. Transmural erosion of the gastric wall

question:
I am a 19-year-old woman who was found unconscious on a running trail by my neighbor. I had been training for a marathon since the beginning of the summer. After my neighbor discovered me, I was brought to the emergency department by ambulance, which took about 30 minutes.

Upon arrival at the hospital, I was alert and oriented but felt a surge of irritability when I realized where I was. I refused to answer questions from the medical staff. I felt extremely tired during this time. My height is 174 cm (5 ft 7 in) and I weigh 51 kg (112 lb).

During the examination, the medical team noted that my temperature was 35.5°C (96°F), my pulse was 44 beats per minute, my respirations were 20 per minute, and my blood pressure was 84/48 mm Hg. They observed that I had dry, scaly skin and dry mucous membranes. A cardiopulmonary examination revealed a high-frequency, mid-to-late systolic murmur best heard at the apex of my heart. Additionally, my hemoglobin concentration was recorded as 11.9 g/dL.
options: A. Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy B. Hypothyroidism C. Heat exhaustion D. Amphetamine use E. Anorexia nervosa F. Occult malignancy

question:
I am a 5-year-old boy who recently went to the emergency department due to a rash. My parents noticed that I had been feeling more unwell lately. About three days ago, I developed a rash on my head, which has since spread to other parts of my body. Although I have generally been healthy, my condition has noticeably worsened over the past few days.

My parents mentioned that I haven't seen a pediatrician or attended any general checkup or milestone appointments. In an attempt to help me feel better, they tried some homeopathic remedies, including tuber oil, but these did not seem to work. They often take me hiking and swimming in outdoor streams, which might have contributed to my current situation.

When we arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 102°F, and my heart rate was 167 beats per minute. I was also breathing at a rate of 25 breaths per minute, and my oxygen levels were normal. During the physical examination, the healthcare professionals noted that I appeared very ill and somewhat confused. My parents were concerned and wanted to know what was wrong with me.
options: A. Rocky mountain spotted fever B. Roseola C. Rubella D. Rubeola E. Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome

question:
I am a 45-year-old man who experienced a traumatic event where I was stabbed 12 times in different areas of my body. When paramedics arrived, they noted that I had lost a significant amount of blood at the scene. My condition was critical, scoring 3 on the Glasgow Coma Scale, so they secured an endotracheal airway and established large-bore access before transporting me to the emergency department.

Upon arrival, the medical team began aggressive resuscitation using a massive transfusion protocol while preparing for an exploratory laparotomy. They inserted an arterial line and secured central access. At that time, my temperature was recorded at 95°F, my blood pressure was critically low at 50/40 mmHg, and my pulse was 80 beats per minute, with controlled respirations at 20 breaths per minute on lung-protective ventilation.

Despite receiving a transfusion of red blood cells, plasma, and platelets in a 6:6:1 ratio, along with a continuous phenylephrine infusion, my vital signs remained unchanged. The surgical team indicated that there was no active bleeding detected. A stat ScvO2 result showed 39%, although my oxygen saturation was at 100% while on supplemental oxygen. My extremities felt cold, even after the room temperature was increased to 80°F.
options: A. Cardiac tamponade B. Cervical spinal cord transection C. Occult hemorrhage D. Pulmonary embolism E. Undiagnosed pneumonia

question:
I am a mother who brought my 2-year-old son to the emergency room because he was crying persistently and refusing to move his right arm. This episode started about 30 minutes after I lifted him up by his arms. He seemed very distressed and was inconsolable during the car ride to the hospital. 

When we arrived, the medical staff examined him. I noticed that he was holding his right arm close to his body, and it was flexed and pronated. He didn’t want to move it at all, which was unusual for him. I was worried about what might be wrong and hoped the doctors could help him feel better.
options: A. Proximal ulnar fracture B. Anterior shoulder dislocation C. Supracondylar fracture of the humerus D. Olecranon fracture E. Radial head subluxation

question:
I am a 33-year-old woman who experienced a motor vehicle collision while driving unrestrained in the front seat. The collision was a head-on impact at a speed of 25 miles per hour. After the accident, I went to the emergency department for evaluation. 

Upon arrival, my vital signs showed a temperature of 99°F, blood pressure of 129/66 mmHg, a pulse of 127 beats per minute, and respirations at 16 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation was 99% on room air. The medical team performed a primary and secondary survey, noting bruising along my chest wall on both sides. Initial imaging, including a pelvic radiograph and an electrocardiogram (ECG), did not show any abnormalities. However, a chest radiograph revealed a sternal fracture and several rib fractures. 

I was administered morphine for pain relief, which caused my heart rate to improve to 80 beats per minute. I remained under observation in the emergency department for the next six hours, during which my laboratory values and a repeat ECG returned to normal limits. 

Suddenly, I began to experience shortness of breath. At that time, my temperature was 99.5°F, blood pressure was 127/68 mmHg, my pulse was 120 beats per minute, and my respirations increased to 28 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation dropped to 91% on room air, prompting a repeat chest radiograph for further evaluation.
options: A. Acute respiratory distress syndrome B. Cardiac contusion C. Hemothorax D. Pneumonia E. Pulmonary contusion

question:
I am a 63-year-old man with a history of hypertension and dyslipidemia. This morning, I suddenly noticed swelling in my face and experienced difficulty breathing, which worsened as the day went on. A few weeks ago, I started taking lisinopril to manage my blood pressure. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my blood pressure was measured at 110/74 mm Hg, my heart rate was 94 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 20 breaths per minute. The medical staff conducted a physical examination and found that my lips were swollen, and I had a stridor during inhalation, indicating a problem with my airway.

The healthcare team considered various potential diagnoses based on my symptoms and history. I was informed that my C1 esterase inhibitor levels were normal, which was part of the assessment process. I was concerned about my condition and hoped for a prompt resolution to my breathing difficulties.
options: A. Scleredema B. Erysipelas C. Facial lymphedema D. Drug-induced angioedema E. Contact dermatitis

question:
I am a 26-year-old man and recently experienced a concerning incident during a jiu jitsu competition. While grappling, I was choked and lost consciousness for approximately 10 seconds. Fortunately, I regained my awareness without any confusion and returned to my baseline state. 

To ensure my health and safety, I decided to visit the emergency department for further evaluation. I typically do not visit my primary care physician, but I consider myself generally healthy. Upon arriving at the hospital, my vital signs were taken: my temperature was recorded at 99.3°F, blood pressure at 122/88 mmHg, pulse at 77 beats per minute, respirations at 14 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was at 99% while breathing room air. 

Basic laboratory studies were conducted, and the results were unremarkable. Additionally, an ECG was performed to assess my heart's condition, and the current cardiac troponin levels were pending at that time. I am now awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely diagnosis related to my loss of consciousness.
options: A. Brugada syndrome B. De Winter T wave C. Hypokalemia D. ST elevation myocardial infarction E. Wellens syndrome

question:
I am a 71-year-old male who presented to the emergency department after experiencing a generalized tonic-clonic seizure. My son informed the medical staff that I have no prior history of seizures, but I had been feeling increasingly confused and weak over the past several weeks. 

Upon examination, I was found to be disoriented, though my pupils were round and responsive to light and accommodation. My vital signs showed a temperature of 37°C, respirations at 15 per minute, a pulse of 67 beats per minute, and a blood pressure reading of 122/88 mm Hg. My mucous membranes were moist, and during the physical examination, the doctors noted that my heart rhythm was regular without murmurs, and my lungs were clear when they listened with a stethoscope. 

My abdomen felt soft, and while my extremities showed no signs of swelling, I exhibited muscular strength of only 3 out of 5 on both sides. There was also a decreased reflex response in all four extremities. The medical team considered my symptoms and the findings from the examination to determine the most likely cause of my condition.
options: A. Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone (SIADH) B. Sheehan’s syndrome C. Lithium use D. Diabetic ketoacidosis E. Hereditary diabetes insipidus

question:
I am a 30-year-old pregnant woman, currently in my 15th week of pregnancy, and I visited the obstetrics clinic due to lower abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding. This is my third pregnancy, and I have a history of one prior delivery. Early in this pregnancy, I experienced some spotting, but I had not encountered any other issues until now.

During the examination, I felt mildly anxious. My vital signs were taken, and I was informed that my heart rate was 120 beats per minute, while other readings were normal. The examination revealed no abdominal tenderness, and the cervical os was closed, although there was a small amount of blood pooling in the vagina. The doctor did not observe any fetal tissue.

Afterward, a blood sample was taken for a quantitative β-hCG level, and an ultrasound was conducted. I was relieved to learn that there was a viable fetus with a normal heart rate. The obstetrician provided me with instructions to rest and to avoid physical activity, including sexual intercourse. I was also advised to return to the emergency department if the bleeding became excessive.
options: A. Incomplete abortion B. Inevitable abortion C. Threatened abortion D. Complete abortion E. Missed abortion

question:
I am a 20-year-old college student, and I went to the emergency room because I was experiencing persistent vague abdominal pain, along with nausea and vomiting. I noticed that I was feeling full after eating much sooner than I usually do. 

Recently, I have been pledging at a fraternity, which involved binge drinking and using substances like marijuana and cocaine. I've also been active in intramural sports, and during this time, I shared drinks and paraphernalia with other fraternity members. Some of them have reported being ill recently. 

In addition to these issues, I have a history of asthma and depression. To manage pain from minor injuries related to sports, I have been taking large amounts of ibuprofen. 

During the physical exam, I was found to have mild tachycardia and tenderness in the epigastric region. My vital signs showed a temperature of 99.5°F, blood pressure of 127/68 mmHg, pulse at 105 beats per minute, and respirations at 17 per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 98% on room air. A CT scan was performed to further evaluate my condition.
options: A. Gastric ulcer B. Gastritis C. Gastroenteritis D. Pancreatic pseudocyst E. Pancreatitis

question:
I was involved in a high-speed motor vehicle collision and was subsequently brought to the emergency department by paramedics. Upon arrival, I experienced excruciating chest pain, which I described as tearing. Prior to the accident, I had been in good health, not taking any medications, and I was not under the influence of drugs or alcohol.

During the examination, the medical staff noted my heart rate was 97 beats per minute. They measured my blood pressure, which was 95 over 40 mm Hg in my right arm and 60 over 30 mm Hg in my left arm. I also learned that there were no detectable pulses in my right leg, and the pulses in my left leg were diminished. A neurological examination showed no abnormalities.

After these assessments, a chest X-ray was performed, which revealed a widened mediastinum. The medical team began discussing potential causes for my condition based on the information gathered.
options: A. Rib fracture B. Traumatic aortic dissection C. Myocardial rupture D. Pulmonary contusion E. Diaphragmatic rupture

question:
I am a 27-year-old woman who was recently involved in an accident where I was hit by a car while walking on the sidewalk. I was brought to the emergency department by ambulance. Upon arrival, I was conscious and did not experience any pain, bleeding, or memory loss.

As a veterinarian specializing in farm animals, particularly horses, I was aware of my surroundings. My vital signs were stable, with a temperature of 98.7°F, blood pressure of 120/70 mmHg, pulse of 90 beats per minute, and respirations at 15 per minute. The physical examination revealed a small bruise over my right elbow and right upper quadrant, along with some scrapes on my right lateral thigh.

Radiographic imaging of my right arm, hip, and knee showed no significant findings. However, an abdominal ultrasound identified a 6 x 4 cm cystic mass in the right hepatic lobe. A subsequent computed tomography scan confirmed the size and location of the cystic mass. 

I did not have any significant changes in my blood count that would indicate an acute issue. My leukocyte count was elevated, but it did not seem to be of immediate concern. Overall, I was assessed for any critical injuries following the accident and further investigations were conducted regarding the cystic mass.
options: A. Klebsiella abscess B. Echinococcosis C. Cystic teratoma D. Cysticercosis E. Hepatic hemangioma

question:
I am a 75-year-old man who recently visited my physician for a follow-up examination. Over the past few months, I have experienced shortness of breath while walking during my daily exercise routine. Additionally, I often feel tired. I have not had any fever or noticeable weight loss, and I do not have a history of severe illness. I take no medications, do not smoke, and I drink alcohol occasionally, but I do not follow a specific diet.

During the examination, my vital signs were reported to be within normal limits. The doctor noted that my conjunctiva appeared pale. A physical examination of my heart, lungs, abdomen, and extremities did not reveal any abnormalities, and no lymph nodes were enlarged. 

The doctor performed several tests, including a blood test that showed my hemoglobin level was low, and the mean corpuscular volume indicated larger red blood cells. Other blood counts were within expected ranges. An abdominal ultrasound showed no signs of organ enlargement or other issues. A peripheral blood smear revealed large and hypogranular platelets and neutrophils with unusual nuclei. A bone marrow aspiration demonstrated hypercellularity and other specific changes, including ring sideroblasts and disorganized nuclei in megakaryocytes.

I am awaiting further clarification on what these findings mean.
options: A. Acute myeloid leukemia B. Aplastic anemia C. Myelodysplastic syndrome D. Primary myelofibrosis E. Vitamin B12 deficiency

question:
I am a 4-year-old boy who recently went to the emergency department due to diarrhea. A few days ago, I started having a fever, which then progressed to vomiting and diarrhea. I experienced multiple episodes of diarrhea, and I felt very fatigued during this time. 

I am not up to date on my vaccinations, and I take various herbal supplements that my parents give me. When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was measured at 101°F (38.3°C). The medical staff checked my blood pressure, which was 100/55 mmHg, and my pulse was 111 beats per minute. My breathing rate was recorded at 19 breaths per minute, and my oxygen levels were 100% in room air.

During the physical examination, the doctors noted that I had dry mucous membranes and appeared fatigued. They assessed my symptoms and medical history to determine the most likely cause of my condition.
options: A. Campylobacter jejuni B. Coronavirus C. Norovirus D. Rotavirus E. Vibrio cholerae

question:
I am a 27-year-old woman with no significant health issues prior to this experience. For the past three weeks, I have been feeling increasingly fatigued and have been suffering from headaches and a dry cough. I do not smoke or use illicit drugs. 

During my visit to the physician, my temperature was recorded at 37.8°C (100°F). The chest examination revealed mild inspiratory crackles in both lung fields. To further investigate my symptoms, a chest x-ray was performed, which showed diffuse interstitial infiltrates in both lungs. 

In an effort to identify any underlying causes of my symptoms, I provided a sample of sputum that was induced with saline. The Gram stain on this sample showed no organisms. However, when the sputum was inoculated on a specialized cell-free medium enriched with yeast extract, horse serum, cholesterol, and penicillin G, colonies began to grow that resembled fried eggs. 

This entire sequence of events has led to a deeper investigation into the specific organism that may have been isolated from the culture medium, as I seek to understand the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Bordetella pertussis B. Mycobacterium tuberculosis C. Chlamydophila psittaci D. Mycoplasma pneumoniae E. Chlamydophila pneumoniae F. Coxiella burnetii G. Haemophilus influenzae H. Chlamydia trachomatis I. Escherichia coli J. Legionella pneumophila K. Cryptococcus neoformans

question:
I am a 4-month-old boy who was brought to the emergency department by my mother due to experiencing lethargy and vomiting since waking up an hour ago. My last breastfeeding occurred the previous evening, and I slept through the night for the first time. My family recently immigrated from Bolivia.

Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was measured at 38.7°C (101.2°F). During the physical examination, the doctor noted that I had dry mucous membranes and enlarged, reddened tonsils, which seemed concerning.

My mother explained to the medical staff about my recent symptoms and history. They conducted several tests to understand what might be happening to me. There were indications of low glucose levels in my blood, and my liver enzymes were elevated. Additionally, the ammonia levels were above the normal range.

Given the symptoms and the findings, the medical team began to consider possible deficiencies or conditions that could explain my situation.
options: A. Phenylalanine hydroxylase B. Medium-chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase C. Alpha-L-iduronidase D. Galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase E. Propionyl-CoA carboxylase F. Lysosomal acid α-1,4- glucosidase

question:
I am a 27-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to a noticeable yellowing of my skin, which was painless. I generally consider myself healthy and have no significant past medical history to mention. I do smoke about two packs of cigarettes per day. Not long ago, I was treated for a urinary tract infection, receiving a single dose of ceftriaxone followed by a seven-day course of ciprofloxacin.

I had just returned from a three-day hiking trip, and I follow a vegan diet. Aside from the yellowing of my skin, I have experienced a mild cough for the past few days. During my visit to the emergency department, my vital signs were stable: my temperature was 97.5°F, blood pressure was 122/82 mmHg, pulse was 85 beats per minute, respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air.

The physical examination showed that my abdomen was non-tender, but there was mild scleral icterus and sublingual jaundice present. I was advised that further investigation would be necessary to determine the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Carotenoid consumption B. Ceftriaxone administration C. Crigler-Najjar syndrome D. Gilbert syndrome E. Pancreatic cancer

question:
I am a 9-year-old girl who was brought to the physician by my mother due to a 3-day history of swelling in my face and feet. I noticed that my urine was dark, and I developed a rash on my hands and feet. My mother mentioned that I had been experiencing a low-grade fever, shortness of breath, and a dry cough for the past 8 days. Additionally, I felt generally weak and had pain in my right knee and ankle.

When I arrived at the doctor's office, I appeared lethargic. My temperature was recorded at 38.4°C (101.1°F), my pulse was measured at 130 beats per minute, and my respirations were 34 per minute. My blood pressure was 110/60 mm Hg. The examination revealed small, non-blanching purple lesions on my palms, soles, and under my fingernails, along with noticeable swelling of my eyelids and feet.

During the funduscopic examination, the doctor observed retinal hemorrhages. They also detected holosystolic and early diastolic murmurs. My medical history includes a ventricular septum defect diagnosed at birth. After various tests, it was determined that I had some abnormalities, and blood cultures revealed the presence of Streptococcus pyogenes.
options: A. Pneumonia B. Infective endocarditis C. Rheumatic fever D. Hand-Foot-and-Mouth Disease E. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia F. Systemic lupus erythematosus G. Myocarditis H. Kawasaki disease

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who recently visited my physician due to persistent fatigue and an unexpected weight loss of 5 kilograms (11 pounds) over the past six months, despite maintaining a good appetite. I do not take any medications, and I do not smoke or use illicit drugs. 

During my physical examination, the doctor noted that I have hepatosplenomegaly, which is an enlargement of my liver and spleen, along with diffuse, nontender lymphadenopathy. These findings raised some concerns. 

The doctor conducted several laboratory tests, which revealed that my hemoglobin concentration is 11 g/dL and my leukocyte count is 16,000/mm³. Additionally, a direct antiglobulin (Coombs) test came back positive. 

Given these symptoms and test results, my physician is considering potential diagnoses related to my condition. I am currently waiting for further evaluation and guidance on the next steps in my care.
options: A. Chronic myelogenous leukemia B. Acute myelogenous leukemia C. Follicular lymphoma D. Hairy cell leukemia E. Hodgkin lymphoma F. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia G. Hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis

question:
I am a 25-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by my girlfriend due to a persistent nosebleed. I had been pinching my nose for the past hour, but the bleeding had not stopped. This was not the first time I experienced such an issue; for the past several months, I have had recurring nosebleeds that typically resolved with pressure. 

I do not have a history of hypertension or any recent trauma. I have asthma, which is well managed with an albuterol inhaler. Additionally, I occasionally experience tension headaches, for which I take aspirin. 

Upon arrival at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37.9°C (100.2°F), my pulse was 114 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was measured at 160/102 mm Hg. The examination showed active bleeding from both nostrils. The medical team noted that my pupils were 6 mm in size under bright light, and my lungs were clear upon auscultation. 

Given the symptoms and my medical history, the healthcare providers were tasked with determining the most likely explanation for my ongoing nosebleeds.
options:
A. Hypertension B. Digital manipulation C. Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia D. Adverse effect of medication E. Cocaine use F. Nasopharyngeal angiofibroma
"

question:
I am a 67-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to increased fatigue. Over the past few weeks, I have been feeling unusually tired, but today was particularly alarming when I lost consciousness while walking up the stairs. Alongside this fatigue, I have experienced mild abdominal distension and discomfort, unintentional weight loss, a persistent cough, and several nights of waking up drenched in sweat.

I do not have a primary care physician, but I do smoke 2 to 3 packs of cigarettes daily and consume 1 to 3 alcoholic beverages each day. Recently, I traveled to Taiwan and Nicaragua. Upon examination in the emergency department, my temperature was noted at 99.5°F, and my blood pressure was elevated at 177/98 mmHg. My pulse was 100 beats per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% on room air. 

The physical examination revealed that I appeared fatigued but was well-groomed. There were mild expiratory wheezes during the cardiopulmonary exam, and an abdominal examination identified a non-pulsatile mass in my left upper quadrant. Following this assessment, laboratory values were ordered to further investigate my condition.
options: A. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia B. Acute myelogenous leukemia C. Chronic myeloid leukemia D. Leukemoid reaction E. Tuberculosis

question:
I was born as a male newborn at 27 weeks' gestation and was evaluated shortly after birth for rapid breathing and hypoxia. My mother did not receive any prenatal care during her pregnancy. During the cardiopulmonary examination, the doctors noted normal heart sounds, but I exhibited intercostal retractions and nasal flaring. 

To assess my condition further, an x-ray of my chest was performed. The results showed low lung volumes, air bronchograms, and diffuse ground-glass opacities. Given these findings, I was started on nasal continuous positive airway pressure to assist with my breathing. 

As my medical team continued to evaluate my condition, they anticipated that further assessments would reveal additional findings related to my premature birth and respiratory difficulties.
options: A. Bilateral pleural effusions on lung ultrasound B. Corkscrew-shaped organisms on umbilical cord culture C. Hyaline membranes lining the alveoli on lung biopsy D. Meconium-stained fluid on deep suctioning E. Patent ductus arteriosus on echocardiography

question:
I am a 58-year-old woman who has been experiencing progressively worsening pain in my knees and fingers for the past two years. The pain in my knees becomes particularly bothersome when I walk for longer than 30 minutes. Each morning, I notice stiffness in my fingers and knees that lasts for about 15 minutes. I cannot recall any specific trauma to my joints that might have caused this discomfort.

Two years ago, I was treated with amoxicillin after a tick bite, but since then, I have generally been healthy. My only medications include a multivitamin and occasional acetaminophen to manage the pain. I typically drink 1 to 2 glasses of wine daily. As for my physical measurements, I am 160 cm tall and weigh 79 kg, giving me a BMI of 31.

During my recent examination, my doctor noted mild genu varum in my lower extremities. The range of motion in both knees is limited, and I experience palpable crepitus, as well as pain with complete flexion and extension. Additionally, I have tender nodules on the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints of my index, ring, and little fingers on both hands.
options: A. Gout B. Lyme arthritis C. Rheumathoid arthritis D. Osteoarthritis E. Septic arthritis F. Pseudogout

question:
I am a 78-year-old man who recently visited my primary care physician due to persistent back pain. This pain had been bothering me for some time, but it intensified after I helped my son move heavy furniture last weekend. Since then, the discomfort has become constant and occurs throughout the day.

In addition to the back pain, I have noticed a recent weight loss of about 15 pounds and have been dealing with constipation. During my visit, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, my blood pressure was 137/79 mmHg, my pulse was 90 beats per minute, and my respirations were 15 per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 98% on room air.

The cardiovascular examination revealed a murmur at the right sternal border that radiates to my carotids. The pulmonary exam showed mild crackles in the lower parts of my lungs. My back examination indicated mild tenderness in the lower thoracic and upper lumbar spine, but there were no signs of bruising or external trauma. Lying down or lifting my leg did not worsen the pain. My strength was normal in both my lower and upper extremities, and sensation was intact bilaterally.

Following my consultation, laboratory tests were ordered, and I await their results for further evaluation.
options: A. Muscle strain B. Herniated nucleus pulposus C. Sciatic nerve irritation D. Piriformis muscle inflammation E. Plasma cell dyscrasia

question:
I am a 59-year-old woman who went to the emergency department due to sudden abdominal pain that began this morning. My medical history includes alcoholism, obesity, and peptic ulcer disease. I take medications such as ibuprofen, acetaminophen, and naproxen.

Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was measured at 98°F, and my blood pressure was 117/58 mmHg. My pulse was elevated at 120 beats per minute, while my respirations were stable at 16 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 99% on room air.

During the physical examination, the doctor noted diffuse tenderness in my abdomen, as well as a positive Murphy sign and tenderness in the epigastric region. I was also experiencing vomiting and had a noticeable smell of alcohol. A radiograph was obtained to further assess my condition, and laboratory values were pending at that time.

The medical team was focused on determining the most likely diagnosis based on these observations and my medical history.
options: A. Acute cholecystitis B. Boerhaave syndrome C. Gastritis D. Mallory Weiss syndrome E. Perforated peptic ulcer

question:
I am a 38-year-old woman who visited the emergency department due to a progressive headache, blurry vision, and nausea that had persisted for one day. Four days prior, I was diagnosed with an infection in my right middle ear. When I arrived at the emergency department, I felt lethargic, and my temperature was recorded at 39.1°C (102.3°F). My blood pressure measured 148/95 mm Hg.

During the ophthalmologic examination, the doctor observed bilateral swelling of my optic discs. I also experienced an absent corneal reflex in my right eye, and there was reduced sensation to touch on the upper right side of my face. The medical team conducted serum studies, which indicated increased concentrations of fibrin degradation products. Given these symptoms and findings, I was informed that further evaluation would be necessary to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Cerebral venous thrombosis B. Hypertensive emergency C. Subarachnoid hemorrhage D. Migraine headache E. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension F. Viral meningitis

question:
I am a 50-year-old woman with obesity and a history of hypertension. I arrived at the emergency department after experiencing chest pain for the last 12 hours. The pain was substernal and crushing, radiating into my neck, and I was sweating profusely. I recognized that I had not been compliant with my hypertension medications.

At the clinic, an ECG confirmed that I was experiencing a STEMI, and I was given aspirin. Unfortunately, while being transported by ambulance, there was an accident that delayed my arrival at the hospital. By the time I reached the angiography suite, the cardiologist decided to postpone any intervention due to the late presentation, although my pain had started to improve.

I was admitted to the hospital and remained stable for three nights, with no issues like dyspnea or edema, and my blood pressure was managed effectively. However, on the fourth night, I became quite agitated and soon lost consciousness. My pulse could not be felt, and I noticed that my jugular venous pressure was elevated. When the doctor listened to my heart, the sounds seemed distant.
options: A. Acute aortic dissection B. Acute pericarditis C. Ventricular septal rupture D. Left ventricular free wall rupture E. Papillary muscle rupture F. Pulmonary embolism

question:
I am a 2-year-old girl who recently emigrated from Pakistan, arriving just two weeks ago. I was brought to the emergency department because I experienced weakness in my lower limbs for one day. About a week prior, I had a three-day episode of flu-like symptoms, but those resolved without any treatment. 

I have not yet received any routine childhood vaccinations since my arrival. During the examination, the doctors noted that my deep tendon reflexes were 1+ in my right lower extremity but absent in my left lower extremity. They also conducted a lumbar puncture to analyze my cerebrospinal fluid. The results showed a leukocyte count of 38 cells/mm³, with 68% being lymphocytes. The protein concentration was 49 mg/dL, and the glucose concentration was 60 mg/dL. 

The medical team is working to determine the most likely diagnosis based on my symptoms and test results.
options:
A. Coxsackie meningitis B. Poliomyelitis C. HSV encephalitis D. Botulism E. Tetanus F. Guillain-Barre syndrome
"

question:
I am a 27-year-old man who went to the emergency department because I was experiencing a sensation of fluttering in my chest. I had felt this intermittently in the past, but this time the symptoms were persistent. At the moment, I am studying for exams and have been consuming about 10 cups of coffee a day. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 98°F, and my blood pressure was 115/60 mmHg. My pulse was notably high at 124 beats per minute, while my respirations were normal at 14 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation was measured at 99% while I was breathing room air. 

During the physical examination, the medical staff noted the tachycardia. An electrocardiogram (ECG) was performed to further assess my condition. I was seeking clarity regarding the potential diagnosis related to my symptoms.
options: A. Atrial fibrillation B. Atrial flutter C. Multifocal atrial tachycardia D. Premature atrial contractions E. Supraventricular tachycardia

question:
I am a 32-year-old man who recently visited an urgent care clinic due to experiencing rapid pulsations in my chest, shortness of breath, and lightheadedness for about two hours. I had never encountered similar symptoms before and do not have any chronic health conditions. I consume alcohol socially but do not smoke cigarettes.

Upon arrival at the clinic, my vital signs were taken. My blood pressure was noted to be 100/60 mmHg, and my pulse was measured at 140 beats per minute. The medical team decided to perform an electrocardiogram (ECG) to assess my heart's activity.

After reviewing the ECG results, I was administered adenosine intravenously. Fortunately, this treatment resolved my symptoms. About an hour later, another ECG was conducted to monitor my heart's condition again. 

Although I am unsure what specifically caused my symptoms, I am relieved that the intervention was effective and my condition improved.
options: A. Anemia B. Atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia from accessory conduction pathway C. Premature ventricular complex D. Intense emotional episodes

question: I was involved in a motor vehicle accident, which ultimately led to my death. Following the accident, an autopsy was conducted on my heart. During the examination, the medical team discovered multiple nodules located near the line of closure on the ventricular side of my mitral valve leaflet. A closer inspection revealed that these nodules were made up of immune complexes, mononuclear cells, and thrombi interwoven with fibrin strands. The findings raised questions about the underlying conditions that could have contributed to the formation of these nodules. It was noted that such nodules are typically found in specific patient populations, prompting further consideration of my medical history and any potential pre-existing conditions.
options: A. A 54-year-old male who recently underwent dental surgery B. A 71-year-old male with acute-onset high fever and nail bed hemorrhages C. A 41-year-old female with a facial rash and nonerosive arthritis D. A 28-year-old HIV-positive female intravenous drug user E. A 62-year-old male with Cardiobacterium hominis bacteremia F. A 6-year-old female with subcutaneous nodules and erythema marginatum

question:
I am a 33-year-old man who recently experienced a sudden episode of confusion. My coworkers found me at a local construction site, where I was unresponsive on the ground. I have a history of seizure disorder and schizophrenia, for which I take haloperidol. Additionally, I underwent surgery two months ago to remove an inflamed appendix.

When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 105°F, and my blood pressure was 120/84 mmHg. My pulse was elevated at 150 beats per minute, and my respirations were 19 per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 99% while breathing room air. 

During the physical examination, I was unable to answer questions and appeared confused, with my clothes soaked in sweat. Although I was not making purposeful movements with my limbs, there were no obvious neurological deficits noted.

My condition required prompt medical evaluation to determine the underlying cause of my confusion and other symptoms.
options: A. Exertional heat stroke B. Heat exhaustion C. Malignant hyperthermia D. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome E. Nonexertional heat stroke

question:
I am a 55-year-old woman who recently visited the clinic after experiencing an unusual episode. During this episode, I felt tingling in my fingers and had a strange sensation of smelling sour milk. I did not lose consciousness, feel confused, or experience any incontinence. I do not have a history of head trauma or any exposure to toxic substances.

My medical history includes well-controlled type 2 diabetes, for which I take metformin. When I arrived at the clinic, my vital signs were stable: my temperature was 36.8°C, heart rate was 98 beats per minute, respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was 100/75 mm Hg with an oxygen saturation of 100% on room air.

The physical examination, including a thorough neurologic and cardiac assessment, showed no abnormalities. I underwent various laboratory tests, which returned normal results. A brain MRI revealed no areas of infarction or hemorrhage, and I had a normal ECG. An EEG was pending at the time of my visit.

I am unsure what these episodes may signify and seek further understanding of the situation.
options: A. Simple partial B. Complex partial C. Absence D. Tonic-clonic E. Myoclonic

question:
I am a 66-year-old man who recently underwent a below-knee amputation of my right lower leg due to an acute arterial embolism. This event occurred three weeks ago, and unfortunately, there was not enough time to revascularize my leg. Since the amputation, I have experienced episodic hot, shooting, and tingling pain in the stump of my right leg, which began shortly after the procedure.

I have a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and have been a smoker for the past 30 years, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily. Currently, I take metformin for my diabetes and receive prophylactic subcutaneous heparin to prevent complications. 

During my follow-up examination, my vital signs were stable, with a temperature of 37.1°C, pulse of 78 beats per minute, and blood pressure of 135/88 mm Hg. The examination of my stump revealed slight erythema, but the sutures were clean. The skin over the stump felt warm and well-perfused. Additionally, muscle strength and sensation appeared normal in my remaining extremities and in my left leg. I am now seeking to understand the cause of the pain I have been experiencing since the amputation.
options: A. Phantom limb pain B. Foreign body reaction C. Reinfarction D. Diabetic neuropathy E. Osteomyelitis

question:
I was taken to the emergency department because I had been experiencing severe abdominal pain for the past week. My father explained to the physician that the stomach aches were intermittent, and whenever they occurred, I would cry and pull my knees to my chest, which seemed to help a bit. My parents also mentioned that I had been having mucousy stools, and sometimes there was bright red blood, along with clots. They noted that I had never felt this kind of abdominal pain before.

I was born at 39 weeks gestation through a spontaneous vaginal delivery, and my vaccination schedule is up to date. I am meeting all my developmental milestones. During the examination, the doctors found my vital signs were mostly normal, but I had a slight fever and was mildly tachycardic. I felt quite uncomfortable during the exam. When the doctor examined my abdomen, they found a sausage-shaped mass in my right upper abdomen. The attending physician was looking to determine the most common cause of these symptoms.
options: A. Meckel's diverticulum B. Enlarged mesenteric lymph node C. Gastrointestinal infection D. Henoch-Schonlein purpura E. Idiopathic

question:
This morning, I began experiencing confusion that escalated throughout the day. Initially, I had abdominal pain accompanied by diarrhea and fatigue after eating. These symptoms worsened, and I vomited three times. My husband noticed my confusion increasing and decided to take me to the emergency department.

In the hospital, I learned that my medical history includes morbid obesity, diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidemia, and a sleeve gastrectomy performed a month ago. I've also dealt with depression and previously made multiple suicide attempts. 

When I arrived, my vital signs were taken: my temperature was 98.0°F, blood pressure was 104/54 mmHg, my pulse was 120 beats per minute, my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% on room air. During the physical examination, the staff noted my generalized confusion, which was quite concerning.

I was informed that various laboratory tests would be conducted to help determine the cause of my symptoms. I felt anxious as I waited for answers, hoping for a clear diagnosis and appropriate treatment.
options: A. Dumping syndrome B. Glipizide overdose C. Insulin overdose D. Malnutrition E. Propranolol overdose

question:
I am a 67-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to chest pain. While I was working in my yard, I first felt a "pull" in my chest. After that, I started to feel lightheaded, which prompted me to seek medical attention. I do not have any previous medical history, and I am not currently taking any medications. 

Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was measured at 98.4°F, my blood pressure was recorded at 137/77 mmHg, my pulse was 90 beats per minute, and my respirations were 17 per minute. My oxygen saturation was 98% while I was breathing room air. An ECG was performed to assess my heart's condition, and I was informed that initial laboratory values and troponins would be pending.
options: A. Complete heart block B. First degree heart block C. Mobitz type I D. Mobitz type II E. Non-ST elevation myocardial infarction

question:
I am an 8-year-old boy who recently visited the pediatrician with my mother. I had been experiencing nausea and vomiting, and I noticed that I was urinating less frequently than usual. Five days prior, I received my first dose of chemotherapy for acute lymphoblastic leukemia, a condition I have been diagnosed with.

During my visit, the doctor checked my vital signs. My pulse was at 110 beats per minute, my temperature was 37.0°C (98.6°F), and my blood pressure was measured at 100/70 mm Hg. The doctor also examined my body and found that I had swelling in both of my feet. 

After this assessment, the doctor discussed the next steps and mentioned the importance of certain serum studies and urinalysis findings to better understand my condition and confirm a diagnosis. The entire experience was focused on addressing my symptoms and ensuring I received the appropriate care as I continue my treatment for leukemia.
options: A. Hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, hypocalcemia, and extremely elevated creatine kinase (MM) B. Hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, hypocalcemia, hyperuricemia, urine supernatant pink, and positive for heme C. Hyperuricemia, hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, lactic acidosis, and urate crystals in the urine D. Hyperuricemia, hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, and urinary monoclonal spike E. Hyperuricemia, hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, lactic acidosis, and oxalate crystals

question:
I am a 24-year-old man who was involved in a motor vehicle accident while driving without a seatbelt. I experienced a head-on collision, which resulted in my ejection from the front seat of my car. Paramedics found me outside my vehicle.

Upon arrival at the trauma bay, I was started on intravenous fluids, blood products, and vasopressors to stabilize my condition. Medical staff performed a FAST exam and a chest radiograph to assess my injuries. I had multiple lacerations that required repair.

After the initial resuscitation efforts, my vital signs were recorded: my temperature was 98.4°F, blood pressure was 107/58 mmHg, my pulse was 122 beats per minute, and my respirations were 22 breaths per minute. I was conscious but in significant discomfort, particularly with severe pain in my left shoulder. I also experienced shortness of breath, and I vomited several times during my assessment.

The medical team was evaluating my symptoms and injuries to determine the most likely diagnosis based on my condition at that time.
options: A. Diaphragmatic rupture B. Perforated viscus C. Pulmonary contusion D. Spontaneous pneumothorax E. Tension pneumothorax

question:
I am 67 years old and have a history of diabetes mellitus, COPD, and a previous ST-elevation myocardial infarction. Recently, I missed my dialysis appointment and have not been compliant with my medications. For the past two hours, I have been experiencing shortness of breath. This feeling intensified after I learned that my best friend passed away this morning.

When I sought medical attention, my temperature was 98.7°F, my blood pressure measured 87/48 mmHg, my pulse was 130 beats per minute, and my respirations were 27 per minute. My oxygen saturation was at 92% while I was breathing room air. During a bedside ultrasound, the doctors noted an anechoic rim surrounding my heart and observed poor cardiac squeeze, global hypokinesis, and right ventricular collapse with pleural sliding. 

I understand that my medical history and recent events have contributed to my current condition, and I am aware that my missed dialysis and medication noncompliance may have played a role in the deterioration of my health.
options: A. Cardiac tamponade B. Hyperkalemia C. Myocardial infarction D. Takotsubo cardiomyopathy E. Tension pneumothorax

question:
I am a 57-year-old man who went to the emergency department after experiencing an episode of syncope at home. I suddenly felt weak and had persistent back pain. Following the episode, I vomited forcefully several times. 

My medical history includes diabetes, hypertension, dyslipidemia, and depression. I smoke about 1.5 packs of cigarettes daily and typically consume around 10 alcoholic beverages each night. 

When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 97.5°F. My blood pressure was low at 107/48 mmHg, and my pulse was elevated at 130 beats per minute. My breathing rate was 19 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was normal at 99% on room air. 

The physical examination showed tenderness in my abdomen, and I was positioned uncomfortably. A chest X-ray was performed and appeared normal. Although my urinalysis is still pending, it indicated that my urine was concentrated. 

Given these symptoms and my medical background, I am awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Abdominal aortic aneurysm B. Aortic dissection C. Boerhaave syndrome D. Nephrolithiasis E. Pancreatitis

question:
I am a 27-year-old man, and I recently went to the emergency department after experiencing an episode of palpitations. This was followed by a brief loss of consciousness. I woke up after being unconscious for a few seconds, but I still felt as though my heart was racing. 

I do not have a primary care doctor and have never experienced any health issues before this incident. When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was measured at 98.5°F (36.9°C), my blood pressure was 133/91 mmHg, my pulse was 95 beats per minute, my respirations were 19 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 99% while breathing room air. 

To investigate further, the medical team performed an electrocardiogram (ECG). I am now awaiting the results and hoping to understand what might have caused these symptoms.
options: A. Cardiac muscle hypertrophy B. Electrolyte abnormality C. Fibrofatty replacement of the myocardium D. Ischemia and necrosis of the myocardium E. Sodium channel abnormality

question:
I was brought to the emergency department by my parents because I had been experiencing very fast heartbeats. Prior to this incident, I had been healthy and hadn’t needed to see a doctor in the past two years. During the examination, the medical staff noted that my heart rate was 198 beats per minute. 

The physician conducted a further examination and found a grade III holosystolic murmur over my anterior chest wall. After my heart rate was reduced, an ECG was performed to get a better understanding of my condition. The results showed a short P-R interval along with a slow upstroke of the QRS complex. 

This experience was concerning for both me and my parents, but I was reassured that the medical team was working to determine the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Pulmonic stenosis B. Tricuspid atresia C. Ebstein anomaly D. Tetralogy of Fallot E. Atrial septal defect

question:
I was involved in a motor vehicle collision while driving without a seatbelt. Approximately 15 minutes after the accident, I was brought to the emergency department. Upon arrival, I was unconscious. Medical personnel noted that my breathing rate was 24 breaths per minute, and my systolic blood pressure was palpated at 60 mm Hg, with a pulse of 141 beats per minute that was irregular.

During the examination, doctors observed multiple bruises on my chest and identified two lacerations: a 3-cm one on my abdomen and a 4-cm one on my scalp. They noted that my jugular venous pressure was elevated and heard bilateral crackles in my lungs. My cardiac assessment did not reveal any murmurs, rubs, or gallops, and my abdomen was soft.

They inserted two large bore intravenous catheters and started an infusion of 0.9% saline. A focused assessment with sonography in trauma (FAST) was performed and returned negative results.
