I am seeking to understand what might be causing the tingling and numbness in my hands, especially considering my diabetes and the other health factors I described.
options: A. Hypothyroidism B. Acute intermittent porphyria C. Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis D. Diabetic neuropathy E. Multiple sclerosis

question:
I am a 17-year-old male and recently went to the emergency department due to pain in my left eye. For the past week, the pain has been progressively worsening. I have not noticed any changes in my vision, nor have I experienced difficulty moving my left eye. Additionally, I have not had any recent trauma to the area.

In my lifestyle, I smoke about one pack of cigarettes daily and drink alcohol socially. Over the past month, I have had unprotected sexual encounters with two males and four females. My current medications include loratadine, nasal saline spray, and diphenhydramine.

When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, my blood pressure was 100/55 mmHg, my pulse was 72 beats per minute, and my respirations were 11 per minute. My oxygen saturation was measured at 98% on room air. 

During the physical examination, I was noted to be a healthy young man, and the cardiopulmonary exam was within normal limits. The exam revealed certain findings that were noted on a figure provided by the medical staff. The healthcare team discussed potential diagnoses based on my symptoms and examination results.
options: A. Obstruction of the nasolacrimal duct B. Staphylococcus aureus infection of the inferior rectus C. Sexually transmitted infection D. Thrombosis of a major vessel E. Infection of a hair follicle

question:
I am a 17-year-old rugby player, and I recently experienced an injury during a game. While running, I rolled my ankle, which caused me to limp into the emergency room for evaluation. The medical staff assessed my injury and noted that the mechanism of injury involved both ankle plantar flexion and inversion. 

During the examination, they checked for point tenderness around the medial and lateral malleolus, but there was none present. They performed an anterior drawer test on my ankle, which returned a positive result, indicating some instability. However, the talar tilt test was negative, suggesting that certain ligamentous structures were intact. 

Based on these findings, the medical team concluded that I likely sustained a specific type of ankle injury, although the exact nature of the injury was not detailed in the conversation. Overall, the experience left me concerned about my recovery and the impact this injury might have on my ability to play rugby in the future.
options: A. Anterior talofibular ligament (ATFL) sprain B. Calcaneofibular ligament (CFL) sprain C. Deltoid ligament sprain D. Tibia fracture E. Fibula fracture

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to colicky pain in my lower abdomen and noticeable abdominal distension that had been occurring for the past 12 hours. I have a history of chronic constipation, for which I regularly take lactulose and senna laxatives. When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 37.1°C (98.7°F), my blood pressure was 110/60 mm Hg, and my pulse was 85 beats per minute.

During the physical examination, the doctor observed diffuse abdominal distension and tenderness, and I noticed that my bowel sounds were faint. After these observations, I underwent a plain abdominal radiograph to assess my condition further. The medical team was evaluating the situation to determine the most likely diagnosis related to my symptoms.
options: A. Intussusception B. Infectious colitis C. Bowel adhesions D. Volvulus E. Acute diverticulitis

question:
I am a 16-year-old girl, and I was brought to the physician by my mother because I have not yet had my menstrual period. At birth, I was diagnosed with partial labial fusion and clitoromegaly. My mother mentioned that during her pregnancy with me, she noticed abnormal hair growth on her chin. I have been experiencing severe acne, which has been quite distressing. 

Three years ago, I broke my wrist after a minor injury, and last year, I sustained a spinal compression fracture while lifting a box during a move. Currently, I am taking oral isotretinoin for my acne and an oral contraceptive. In terms of growth, I am at the 97th percentile for height and the 50th percentile for weight. 

During the physical examination, the doctor observed numerous inflamed pustules on my face and upper back. My breast development is at Tanner stage I. I chose not to undergo a pelvic examination. A pelvic ultrasound was performed, which revealed that I have multiple cysts on my ovaries and a normal uterus.
options: A. Polycystic ovary syndrome B. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia C. Müllerian agenesis D. Hyperprolactinemia E. Imperforate hymen F. Turner syndrome G. Pregnancy H. Aromatase deficiency

question:
I am a 72-year-old woman who visited the emergency department four hours after experiencing a sudden onset of a diffuse, dull, throbbing headache. Along with the headache, I noticed blurred vision, nausea, and had one episode of vomiting. My medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus, for which I take hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril, atorvastatin, and metformin. 

I have been a smoker for 30 years, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily, and I drink 1 to 2 glasses of wine each day. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 36.6 °C (97.9 °F), my pulse was 90 beats per minute, my respirations were 14 per minute, and my blood pressure was elevated at 185/110 mm Hg. 

During the examination, the doctor performed a fundoscopic examination, which revealed bilateral blurring of the optic disc margins. The physical and neurologic examinations showed no other abnormalities. Additionally, a complete blood count and serum tests for electrolytes, urea nitrogen, and creatinine were found to be within the reference range. A urinalysis indicated 2+ protein but did not show the presence of white blood cells or red blood cells.
options:
A. Ischemic stroke B. Subarachnoid hemorrhage C. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension D. Migraine headache E. Hypertensive emergency F. Transient ischemic attack G. Giant cell arteritis
"

question:
I am a 24-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to worsening shortness of breath and an intermittent cough that produced blood-tinged sputum over the past 10 days. During this period, I experienced three episodes of blood in my urine. 

I had been diagnosed with latent tuberculosis six years ago after a positive tuberculin skin test and received treatment at that time. I do not take any medications currently. My family history includes my maternal aunt, who has systemic lupus erythematosus. 

Upon examination in the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37°C (98.6°F), my pulse was 92 beats per minute, and my respirations were elevated at 28 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 152/90 mm Hg. The doctor noted diffuse crackles in both lung bases during the examination. 

I underwent several tests, including blood and urine analyses, and a chest X-ray, which showed patchy pulmonary infiltrates in both lungs. Additionally, a renal biopsy revealed linear deposits of IgG along the glomerular basement membrane. These findings were concerning, and I was informed that further evaluation was necessary to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options:
A. Goodpasture syndrome B. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis C. IgA nephropathy D. Granulomatosis with polyangiitis E. Reactivated tuberculosis F. Microscopic polyangiitis G. Lupus nephritis
"

question:
I visited the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain that I had developed 12 hours prior. The pain was constant and I rated it a 7 out of 10. Alongside the pain, I experienced nausea and had vomited twice. In the last four hours, I had two episodes of nonbloody diarrhea, and I have a 12-month history of intermittent constipation.

I do not have any sick contacts or a history of recent travel. My past medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, mild intermittent asthma, and allergic rhinitis. My diet mainly consists of high-fat foods, and I do not smoke; I drink 1 to 2 glasses of wine per week and do not use illicit drugs. My current medications include lisinopril, metformin, an albuterol inhaler, fexofenadine, and psyllium husk fiber. I have no known drug allergies.

During the physical examination, I was lying back in the hospital bed and appeared uncomfortable. My temperature was elevated at 38.4°C (101.1°F). The examination revealed tenderness in the left lower quadrant of my abdomen, but there was no guarding or rebound tenderness. My extremities showed no edema, and I was alert and oriented throughout the assessment.
options: A. Ischemic colitis B. Crohn disease C. Cholecystitis D. Irritable bowel syndrome E. Appendicitis F. Ulcerative colitis G. Diverticulitis

question:
I am a 55-year-old man who recently visited the office for an eye exam. Over the past few weeks, I have experienced some difficulty seeing, although I have not felt any pain associated with my vision changes. I have a history of HIV, which I was diagnosed with about 20 years ago due to my intravenous drug use. I stopped using drugs 10 years ago, but I have not been consistent with my medication regimen.

During my visit, the healthcare provider noted that my last CD4+ count was 42, recorded six months prior. My vital signs were within normal ranges, and I underwent a fundoscopic exam as part of the eye examination. The results showed that I have experienced some loss of both central and peripheral vision. The provider discussed potential diagnoses related to my symptoms and medical history.
options: A. Retinal vein occlusion B. Retinal detachment C. Acute angle closure glaucoma D. CMV retinitis E. HSV retinitis

question:
I am a 45-year-old woman who has been concerned about my inguinal hernia. Two months ago, I went to the emergency department because I noticed a swelling in my left lower abdomen. The doctors at the hospital were able to easily reduce the mass and referred me to the general surgery clinic for an elective surgical repair. Since my condition was not deemed urgent, I was placed on a waiting list for surgery.

Despite this reassurance, I find myself repeatedly visiting the clinic and the emergency department, anxious that my bowels might be trapped and dying. Each time I go, the medical staff reassures me, and any protrusion is quickly reduced. In addition to my hernia concerns, I have a history of abdominal pain and inconsistent bowel habits, which I have discussed with my primary care physician multiple times. However, no specific cause has been identified for these symptoms.

I continue to experience intermittent abdominal discomfort and spend several hours each day worrying about my health and what might be happening to me. I do not have any other significant medical history, but the ongoing anxiety about my condition has been challenging to manage.
options: A. Conversion disorder B. Malingering disorder C. Factitious disorder D. Illness anxiety disorder E. Somatic symptom disorder

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who was involved in a traffic collision. After the accident, I was transported to the emergency room by ambulance. Upon arrival, I was in shock and comatose. The medical team examined me and noted a heart rate of 60 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 70 over 40 mm Hg. Despite their resuscitative efforts, I did not survive.

Following my death, an autopsy was performed, which revealed multiple internal hemorrhages and signs of ischemic damage in my lungs, kidneys, and brain. The examination of my heart showed significant anomalies. The medical staff suggested that acute hypovolemia was likely the cause of the ischemic changes observed in my organs. However, they were also interested in understanding the underlying reason for the gross anomaly found in my heart.
options: A. Aortic valve regurgitation B. Mitral valve stenosis C. Senile calcific aortic stenosis D. Accumulation of amyloid in the myocardium E. Genetic mutation

question:
I am a 45-year-old man who was brought to the emergency room by my wife due to confusion that had developed over the past day. Upon arrival, I was found to have a fever, with an oral temperature of 103.6 degrees Fahrenheit. My vital signs were otherwise stable. During the physical examination, the doctor noted some unusual lesions on my skin that I had never seen before. Additionally, I experienced subtle weakness on the right side of my body, which affected both my upper and lower extremities.

While in the emergency room, I underwent various tests. The healthcare team informed me that my blood counts were concerning, particularly my hemoglobin level, which was significantly low. They mentioned that both my PT/INR and PTT results were normal, which offered some reassurance. I was not aware of any previous health issues that could have led to my current state, and it was alarming to find myself experiencing these symptoms. The medical team was focused on determining the underlying cause of my condition, and I was waiting for further assessment and diagnosis.
options: A. Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura B. Disseminated intravascular coagulation C. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura D. Hemolytic uremic syndrome E. Evan's syndrome

question:
I am a 60-year-old woman who recently went to the emergency department because I had been experiencing progressive shortness of breath and a dry cough for the past week. I noticed that my symptoms worsened with physical activity but improved when I rested. 

Two years ago, I was diagnosed with chronic kidney disease, and I had just started regular dialysis treatment. When I arrived at the emergency department, my pulse rate was measured at 105 beats per minute, my blood pressure was 110 over 70 mm Hg, my respiratory rate was 30 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 37.8°C (100.0°F). 

During the respiratory examination, the doctor noted dullness on percussion, decreased vocal tactile fremitus, and decreased breath sounds over the base of my right lung. The remainder of the physical exam was normal. 

I am uncertain about the exact cause of my symptoms, but I am here seeking help for my condition.
options: A. Primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP) B. Pleural effusion C. Pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) D. Pneumonia E. Acute bronchitis

question:
I was taken to the physician for a follow-up examination after experiencing recurrent asthma attacks. My mother mentioned that I had been having mild abdominal pain for the past two weeks. At the time of the visit, I was using daily inhaled fluticasone and inhaled albuterol as needed for my asthma.

During the examination, the physician noted that I appeared well. My temperature was measured at 37°C, my pulse was 100 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was recorded at 130/85 mm Hg. The doctor listened to my lungs and found them clear, with no signs of murmurs, rubs, or gallops in my heart. 

When it came to my abdomen, the doctor found a smooth, nontender mass on the left side that did not cross the midline. The rest of the examination showed no abnormalities. The physician also reviewed some lab results, which indicated that my complete blood count and serum concentrations of electrolytes, urea nitrogen, and creatinine were all within the reference range. 

Overall, I felt comfortable during the visit, but the physician was concerned about the abdominal mass and the ongoing mild pain.
options:
A. Polycystic kidney disease B. Lymphoma C. Acute leukemia D. Wilms' tumor E. Neuroblastoma F. Renal cell carcinoma G. Ovarian cyst
"

question:
I am a 49-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by ambulance due to sudden-onset chest pain. This pain began while I was having dinner about two hours prior. The discomfort was substernal and radiated into my neck and down my left arm. 

I have a medical history that includes hypercholesterolemia, which I manage with statin therapy, and coronary artery disease. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F). My blood pressure was noted to be 155/90 mm Hg, my pulse was 112 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 25 breaths per minute. 

The medical staff conducted tests, including measuring my troponin I levels, which were elevated. Additionally, they performed a 12-lead ECG to gather more information about my condition. Based on my symptoms and medical history, the healthcare team began assessing the likely cause of my presentation.
options: A. Coronary vasospasm B. Left main coronary artery occlusion C. Left circumflex artery occlusion D. Left anterior descending artery occlusion E. Right main coronary artery occlusion

question:
I am a 51-year-old man who recently found myself in the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain and cramping that had persisted for the past three hours. The pain radiated to my back, and I experienced multiple episodes of vomiting. 

Throughout my life, I have faced challenges with alcohol, which has led to repeated hospitalizations for intoxication and abdominal pain. During this visit, my body temperature was elevated at 103.8°F (39.8°C). My respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute, my pulse was 107 beats per minute, and my blood pressure measured 100/80 mm Hg. 

The pain was so intense that I refused a physical examination, as I found it difficult to tolerate. I understood that the medical staff would conduct blood work to assess my condition. While I was aware of the various tests they would perform, I did not focus on the specific results at that moment. My primary concern was the overwhelming pain and discomfort I was experiencing. I hoped for relief and clarity on my condition as the medical team continued to evaluate my situation.
options: A. Cholecystitis B. Pancreatitis C. Choledocholithiasis D. Duodenal peptic ulcer E. Gallbladder cancer

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who visited the emergency department due to hematuria and hemoptysis that began that morning. Throughout my adult life, I have experienced frequent lung infections, with the most recent one occurring two weeks ago. I have had hematuria on two previous occasions, but the severity I experienced this time was unprecedented. 

In terms of my medical history, it is quite non-significant aside from these issues, and I only take acetaminophen as needed for discomfort. Upon arrival at the emergency department, my blood pressure was recorded at 136/92 mm Hg, my heart rate was 86 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 16 breaths per minute, and my temperature was normal at 37.0°C (98.6°F). 

A chest X-ray revealed a resolving opacity in my right middle lobe, suggesting some recent lung involvement. While I was in the examination room, I unexpectedly developed a spontaneous nosebleed. The medical team conducted initial laboratory tests, which indicated elevated levels of inflammatory markers, but I am not aware of the specific details. Overall, I felt concerned about my symptoms and their implications for my health.
options: A. Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis B. IgA nephropathy C. Goodpasture syndrome D. Minimal change disease E. Granulomatosis with polyangiitis

question:
I am a 10-month-old infant who was brought in by my parents due to concerns about my health. I had been vomiting multiple times over the past couple of hours, and my most recent vomit was green in color. My parents mentioned that I had not passed any stool during this time. 

Upon arrival at the medical facility, I was examined by a healthcare professional. During the examination, I was found to be irritable and crying. The doctor palpated my abdomen and discovered an abdominal mass in the periumbilical region. 

Given these findings, an emergency laparotomy was performed to investigate further. The procedure revealed that a part of my intestine had folded into the section adjacent to it. This condition led to my symptoms and required immediate medical intervention.
options: A. Hirschsprung’s disease B. Meckel’s diverticulum C. Duodenal atresia D. Pyloric stenosis E. Intussusception

question:
I arrived at the emergency department due to severe pain and swelling in the proximal joint of my right hand's third finger. This pain was so intense that it woke me from sleep earlier that morning. I had never experienced anything like this before. 

For the past 25 years, I have been smoking about a pack of cigarettes daily and consuming alcohol heavily on weekends. Last night, I attended a party where I drank 3 to 4 beers and was unable to drive home afterward. I do not have any significant past medical history, but my family health history includes my mother, who passed away from pancreatic cancer at 55, and my father, who died from a stroke two years ago.

When I was examined, my temperature was noted at 37.7°C, with a blood pressure of 130/70 mm Hg and a pulse rate of 104 beats per minute. I was in moderate distress from the pain. The examination revealed that the proximal interphalangeal joint of my third finger was very tender, swollen, warm, and slightly red. Due to the extreme tenderness, the range of motion could not be assessed. 

A synovial fluid aspiration was performed on the joint, and the findings included cloudy, dense yellow fluid with a high white blood cell count and negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals.
options: A. Pseudogout B. Chronic gout C. Septic arthritis D. Acute gout E. Reactive arthritis

question:
I am a 22-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to pain and swelling in my left knee. This occurred one day after I injured it while playing soccer. While sprinting on the field, I slipped while trying to kick the ball and landed on the front of my knee.

In my medical history, I had an appendectomy when I was 16 years old. Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were within normal limits. The examination revealed that my left knee was swollen and tender, and I experienced limited range of motion due to pain. The tibial tuberosity was also tender to touch. When force was applied to the proximal tibia after flexing my knee, it was noted that the left tibia was displaced posteriorly. The rest of the examination showed no other abnormalities.

An x-ray of my left knee joint was performed, which indicated an avulsion fracture of the tibial condyle. The medical team is now considering the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Anterior cruciate ligament injury B. Lateral meniscus injury C. Posterior cruciate ligament injury D. Lateral collateral ligament injury E. Medial meniscus injury F. Medial collateral ligament injury

question:
I am a 78-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by my son after I recently fell. I complained of pain in my ribs and had been feeling less responsive than usual. Additionally, I had been experiencing diarrhea. I live alone in my apartment and have a history of hypertension and dementia. My current medications include lisinopril for my blood pressure, as well as memantine and donepezil for my cognitive condition.

Upon arrival at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, my blood pressure was 120/75 mmHg, my pulse was 95 beats per minute, my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 97% on room air. During the physical examination, I felt uncomfortable. I was able to respond to questions, but my answers were often inappropriate, and I struggled to find the right words. 

The neurological exam revealed an unsteady gait and nystagmus. The dermatological examination showed scattered bruises, and my hair appeared fragile and coiled. The cardiac exam indicated a systolic murmur radiating to my carotids, and a pulmonary exam detected mild crackles in my lungs. I was started on IV fluids, and further radiography was ordered to assess my condition.
options: A. Elder abuse B. Alcohol abuse C. Celiac disease D. Poor dietary intake E. Normal aging

question:
I am a 73-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department due to a fever and a productive cough that had persisted for two days. Over the past two weeks, I experienced increasing fatigue and shortness of breath, during which I also lost about 3 kilograms (6.6 pounds). A year ago, I underwent chemotherapy for myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) and have since been receiving supportive treatment and regular blood transfusions. I do not smoke or consume alcohol.

Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were recorded: I had a temperature of 38.5℃ (101.3℉), a pulse of 93 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute, and a blood pressure reading of 110/65 mm Hg. The examination revealed petechiae on my lower extremities and purpura on my trunk and limbs. Additionally, several enlarged lymph nodes were noted in both my axillary and cervical regions. When my lungs were auscultated, crackles were detected in the left lower lobe.

A physical examination of my heart and abdomen showed no abnormalities. The medical team conducted laboratory studies, although I do not have the results to discuss. Based on the clinical findings, the healthcare providers evaluated my condition further.
options: A. Acute myeloid leukemia B. Burkitt lymphoma C. Disseminated intravascular coagulation D. Non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema E. Small cell lung cancer

question:
I am a 45-year-old man who recently visited an urgent care clinic due to a concerning symptom. This morning, I coughed up blood for the first time, despite having a persistent cough for the past three weeks. I also noticed that my voice has been hoarse for the last few months, which I initially attributed to the cough.

I have a history of smoking a pack of cigarettes a day since I was 20, and I drink wine every night before bed. I have no significant past medical history or family history that I am aware of. 

During my visit, the healthcare provider noted my vital signs, which included a heart rate of 78 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 14 breaths per minute, a temperature of 36.5°C (97.8°F), and a blood pressure of 140/88 mm Hg. They performed an indirect laryngoscopy, during which they found a rough vegetating lesion on the free border of my right vocal cord. 

I left the clinic with a lot of questions about what could be causing these symptoms and what the next steps would be for diagnosis and treatment.
options: A. Acute laryngitis B. Leukoplakia C. Polypoid corditis D. Vocal cord nodule E. Laryngeal carcinoma

question:
I recently visited the physician for a well-child examination, as I had some concerns about my weight. At 17 years old, I often find myself at buffet restaurants, but I usually feel guilty about my eating choices afterward. I also have a history of burning my extremities with cigarettes, which I know is not a healthy behavior. 

My last menstrual period occurred three weeks ago. I am currently in high school and play field hockey on the school team, which keeps me active. During the examination, the doctor noted that I am in the 25th percentile for height, the 12th percentile for weight, and the 17th percentile for BMI. 

During the physical exam, the doctor observed bilateral enlargement of my parotid glands. They also examined my mouth and found signs of perimolysis. Fortunately, the rest of the examination did not reveal any other abnormalities. After discussing my symptoms and concerns, the physician considered my situation and indicated that there are potential diagnoses that could explain my symptoms.
options:
A. Major depressive disorder B. Kleine-Levin syndrome C. Binge eating disorder D. Bulimia nervosa E. Obsessive compulsive disorder F. Borderline personality disorder G. Body dysmorphic disorder H. Anorexia nervosa
"

question:
I am 57 years old and recently experienced two days of severe, generalized abdominal pain that worsened after meals. Along with the pain, I felt nauseated and noticed that I had occasional diarrhea, which was mixed with blood. My medical history is mostly unremarkable, aside from having essential hypertension. 

During this time, my vital signs were taken: my temperature was 36.9°C (98.4°F), my blood pressure was measured at 145/92 mm Hg, and my pulse was irregular, at 105 beats per minute. When examined physically, the doctor noted mild tenderness around my belly button. The combination of these symptoms raised concerns, and I was informed that further evaluation was necessary to determine the cause of my condition.
options: A. Acute pancreatitis B. Crohn's disease C. Acute mesenteric ischemia D. Diverticular disease E. Gastroenteritis

question:
I am a 57-year-old woman who recently visited the hospital due to persistent abdominal pain that has lasted for the past four months. Along with this pain, I have been experiencing early satiety, which has worsened lately. The situation escalated when I had several episodes of vomiting blood, prompting me to seek help at the emergency department.

It’s been about eight years since my last menstrual period, and I am still sexually active with my husband. Recently, I have encountered pain during intercourse and noticed some spotting afterward. In addition to these issues, I've been feeling nauseous and have lost weight, which I believe is related to my abdominal discomfort.

During my visit, my vital signs were recorded: my blood pressure was 125/84 mm Hg, my respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute, and my heart rate was 76 beats per minute. The healthcare team considered my symptoms and medical history to determine the most likely diagnosis and the necessary next steps for my care.
options: A. PAS-positive macrophages B. Signet ring cells C. Ectopic thyroid tissue D. Hyperplasia of gastric mucosa E. Intestinal metaplasia in the stomach

question:
I am a 28-year-old man who has been experiencing chronic back pain for the past year. This pain began after I started working at a logistics company, and I do not recall any specific injury that could have caused it. I have seen two other physicians about my back pain, but neither was able to provide a diagnosis. 

In addition to the back pain, I began to notice abdominal bloating and a feeling of constipation that started about three weeks ago. After researching my symptoms online, I became concerned that these issues might be related to pancreatic cancer, prompting me to request a CT scan of my abdomen for reassurance. 

I also have a history of episodic chest pain, which I discussed with another healthcare provider, but tests at that time did not indicate any problems. I do not smoke or drink alcohol, but I do feel significant pressure from my superiors at work due to frequent performance evaluations. For my overall health, I take daily multivitamins and glucosamine to help prevent arthritis. 

During my examination, my vital signs were normal, and my abdomen was soft, non-tender, and non-distended. There was mild tenderness in my paraspinal muscles, but the rest of the examination, including a neurological assessment, showed no abnormalities. An x-ray of my spine also revealed no issues.
options: A. Adjustment disorder B. Malignant neoplasm C. Illness anxiety disorder D. Atypical depression E. Irritable bowel syndrome F. Conversion disorder G. Somatic symptom disorder H. Acute stress disorder

question:
I am a 52-year-old man who recently visited my primary care physician due to persistent fatigue. Over the past few weeks, I noticed that I felt unusually tired and thought I appeared more pale than usual. During my appointment, my physician conducted a thorough evaluation and ordered a complete blood count to better understand my symptoms.

The results indicated that my hemoglobin level was low, and I had a significantly reduced white blood cell and platelet count. Given these findings, my physician referred me for a bone marrow biopsy to investigate further. I underwent the biopsy procedure, which was necessary to determine the underlying cause of my symptoms and blood count abnormalities. I am currently awaiting the results to understand my diagnosis and the next steps in my care.
options: A. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia B. Acute myelogenous leukemia C. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia D. Chronic myelogenous leukemia E. Multiple myeloma

question:
I am a 44-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by my daughter. For the past week, I have been experiencing weakness in my right leg, which has made my gait unsteady and resulted in multiple falls. Over the last six months, I have noticed an increase in forgetfulness, and there have been instances where I lost my way even on familiar routes. I have found it difficult to operate simple kitchen appliances like the dishwasher and coffee maker.

Recently, I have felt increasingly paranoid, agitated, and restless. I have a medical history that includes HIV, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. It has been over two years since my last visit to a physician, and I have not been compliant with my medications.

Upon examination in the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37.2°C (99.0°F), with a blood pressure of 152/68 mm Hg and a pulse of 98 beats per minute. I felt somnolent and slightly confused, being oriented to my identity but not to my location or time. The examination revealed mild lymphadenopathy in my cervical, axillary, and inguinal areas, along with weakness in my right lower extremity. I was advised that further evaluations, including an MRI of my brain, would be necessary to determine the underlying cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Cerebral toxoplasmosis B. Cryptococcal meningoencephalitis C. HIV encephalopathy D. Primary CNS lymphoma E. Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy

question:
I am a 28-year-old resident in general surgery, and for the past two months, I have been feeling increasingly burned out. My workload has been heavy, with extremely long hours under stressful conditions. As a result, I have noticed that I am often irritable, edgy, and unfocused. I also find myself being forgetful, which has raised my anxiety about my performance at work. This anxiety has been significant enough to interfere with my sleep, even during my time off.

To address these issues, I was referred for counseling and prescribed some mild sleep aids to help me manage my sleep difficulties. When I returned for a follow-up a few months later, I noted a significant improvement in my condition. This improvement coincided with better staffing at the hospital and a more manageable workload, which has helped alleviate some of the stress I was experiencing. Overall, I feel much better now and am more capable of handling my responsibilities.
options: A. Adjustment disorder B. Generalized anxiety disorder C. Anxiety disorder D. Panic disorder E. Normal human behavior

question:
I am an 8-year-old boy who was brought to the emergency department by my parents due to sudden abdominal pain that started about an hour ago. Earlier that morning, I had an episode of dark urine. Just three days prior, I was diagnosed with a urinary tract infection and was treated with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole.

My family and I emigrated from Liberia to the U.S. three years ago, and I don't have a personal history of serious illness. My immunizations are current. When my parents took me to the hospital, the doctors checked my vital signs, which were normal. During the examination, they found that my abdomen was tender all over, and they noticed that the whites of my eyes had a yellowish tint. They also felt my spleen, which was slightly enlarged.

I understand that they did some tests, but I am not aware of the specific results. I was feeling pretty uncomfortable, and my parents were worried about my condition. The doctors seemed to be trying to figure out the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Production of hemoglobin S B. Defective UMP synthase C. Cold agglutinins D. Absent hemoglobin beta chain E. Lead poisoning F. Deficient glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase G. Defective RBC membrane proteins H. Absent UDP-glucuronosyltransferase

question:
I arrived at the emergency room at the age of 42, experiencing noticeable facial droop. I first became aware of this issue that morning while preparing for work; my smile appeared asymmetric, and I found it difficult to fully close my left eye. Additionally, I had been dealing with foul-smelling drainage from my left ear for about a month. 

My medical history includes recurrent ear infections during childhood. Upon examination, my temperature was recorded at 99.0°F, and my vital signs showed a blood pressure of 110/65 mmHg, a pulse of 72 beats per minute, and respirations at 14 per minute. I maintained an oxygen saturation of 99% on room air.

During the physical exam, the doctor noted that my mouth was drooping downward on the left side, and I was unable to fully close my left eye. There was also drainage from my left ear, which was further examined with an otoscope. An audiometric evaluation revealed that I had conductive hearing loss in the left ear. The medical team began to assess the situation to determine the most likely explanation for these findings.
options: A. Acute otitis externa B. Cholesteatoma C. Foreign body D. Schwannoma E. Tympanosclerosis

question:
I am a 32-year-old man and recently experienced severe breathlessness that lasted for several hours, prompting me to go to the emergency room. For the past few years, I have been treated for asthma by multiple physicians, but my symptoms have continued to worsen. I have never smoked, nor have I been exposed to cigarette smoke.

Family history is significant; my father passed away at the age of 40 due to chronic obstructive pulmonary disorder, and my uncle, who was my father’s brother, also died from a similar condition. 

Upon arrival at the emergency room, my respiratory rate was measured at 19 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 37.0°C (98.6°F). During the physical examination, it was noted that my exhalation was significantly longer than my inhalation, with an expiratory time exceeding six seconds. The examination also revealed the presence of clubbing and bilateral crackles during chest auscultation. Additionally, I was found to have mild hepatomegaly. 

These symptoms and findings have raised concerns about my respiratory health and the progression of my condition.
options: A. Pulmonary edema B. Lung cancer C. α1-antitrypsin-deficiency D. Asthma E. Pneumonia

question:
I am a 61-year-old woman with diabetes, and I was brought to the emergency department after experiencing multiple bouts of abdominal pain over the past 24 hours. The pain was dull and aching, radiating to my back, and it worsened after meals. I also felt nauseous and occasionally vomited. This was not the first time I had these symptoms; I had been hospitalized several times in the past for similar issues.

During my assessment in the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37° C (98.6° F), my respiratory rate was 16 breaths per minute, my pulse was 77 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 120/89 mm Hg. The examination revealed dark hyperpigmentation of the skin in my axillary area. 

I was aware that my condition had been monitored previously, and I had a blood test report from last month that indicated my glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c) was 9.1%, and my triglyceride levels were notably high at 675 mg/dL. My cholesterol levels were also elevated, and my kidney function tests showed slightly increased serum creatinine. Given my symptoms and medical history, I understood that these factors would be important for my diagnosis.
options: A. Cholecystitis B. Choledocholithiasis C. Pancreatitis D. Duodenal peptic ulcer E. Gallbladder cancer

question:
I am a 5-year-old boy who recently visited the emergency room due to rapid swelling in my right knee after I fell while playing. My mother mentioned that I have always bruised easily, which has been a consistent part of my life. There is also a family history of bleeding issues; my uncle passed away from blood loss following a benign surgical procedure.

During the physical examination, the doctor noted multiple bruises on my arms, legs, and abdomen, each showing different stages of healing. My right knee was swollen, red, and tender to the touch. The doctor performed a procedure called arthrocentesis, which involved drawing fluid from my knee, and the fluid was bloody. They observed about 1,000 white blood cells in the aspirate. 

The medical team conducted further tests. I learned that my bleeding time was 4 minutes, which is within the normal range, but my activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) was 67 seconds, significantly longer than the normal range of 30 to 40 seconds. Given these observations and my symptoms, the doctors are considering a medical condition that may be causing the swelling in my knee.
options: A. Child abuse B. Type 1 von Willebrand's (vW) disease C. Septic arthritis D. Vitamin C deficiency E. Hemophilia A

question:
I am a 65-year-old woman who recently sought medical attention due to persistent pain in my right shoulder that has lasted for two months. The pain is localized to the top of my shoulder and intensifies with movement. I experience stiffness in my right shoulder, particularly in the morning, which typically lasts about 20 minutes. 

This discomfort has significantly impacted my daily activities; I can no longer brush my hair and have stopped attending my regular tennis lessons. I do not recall any incidents of falling or trauma that could have caused this issue. 

During the examination, I noticed that when my right arm is passively lifted in an arc, I feel pain between 60 and 120 degrees of abduction. Additionally, when asked to slowly lower my right arm from a position of 90 degrees of abduction, I found it difficult to hold my arm up, and it dropped to my side. 

The physician assessed my passive range of motion, which appeared normal. To further evaluate my condition, an injection of 5 mL of 1% lidocaine was administered into the right subacromial space; however, this did not relieve my pain or improve the active range of motion in my right arm.
options:
A. Cervical radiculopathy B. Rotator cuff tear C. Calcific tendinitis D. Subacromial bursitis E. Polymyalgia rheumatica F. Biceps tendinitis G. Rotator cuff tendinitis H. Frozen shoulder
"

question:
I am a 67-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to a sudden change in my vision. Over the past 24 hours, I noticed decreased vision and black spots in front of my left eye. It felt as though a curtain was hanging over that eye, and I experienced intermittent flashes of light. Notably, I did not have any pain or double vision.

Two weeks ago, I underwent cataract surgery on my left eye. I have a medical history that includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. My sister has open-angle glaucoma, which adds some concern to my condition. At the time of my visit, I was taking metformin, linagliptin, ramipril, and hydrochlorothiazide, and my vital signs were within normal limits.

During the examination, the doctor assessed my visual acuity; I was able to see 20/25 with my right eye, but I could only count fingers at a distance of 3 feet with my left eye. My pupils were equal and reactive, and the corneal reflex was present. The anterior chamber showed no abnormalities. However, the confrontation test revealed nasal and inferior defects in my left eye. After this assessment, I was awaiting dilation for a fundus examination to determine the next steps.
options: A. Degenerative retinoschisis B. Retinal detachment C. Acute angle-closure glaucoma D. Endophthalmitis E. Wet age-related macular degeneration F. Hemorrhagic choroidal detachment

question:
I am a 16-year-old boy who was brought to the emergency department by my parents after I collapsed at home. Earlier that day, I had an uneventful dental procedure where several teeth were extracted. After the procedure, I was resting at home when I suddenly became drowsy and then lost consciousness. My parents were unable to rouse me, which prompted them to seek emergency medical help.

Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was recorded at 37.0° C (98.6° F), my respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute, my pulse was 67 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was measured at 122/98 mm Hg. Despite making a good effort to breathe, I had an oxygen saturation of only 85% in room air and appeared deeply cyanosed. The medical team examined my lungs and found them to be clear bilaterally.

An endotracheal tube was inserted to assist my ventilation, but my condition did not improve. The doctors reviewed my dental records, noting that a local anesthetic called pilocarpine was administered during the procedure. They began investigating the most likely cause of my condition.
options: A. Cyanide poisoning B. Methemoglobinemia C. Anaphylactic reaction D. Sulfhemoglobinemia E. Carbon monoxide poisoning

question:
I am a 32-year-old man who started experiencing increasing lethargy over the past two months. During this time, I also found myself getting frequent upper respiratory tract infections and noticed that I was bruising easily. My past medical history has been unremarkable, and I have a smoking history of 14 pack-years, though I only drink alcohol socially. There is no significant family history of health issues.

When I visited the doctor, my vital signs showed a temperature of 36.8°C (98.2°F), blood pressure of 132/91 mm Hg, and a pulse rate of 95 beats per minute. The physical examination revealed conjunctival pallor and scattered bruises on my lower extremities. 

Following this, a series of laboratory tests were conducted. I learned that my hemoglobin level was low, and my leukocyte and platelet counts were also below normal. Additionally, my reticulocyte count was significantly low. To investigate further, a bone marrow biopsy was performed, which revealed that my bone marrow was hypocellular, but there was no abnormal cell population present.

Given these findings, I am seeking to understand the most likely diagnosis related to my symptoms and test results.
options: A. Aplastic anemia B. Myelodysplastic syndrome C. Infectious mononucleosis D. Acute lymphocytic leukemia E. Drug-induced immune pancytopenia

question:
I am a 48-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department after being found in a stuporous state outside my apartment on a cold night. I had a small cut on my forehead. After a non-contrast head CT was performed, the results were normal, and I was monitored in the ED.

Twelve hours later, I experienced a distressing episode where I yelled for help, believing that the wallpaper was threatening my family. At that time, I also had a headache. I have been drinking alcohol regularly for about ten years, and prior to my admission, I consumed a pint of vodka. I occasionally smoke marijuana and use cocaine.

While my vital signs were within normal limits, I appeared markedly distressed and was sweating significantly. During the mental status examination, I was alert and oriented, but I had a fine tremor in my right hand. The rest of the neurological exam showed no abnormalities. A urine toxicology screening was pending at that time.
options: A. Alcoholic hallucinosis B. Phencyclidine intoxication C. Cocaine intoxication D. Wernicke's encephalopathy E. Delirium tremens F. Brief psychotic disorder

question:
I am a 20-year-old college student, and I found myself in the emergency room at 4 AM. For the past two hours, I had been experiencing abdominal cramps, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea. The symptoms started about an hour after I heated and ate some food I had left over from earlier in the day. I had been studying for exams the night before, and I became hungry, which led me to eat that food. 

Upon arrival at the hospital, I was informed that my temperature was normal, but my pulse was elevated at 106 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was low at 90 over 78. The medical team conducted a physical examination and noted signs of dehydration, but other aspects of the exam were within normal limits. 

Throughout the experience, I remained focused on the symptoms I was facing, and I was eager to understand what was causing them. It was a concerning situation, given the sudden onset of my symptoms after eating.
options: A. Cryptosporidiosis B. C. difficile colitis C. Bacillus cereus infection D. Norovirus infection E. Rotavirus infection

question:
I am a 72-year-old man with a history of chronic kidney disease. Recently, I have been experiencing recurrent chest pain, which occurs during physical activity. Initially, I would feel this pain when mowing my lawn, but it has progressed to happening even when I walk short distances, such as to get my mail. I notice that the pain resolves on its own when I sit down and rest.

During my visit to my primary care physician, my vital signs were recorded. My temperature was 98.2°F, blood pressure measured at 157/98 mm Hg, my pulse was 80 beats per minute, and my respirations were 15 per minute. I had an oxygen saturation of 98% while breathing room air. The physical examination indicated that I am an obese man, yet I was not in any distress at that time.

An initial electrocardiogram (ECG) was performed, and it showed no changes from a previous ECG I had taken. Furthermore, my first troponin level was recorded at 0.06 ng/mL, which was also unchanged from earlier tests. Given my symptoms and medical history, I am seeking to understand the most likely diagnosis for my condition.
options: A. NSTEMI B. Stable angina C. STEMI D. Unstable angina E. Variant angina

question:
I am a 32-year-old man who visited the emergency department due to worsening shortness of breath and a productive cough that had persisted for three days. Three weeks ago, I experienced trauma to my right hemithorax during a fight. Following that incident, I had significant pain and mild shortness of breath but did not seek medical attention at the time.

I do not smoke or consume alcohol, and I work as a construction worker. Upon my arrival at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 38.4°C (101.1°F), my pulse was 95 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 18 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 120/75 mm Hg, and my oxygen saturation on room air was 96%.

During the pulmonary examination, the physician noted decreased breath sounds over my right lower lung fields. To further assess my condition, a CT scan of my chest was performed, revealing fractures of my right 7th and 8th ribs, along with right pleural splitting and thickening, as well as a dense fluid collection in the pleural space.
options: A. Viral pleurisy B. Lung abscess C. Hemothorax D. Chylothorax E. Pleural empyema F. Mesothelioma

question:
I am a 48-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department with my wife due to experiencing progressive fatigue, shortness of breath with minimal exertion, and a persistent cough that has worsened at night over the past two months. I have a history of heavy alcohol consumption and occasionally smoke cigarettes. 

During my visit, I learned that my mother has heart disease, which required surgery two years ago for a device implantation in her heart. In the emergency department, my vital signs were recorded, showing a blood pressure of 100/80 mm Hg, a temperature of 36.3°C, and a regular pulse of 65 beats per minute. 

The physical examination revealed that I looked tired, with noticeable icteric sclera. The healthcare provider noted distended neck veins, a mildly distended abdomen, and a palpable, firm liver, along with a slightly enlarged spleen. I also had swelling in both ankles, and they detected S3 heart sounds and crackles at the bases of my lungs. 

A chest X-ray indicated an enlarged cardiac silhouette. Based on the findings, further tests such as liver function tests and an ECG were performed. The staff discussed the likelihood of needing an echocardiogram to assess my heart function.
options: A. Left ventricular hypertrophy with delayed relaxation and normal stroke volume B. Left ventricular dilatation in a spherical pattern with poor systolic function C. Speckled appearance of myocardium D. Apical ballooning of the left ventricle

question:
I am a 36-year-old woman, gravida 4, para 3, and at 35 weeks' gestation when I experienced a sudden episode of painless, bright red vaginal bleeding that lasted for about an hour. I had not received any prenatal care up to that point. My previous pregnancies included a vaginal delivery for my first two children, while my third child was delivered via a lower segment transverse cesarean section due to a preterm breech presentation.

When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My pulse was measured at 100 beats per minute, my respirations were at 15 per minute, and my blood pressure was recorded at 105 over 70 mm Hg. During the examination, the medical team found my abdomen to be soft and nontender, with no contractions detected. There was blood noted on my vulva, the introitus, and on the medial aspect of both thighs.

The fetal presentation was cephalic, and the fetal heart rate was recorded at 140 beats per minute. After about an hour, I noticed that the bleeding had stopped. The medical staff continued to monitor my condition closely.
options: A. Uterine atony B. Abruptio placentae C. Ruptured vasa previa D. Latent phase of labor E. Placenta previa F. Placenta accreta G. Uterine rupture

question:
I am a 58-year-old man who recently experienced severe pain in my right leg, which began suddenly about three hours ago while I was watching a movie. Along with the pain, I noticed tingling and weakness in the same leg. My medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. I have also been a smoker for the past 35 years, averaging 20 to 30 cigarettes a day.

Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were recorded. My blood pressure was noted to be 149/85 mm Hg, and my temperature was 36.9°C (98.4°F). The medical staff observed that my pulse was irregular at a rate of 96 beats per minute. During the physical examination, they found that the pulses in my right popliteal and posterior tibial areas were absent. Additionally, my right leg appeared pale and felt cold to the touch.

These observations led the medical team to consider my symptoms and history carefully. I am awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely diagnosis for my condition.
options: A. Leriche syndrome B. Buerger's disease C. Acute limb ischemia D. CREST syndrome E. Deep vein thrombosis

question:
I was involved in a high-speed motor vehicle collision while I was a restrained passenger. Approximately 20 minutes after the crash, I was brought to the emergency department. Upon arrival, I felt lethargic and struggled to communicate clearly. I had severe lacerations on my face and experienced respiratory distress. My heart rate was elevated at 130 beats per minute, and I was breathing rapidly at 29 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was low, measuring 90 over 58, and my oxygen saturation was only 70% while on room air. 

During the examination, the medical staff noted multiple facial lacerations. They found dullness to percussion and decreased breath sounds on my left lung base. My abdominal area was tender, but there was no guarding or rebound tenderness observed. My bowel sounds were normal, and no other abnormalities were noted during the examination. 

An X-ray of my chest revealed a fractured second rib on the left side, depression of the left mainstem bronchus, and a deviation of the nasogastric tube to the right. There was also a widened mediastinum. Overall, my condition was serious, and the medical team was focused on determining the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Flail chest B. Diaphragmatic rupture C. Pulmonary contusion D. Traumatic bronchial rupture E. Thoracic aortic rupture F. Cardiac tamponade G. Tension pneumothorax

question:
I am a 28-year-old primigravid woman who was brought to the emergency department after experiencing severe abdominal pain for three hours. I had not received any prenatal care prior to this visit. Upon arrival, I noticed I was having contractions, five in ten minutes, each lasting between 70 and 90 seconds. A pelvic examination revealed a closed cervix, and my uterus was consistent in size with a 38-week gestation. 

An ultrasound was conducted, showing that I had a single live intrauterine fetus in a breech presentation, estimated to be around 37 weeks gestation. The amniotic fluid index measured 26, and the fetal heart rate was recorded at 92 beats per minute. There was no evidence of placenta detachment. Due to the nonreassuring fetal heart rate, I was scheduled for an emergency lower segment transverse cesarean section.

After the procedure, my infant was delivered, and the APGAR score was noted to be 8 at one minute. However, soon after, the doctor observed cyanosis of the lips and oral mucosa, which did not improve even when the infant cried. The infant began foaming at the mouth and drooling, accompanied by an intractable cough.
options:
A. Esophageal atresia B. Choanal atresia C. Esophageal stricture D. Achalasia E. Pulmonary hypoplasia F. Defective swallowing reflex G. Normal post C-section status
"

question:
I am a 28-year-old man who recently sought a referral to a dermatologist due to an issue I have been experiencing for the past two months. During this time, I noticed multiple smooth, circular patches of complete hair loss on my scalp. These patches have been increasingly prominent, and I have also felt associated itching and a burning sensation in the affected areas. 

I initially tried some over-the-counter products based on recommendations from my hair stylist, but unfortunately, I did not see any improvement. It's important to note that I do not intentionally pull my hair out. 

When I visited the dermatologist, a physical examination was conducted, revealing no signs of inflammation or redness in the scalp. Additionally, a Wood’s lamp examination showed no fluorescence, which was reassuring. To further investigate the situation, a punch biopsy was performed, which indicated a peribulbar lymphocytic inflammatory infiltrate surrounding the hair follicles, resembling what was described to me as a "swarm of bees." This information was shared with me, and I am now awaiting further guidance on the most likely diagnosis and appropriate treatment options.
options: A. Tinea capitis B. Telogen effluvium C. Lichen planopilaris D. Androgenic alopecia E. Alopecia areata

question:
I am a 4-year-old girl who recently experienced progressive intermittent pain and swelling in both of my knees, as well as my right ankle and wrist, lasting for about three months. To manage the discomfort, I have been taking acetaminophen and using ice packs, which have helped relieve my symptoms. In the mornings, my affected joints feel "stuck" and are difficult to move, but after a few minutes, I can move them freely again. 

Additionally, I have had occasional mild eye pain that resolves on its own. Five months ago, I was diagnosed with an upper respiratory tract infection, which resolved without any treatment. When my doctor examined me, my vital signs were within normal limits. The examination revealed that the joints affected were swollen, red, and tender to touch. 

During a slit-lamp examination, my doctor noted signs of anterior chamber flare and iris inflammation in both eyes. Overall, my recent health has raised some concerns, and further evaluation is needed to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Psoriatic juvenile arthritis B. Postinfectious arthritis C. Seronegative polyarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis D. Acute lymphocytic leukemia E. Enthesitis-related arthritis F. Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis G. Oligoarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis

question:
In July, I was taken to the emergency department after experiencing a fever for five days. I felt very lethargic and had noticed bloody urine over the last 48 hours. I did not have any nausea, vomiting, or abdominal pain. My medical history is clear; I have no serious illnesses and do not take any medications. I haven’t traveled outside my city in several years.

Upon arrival at the hospital, I appeared quite ill. My temperature was recorded at 40.8℃ (105.4℉), my pulse was 108 beats per minute, and my respiration rate was 20 breaths per minute. My blood pressure measured at 105/50 mm Hg. During the abdominal examination, the doctors noted hepatosplenomegaly, but there was no lymphadenopathy. I also had petechiae on my lower extremities.

Despite the medical team's efforts, I felt weak and confused about the sudden changes in my health. This experience was alarming, and I hoped for a quick diagnosis and treatment.
options: A. Babesiosis B. Lyme disease C. Malaria D. Plague E. Leishmaniasis

question:
I am a 5-year-old African American boy who was recently diagnosed with a urinary tract infection by my primary care physician. My mother took me to the emergency department today because I started experiencing abdominal pain and noticed that I was having shortness of breath. 

When we arrived, my mother explained to the medical staff about my recent diagnosis and the medications I had been prescribed a few days ago. During the examination, the doctors checked my vital signs, which were normal, but they observed that I had mild jaundice and mentioned that I seemed short of breath. My mother also shared that my uncle had a similar episode when he was treated for malaria, which seemed relevant to my condition.

I underwent further evaluation, and the doctors noted my hemoglobin levels were low. They conducted various tests to understand what was happening to me. I felt concerned about my symptoms, and my mother stayed close to provide comfort and support as the medical team worked to determine the cause of my discomfort.
options: A. Iron deficiency anemia B. Autoimmune hemolytic anemia C. Sickle cell anemia D. Thalassemia E. G6PD deficiency

question:
I am a 65-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to blurry vision that had persisted for the past 10 hours. Alongside this, I experienced urinary urgency and discomfort while urinating for the last four days. Since yesterday, I began to feel increasingly weak and nauseous. I have a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and arterial hypertension. About a year ago, I was treated for an eye infection.

In terms of my alcohol consumption, I typically drink 2 to 3 glasses of wine each week. My current medications include captopril, metoprolol, metformin, and insulin. Upon examination, my temperature was recorded at 37.5°C, my pulse was 107 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was noted to be low at 95/70 mm Hg. The examination revealed decreased visual acuity in both of my eyes, but my pupils were equal and reactive to light. The corneal reflexes were brisk, and I noticed that the mucous membranes of my mouth were dry. They found my abdomen to be soft and not distended, and there were no abnormalities detected during the cardiopulmonary examination.
options: A. Posterior cerebral artery stroke B. Ischemic optic neuropathy C. Hypoglycemia D. Posterior uveitis E. Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state F. Alcoholic ketoacidosis G. Diabetic retinopathy H. Diabetic ketoacidosis

question:
I am a 40-year-old man who experienced severe substernal chest pain for about an hour. The pain felt like a squeezing sensation, localized to the area beneath my sternum, and it radiated down my left arm. Along with the chest pain, I felt nauseous, dizzy, and I noticed I was sweating more than usual. I did not have any recent fever, chest trauma, heart palpitations, or fainting episodes.

My medical history includes gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), which I have been managing with a proton pump inhibitor for the last three months. I also have uncontrolled type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypercholesterolemia, both diagnosed ten years ago, with my last HbA1c recorded at 8.0.

When I arrived at the medical facility, my vital signs were noted: blood pressure was 140/90 mm Hg, my pulse was 100 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 20 breaths per minute, my temperature was 36.8°C, and my oxygen saturation was 98% on room air. I was given sublingual nitroglycerin, which helped to lessen the chest pain. A chest X-ray appeared normal, but the electrocardiogram (ECG) showed ST-segment elevation in the anterolateral leads.
options: A. Acute coronary syndrome B. GERD C. Diffuse esophageal spasm D. Pulmonary embolism E. Pneumothorax

question:
I am a 68-year-old woman who recently went to the emergency department due to ear pain. This pain began a few days ago and has gradually worsened over time. Alongside the ear pain, I have experienced subjective fevers and neck stiffness. I swim regularly, about 2-3 times a day, which is an important part of my routine.

I have a medical history that includes diabetes, hypertension, and morbid obesity. During my visit, my temperature was recorded at 103°F, and my blood pressure was noted to be 177/99 mmHg. My pulse was 110 beats per minute, my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was measured at 98% on room air. 

The physical examination revealed notable findings that were evaluated further. The healthcare team discussed potential diagnoses based on these symptoms and clinical signs.
options: A. Malignant otitis externa B. Mastoiditis C. Meningitis D. Otitis externa E. Otitis media

question:
I am a 32-year-old expecting my first child and arrived at labor and delivery triage at 38 weeks gestation after experiencing several hours of contractions. The contractions were occurring about four minutes apart. They began after I tripped on a rug and fell on my side. I did not notice any leakage of fluid, and the baby has been moving normally. However, I observed a small amount of blood on my underwear just before coming to the hospital. 

My pregnancy has been uncomplicated up to this point. I have a history of endometriosis, and this pregnancy was achieved through in vitro fertilization. During the pelvic exam in triage, the healthcare provider noted that my cervix was three centimeters dilated, and there was a small amount of blood near the introitus. I am currently awaiting further evaluation and guidance on my condition.
options: A. Normal labor B. Vasa previa C. Placenta previa D. Placental abruption E. Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who went to the emergency department after experiencing difficulty breathing for the past three hours. Over the last week, I had also felt increasingly breathless and fatigued after walking just a few blocks. I have a medical history of diabetes mellitus and hypertension, which I have been managing for the past ten years with medications including metformin, glipizide, and lisinopril. Unfortunately, I did not take my medications last week due to unplanned travel.

About six months ago, I had an episode of acute viral hepatitis, from which I recovered well. When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F), my pulse was 108 beats per minute, my blood pressure was 170/94 mm Hg, and my respiratory rate was 24 breaths per minute. During the physical examination, I was noted to have periorbital edema, along with pitting edema in both ankles and the pretibial areas. There was no pallor or jaundice observed. When the doctor listened to my chest, they detected crackles over the infrascapular regions on both sides. Additionally, my abdomen was tender, and there was evidence of hepatomegaly.
options: A. Acute hepatic failure B. Diabetic ketoacidosis C. Acute decompensated heart failure D. Pulmonary embolism E. Acute renal failure

question:
I was five days old when I was taken to the emergency room at night. My mother reported that I had been experiencing green vomiting for one day and that my belly felt larger than usual. She mentioned that I had passed stool for only two days after my birth and had been feeding well until that morning. After feeding, I vomited and continued to do so sporadically throughout the day.

My mother noted that I had been breastfeeding consistently, although there had been some regurgitation. There were no complications during pregnancy, and I did not have any sick contacts. During the physical examination, the doctors found that my abdomen was distended but did not feel any palpable masses. They also noted that there was no stool in my rectal vault.

I underwent an upper gastrointestinal series to further assess my condition. Throughout this time, my mother was concerned but remained hopeful for a diagnosis that could explain my symptoms.
options: A. Duodenal Atresia B. Mid-gut Volvulus C. Pyloric Stenosis D. Biliary Atresia E. Meconium Ileus

question:
I took my 5-year-old daughter for her routine checkup, where she was found to be up to date on all her vaccinations and meeting all her developmental milestones. During the examination, the doctor noted that she appeared pale and had a few petechiae on her chest, neck, and back. 

The doctor also examined her abdomen and discovered that she had painless hepatosplenomegaly. Following this, some blood tests were conducted, which revealed mildly elevated liver enzymes, slight anemia, and thrombocytopenia. The tests for iron, B12, and folate came back normal. 

To further investigate, a bone marrow biopsy was performed. The results indicated mildly hypocellular marrows and showed diffuse macrophages with eosinophilic cytoplasm, which the doctor described as having a wrinkled tissue paper appearance. Importantly, no blasts were observed in the sample. 

Throughout this process, I remained focused on understanding her condition and what it could mean for her health moving forward. The doctor discussed potential diagnoses based on the findings, and I was eager to learn more about the next steps in her care.
options: A. Viral hepatitis B. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia C. Biliary obstruction D. Autoimmune disorder E. Gaucher disease type I

question:
I am a 46-year-old man who was recently diagnosed with pancreatic adenocarcinoma. Two days ago, I began experiencing fever, malaise, and difficulty breathing, which have progressively worsened. My medical history includes multiple abdominal surgeries, including a procedure to place a stent in my pancreatic duct.

Upon my admission to the hospital, I was taking several medications: rosuvastatin 20 mg daily, aspirin 81 mg daily, esomeprazole 20 mg daily, oxycodone 10 mg twice daily, lorazepam 2 mg three times daily as needed, and ondansetron 10 mg intravenously. My vital signs showed a blood pressure of 105/75 mm Hg, a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute, a pulse of 90 beats per minute, and a temperature of 37.0°C (98.6°F).

On the second day of my hospitalization, I became acutely obtunded. My vital signs changed to a blood pressure of 85/55 mm Hg, a respiratory rate of 32 breaths per minute, and a pulse of 115 beats per minute. During the physical examination, the medical team noted multiple bruises on my body and active bleeding from various IV and venipuncture sites. Additionally, there was significant swelling and redness on the back of my left leg. Further evaluation indicated thrombocytopenia and prolonged PT and PTT, with an elevated D-dimer level. Blood cultures are currently pending.
options: A. Antiphospholipid syndrome B. Disseminated intravascular coagulation C. Factor VIII inhibitor D. von Willebrand disease E. Vitamin K deficiency

question:
I am a 65-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department after a fall in the shower earlier this morning. My wife heard me fall and found me in the bathroom with all four of my extremities twitching. This episode lasted about 30 seconds. When I regained consciousness, I was disoriented and unable to answer simple questions. Fortunately, I have since regained my orientation.

I have a medical history that includes hypertension and hyperlipidemia, for which I take metoprolol and atorvastatin. Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were stable: my temperature was 37.1°C, pulse was 72 beats per minute, respirations were 19 per minute, and my blood pressure was 130/80 mm Hg. My oxygen saturation was 98% on room air.

During the cranial nerve examination, no abnormalities were noted, and I displayed full muscle strength in all my extremities. Sensation to pinprick, light touch, and vibration was normal and symmetrical.

To further investigate, a noncontrast head CT was performed, which revealed a slightly hyperdense mass. A follow-up MRI showed a homogeneous, well-circumscribed 4-cm mass with compression of the adjacent white matter and a hyperintense rim around the mass on T2-weighted imaging.
options: A. Glioblastoma multiforme B. Oligodendroglioma C. Schwannoma D. Hemangioblastoma E. Medulloblastoma F. Meningioma

question:
I am a 44-year-old man who went to the emergency department after experiencing sudden chest pain and difficulty breathing for the past three hours. The pain was located in the retrosternal area and radiated up to my left shoulder and arm. It intensified when I took deep breaths but seemed to ease when I leaned forward. 

Upon arrival, my heart rate was measured at 61 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 16 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 36.5°C (97.7°F). My blood pressure read 115/78 mm Hg. During the physical examination, no abnormalities were noted, but the medical staff detected a pericardial friction rub when they listened to my heart. 

I underwent an ECG as part of the evaluation process. The doctors also mentioned that laboratory results indicated elevated levels of erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and C-reactive protein (CRP), although I do not have those values. The medical team was working to determine the most likely diagnosis based on my symptoms and examination findings.
options: A. Acute pericarditis B. Angina pectoris C. Aortic stenosis D. Infective endocarditis E. Myocardial infarction

question:
I am an 18-year-old woman who recently visited my primary care physician for a physical examination required for school. Over the past year, I have not experienced any illnesses. I am an active member of my school's volleyball team and exercise daily. I do not use drugs and have never smoked cigarettes.

During the physical exam, my doctor noticed some bruising around my neck and what appeared to be burn marks on my back and thighs. When my physician inquired about these marks, I explained that they resulted from my sexual activities. I shared that in order to feel aroused, I engage in acts such as hitting and choking, among other things. 

I live with my boyfriend, and we are in a committed, monogamous relationship. Currently, I am focused on my studies with aspirations of attending law school, and I work part-time in a coffee shop. Overall, my medical history and the rest of the physical examination were unremarkable.
options: A. Domestic abuse B. Dependent personality disorder C. Avoidant personality disorder D. Sexual masochism E. Sexual sadism

question:
I am a 52-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department after experiencing several concerning symptoms over the past three weeks. I noticed significant abdominal distention, a yellowing of my skin, and dark urine. Alongside these changes, I felt increasingly fatigued and short of breath, especially with minimal exertion. 

I have a history of chronic alcohol consumption and was diagnosed with cirrhosis two years ago. Despite being advised to stop drinking, I continued to do so and had avoided further medical consultations until this visit. 

Upon examination, my vital signs showed a heart rate of 62 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 26 breaths per minute, and a temperature of 37.4°C. The medical staff noted my jaundiced skin and eyes, as well as severe abdominal distention and pain on palpation in the right side of my abdomen. They observed significant swelling in my legs, indicating edema. 

During my hospital stay, I experienced decreased urine output and a change in my mental status by the fifth day. The medical team conducted various tests to monitor my condition. They noted a decline in several blood parameters, including an increase in creatinine levels. 

I am aware that my ongoing alcohol consumption and subsequent health issues have contributed to my current state, which has now led to serious complications.
options: A. Acute tubular necrosis B. Chronic kidney disease C. Glomerulonephritis D. Hepatorenal syndrome E. Pyelonephritis

question:
I am a mother of a 2-month-old boy who was brought to the emergency department after he experienced a seizure. This incident occurred 25 minutes prior to our arrival. Over the past week, he has had multiple seizures, which has been concerning. For about a month now, I have noticed that he has become increasingly lethargic and his cry has weakened significantly. 

He was born at 37 weeks' gestation and is currently in the 20th percentile for height and the 15th percentile for weight. Upon examination in the emergency department, his temperature was recorded at 36.7°C (98°F), with a respiratory rate of 50 breaths per minute and a pulse of 140 beats per minute. The doctor noted that his abdomen was soft and nontender, but the liver was palpable 4 cm below the right costal margin, while there was no enlargement of the spleen.

The medical team conducted various serum studies, which revealed several findings, including low glucose levels and elevated lactate levels. They discussed the possibility of an enzyme deficiency being the underlying cause of my son's symptoms. This situation has been very distressing for me as a mother, and I am seeking answers and treatment for my child.
options:
A. Glycogen branching enzyme B. Galactose 1-phosphate uridyltransferase C. Fructokinase D. Glucose 6-phosphatase E. Acid maltase
"

question:
I am a 32-year-old woman, currently 31 weeks pregnant with my second child. I was brought to the emergency department due to confusion. For the past three days, I experienced diffuse abdominal pain, malaise, nausea, and vomiting. I have a two-year history of gastroesophageal reflux disease and previously suffered from preeclampsia during my first pregnancy, which was managed by inducing labor at 37 weeks.

Recently, I spent two weeks in Belize for my honeymoon. Upon arrival at the hospital, I felt tired and had a fever of 38°C (100°F). My vital signs showed a pulse of 82 beats per minute, respiratory rate of 19 breaths per minute, and a blood pressure of 118/79 mm Hg. I was able to respond to sound and communicated in short sentences. During the examination, the medical team noted yellowish discoloration of my sclera and abdominal distention, with tenderness in the right upper quadrant. When asked to extend my hands, I demonstrated a noticeable flapping tremor.

The size of my uterus was consistent with my gestational age. While specific lab results were not shared with me, they were conducted as part of my evaluation. Overall, I was concerned about my symptoms and the implications for my pregnancy and health.
