options: A. Preeclampsia B. Acute fatty liver of pregnancy C. HELLP syndrome D. Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy E. Acute viral hepatitis A F. Acute viral hepatitis B

question:
I am a 42-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain. The pain I experienced was rated 9 out of 10 in severity. It was sharp and primarily located on my right side, radiating to my right shoulder blade. I mentioned to the medical staff that I had experienced similar pain in the past, typically triggered by consuming a large meal.

Upon examination, I appeared well, and my vital signs were taken. My temperature was measured at 36 degrees Celsius, my heart rate was 78 beats per minute, my blood pressure read 130 over 80 mmHg, my respiratory rate was 10 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 100%.

The healthcare team ordered several tests, including a complete blood count, basic metabolic panel, and liver function tests, all of which returned within normal limits. The emergency physician then performed an emergency medicine bedside ultrasound to further investigate the cause of my pain. 

At this point, I awaited further information regarding the underlying issue contributing to my symptoms.
options: A. Viscous distension of gallbladder B. Inflammation of gallbladder C. Inflammation of common bile duct D. Viscous distension of cystic duct E. Inflammation of cystic duct

question:
I am a 50-year-old male and recently visited my primary care provider due to a concerning symptom. For the past six months, I have been experiencing episodes where I smell abnormal odors, specifically burnt rubber, even though there is nothing burning and no one around me can detect these smells. These episodes have occurred intermittently during this time.

Additionally, I've had occasional nosebleeds, which have added to my concerns. I work as a high school teacher, and while I do experience some stress, particularly around exam season, I feel that I manage it effectively. My family medical history is unremarkable, and I do not smoke or consume alcohol. I also do not take any medications.

During my physical examination, my doctor noted unilateral nasal obstruction and observed some dried blood in my nasal passage. I hope to understand the underlying cause of these symptoms and what steps I should take next.
options: A. Psychomotor epilepsy B. Neuroblastoma C. Hypnagogic hallucination D. Substance abuse E. Schizophrenia

question:
I am an 18-year-old woman who was brought to the emergency department by my coach about 30 minutes after injuring my left knee while playing field hockey. During the game, I was tackled from the left side, and since then, I have been unable to bear weight on my left leg. I have a concern that my left knee might be unstable when I try to stand.

I do not have any personal or family history of serious illness. Upon examination, I felt uncomfortable, and the medical staff noted that my vital signs were within normal limits. They observed that my left knee was swollen and tender, and my range of motion was limited due to pain. There was tenderness along the medial joint line of my knee. 

While lying supine, my hip was slightly flexed and abducted, and my knee was also slightly flexed. The medical team applied gentle valgus stress across my left knee, which revealed some medial joint laxity. The remainder of the examination showed no further abnormalities. After this assessment, the medical staff began to discuss the potential diagnosis related to my knee injury.
options: A. Posterior cruciate ligament injury B. Medial meniscus injury C. Anterior cruciate ligament injury D. Lateral collateral ligament injury E. Medial collateral ligament injury F. Lateral meniscus injury

question:
I was 49 years old when I experienced a sudden onset of crushing chest pain accompanied by palpitations. I was taken to the emergency department by ambulance. My medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and obesity. I take several medications daily, including chlorthalidone, lisinopril, atorvastatin, metformin, and an oral contraceptive. My job as a lawyer is quite stressful, and I typically have a glass of wine with dinner every evening. I also smoke about 10 cigarettes a day.

During the ambulance ride, the emergency personnel provided oxygen and stabilized my condition. Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were recorded: my blood pressure was 120/80 mm Hg, my heart rate was 120 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 22 breaths per minute, and my temperature was slightly elevated at 37.7°C (99.9°F). 

The physical exam revealed that I was in acute distress, sweating profusely, and had difficulty breathing. They performed a bedside electrocardiogram (ECG), which indicated ST-segment elevation in leads II, III, and aVF.
options: A. Inferior wall myocardial infarction B. Lateral wall myocardial infarction C. Posterior wall myocardial infarction D. Anteroseptal myocardial infarction E. Right ventricular myocardial infarction

question:
I am a 34-year-old individual with a medical history that includes anxiety, chronic constipation, chronic headaches, and chronic hypertension. Recently, I experienced severe right flank pain that radiated to my scrotum, prompting me to visit the emergency room for evaluation. 

During my visit, the medical team performed a urinalysis and a stone analysis to determine the cause of my pain. While I awaited the results, I was monitored for my blood pressure, which remained high at 170/110 mmHg even before my discharge. Additionally, tests revealed that my calcium and parathyroid hormone (PTH) levels were elevated.

The healthcare providers discussed potential complications related to my condition, particularly concerning my thyroid. They indicated that certain histology slides of thyroid tissue could represent a complication stemming from my current health issues. Overall, the experience was concerning due to the combination of my symptoms and the elevated levels in my tests, and I left the emergency room with a better understanding of my situation and the need for further evaluation.
options: A. Anaplastic thyroid cancer B. Medullary thyroid cancer C. Papillary thyroid cancer D. Lymphoma E. Follicular thyroid cancer

question:
I am a 60-year-old man who presented to the hospital with pain in my right upper quadrant. I have a history of hepatitis B. After undergoing a CT scan of my abdomen, the doctors found a large mass measuring 11.3 cm by 7.2 cm, along with a metastatic retroperitoneal lymph node. I was diagnosed with hepatocellular carcinoma and started receiving radiotherapy while on the transplant list, in hopes of preventing the local expansion of the cancer.

Three months after completing the radiotherapy, I experienced episodes of hematemesis and melena. This prompted me to go to the emergency department for evaluation. Upon arrival, my vital signs were concerning, with a blood pressure of 84/56 mmHg, a heart rate of 92 beats per minute, and a respiratory rate of 20 breaths per minute. 

During the laboratory evaluation, I was found to be severely anemic, with a hemoglobin level of 5.7 g/dL, an INR of 1.8, and a platelet count of 68,000 cells/mm³. I received a blood transfusion to address the anemia. An endoscopic examination revealed diffuse edematous hyperemic mucosa and multiple hemorrhagic patches with active oozing in the antrum. The doctors are now evaluating the likely diagnosis for the lesions observed during the procedure.
options: A. Intrinsic apoptotic pathway B. Coagulative necrosis C. Overexpression of BcL-2 gene D. Cytotoxic CD8 T cells pathway E. Extrinsic apoptotic pathway

question:
I am a 32-year-old man, and I recently went to the emergency room due to sudden chest pain, a persistent cough, and shortness of breath. I noticed that I was having difficulty breathing, which prompted me to seek medical attention. 

Upon examination by the medical staff, they found that I had decreased breath sounds on the right side of my chest. This finding added to my concerns about my respiratory status. The doctors performed a chest radiography, which revealed translucency on the right side of my chest. Additionally, my blood gas levels indicated an elevated pCO2 and a decreased pO2. 

These symptoms and findings were concerning, and the medical team began to assess the possible causes of my condition.
options: A. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease B. Asthma C. Pneumonia D. Tension pneumothorax E. Spontaneous pneumothorax

question:
I am a 57-year-old man and recently visited my primary care physician due to experiencing shortness of breath. Over the past year, I noticed that this shortness of breath has worsened. My medical history includes asthma and constipation, for which I currently take albuterol and sodium docusate. 

I served as an officer in the navy and now live at home with my wife. Additionally, I have a significant smoking history, totaling 52 pack-years. During my visit, my physician performed pulmonary function testing to assess my respiratory condition. The results from this test were compared to my results from 12 years ago. 

I am aware that my symptoms and medical history could suggest various potential diagnoses, and I am seeking clarity on what might be causing my current respiratory issues.
options: A. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease B. Unstable angina C. Interstitial lung disease D. Poorly treated asthma E. Small cell carcinoma of the lung

question:
At 49 years old, I underwent a routine complete blood count (CBC) as part of a regular health check-up. I did not experience any symptoms at the time. However, the results indicated a white blood cell count of 40,000 per microliter, which was significantly elevated. 

To further understand this finding, a peripheral blood smear was performed. The analysis revealed leukocytosis, showing a variety of myeloid cells at different stages of differentiation. Notably, there was a higher percentage of more mature cells compared to the less mature ones. 

Given these observations, my healthcare provider discussed the potential implications of the results and what they might signify regarding my health.
options: A. Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL) B. Acute Myelogenous Leukemia (AML) C. Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL) D. Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia (CML) E. Acute Promyelocytic Leukemia (APL or APML)

question:
I am a 55-year-old truck driver, and three days ago, I developed a fever and started feeling weak. Despite my symptoms, I initially refused medical help. My wife became concerned when I couldn’t go to work due to how I was feeling, so she brought me to see a physician. 

I had a tricuspid valve replacement surgery about a year ago and take aspirin daily. Additionally, I have a medical history that includes a myocardial infarction three years ago and hypertension, which I've been managing with lisinopril for the past ten years. 

When I arrived for the examination, my blood pressure was recorded at 140/80 mm Hg, my pulse was 82 beats per minute, my respirations were 18 per minute, and my temperature was 37.2°C (98.9°F). During the physical examination, the physician noted several hemorrhages on the nail beds of several of my fingers. 

I understand that my symptoms and medical history are crucial in helping to establish a diagnosis, and I am now seeking to understand what further findings might be most helpful in this process.
options: A. Thickened valve with multiple small vegetations B. Bicuspid valve C. Friable irregular masses attached to the valve D. Papillary muscle rupture E. Annular calcification

question:
At 36 weeks gestation, I went to the emergency department due to a sudden onset of voluminous bloody discharge from my vagina. This happened while I was at home, and I also began to experience abdominal pain and felt dehydrated. My medical history includes substance abuse, obesity, and hypertension. Additionally, I have been a victim of domestic abuse.

I was taking folic acid, ibuprofen, and sodium docusate at the time of my visit. Upon arrival, my temperature was 99.5°F, and my blood pressure read 100/55 mmHg. My pulse was at 100 beats per minute, my respirations were 19 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air. 

In the emergency department, I was placed on IV fluids and given 100% oxygen due to my ongoing symptoms, particularly the abdominal pain. The medical team conducted external fetal monitoring to assess the situation further.
options: A. Separation of the placenta from the decidua B. Partial covering of the external cervical os by the placenta C. Placental invasion of the decidua basalis D. Partial tear of fetal vessels E. Normal progression of labor

question:
I am a 24-year-old woman who visited the emergency department due to lower abdominal pain that had persisted for four hours. For the past two days, I had experienced vaginal spotting. My menstrual cycles have been irregular, ranging from 20 to 45 days, and typically last between 3 and 7 days. Notably, my last menstrual period occurred eight weeks ago. 

In my medical history, I was treated for pelvic inflammatory disease at the age of 20 with ceftriaxone and azithromycin. I am currently sexually active with one male partner; however, we use condoms inconsistently. 

Upon arrival at the hospital, my pulse was recorded at 118 beats per minute, my respirations were at 20 per minute, and my blood pressure was 118/66 mm Hg. The examination revealed tenderness in my lower abdomen. During the pelvic examination, my cervix was closed, and my uterus appeared normal in size, but there was tenderness in the right adnexa. 

A serum β-human chorionic gonadotropin test indicated a concentration of 16,000 mIU/mL, and a transvaginal ultrasound revealed a 5-cm hypoechoic lesion located at the junction of the fallopian tube and uterine cavity, surrounded by a 3-mm layer of myometrium.
options: A. Interstitial pregnancy B. Spontaneous abortion C. Incomplete hydatidiform mole D. Complete hydatidiform mole E. Adenomyosis F. Choriocarcinoma G. Placenta previa H. Bicornuate uterus pregnancy

question:
I am a 45-year-old chronic smoker, and I recently visited my physician due to worsening pain in my left shoulder. This discomfort had been present for several months but intensified significantly over the past two weeks. The pain now radiates down my left arm.

During the physical examination, the doctor found a palpable lymph node measuring approximately 2 x 1.5 cm in the supraclavicular area. Additionally, I experienced decreased grip strength in my left hand. The physician also noted partial ptosis of my left eyelid and miosis of my left eye, which I was not previously aware of.

To further investigate my condition, the doctor ordered a chest X-ray, which revealed a soft tissue mass at the apex of my left lung, with possible involvement of the first rib. This progression of symptoms and findings during the examination raised concerns about my health, prompting the need for a more thorough evaluation.
options: A. Pulmonary hamartoma B. Mesothelioma C. Pancoast tumor D. Subclavian aneurysm E. Osteophyte

question:
I was taken to the emergency department by my parents due to severe pain in my right hip that started suddenly about two hours earlier. My parents were visibly anxious, as I have experienced similar episodes of pain in the past that required hospitalization. I was born at 39 weeks of gestation through a spontaneous vaginal delivery. I have kept up with all my vaccinations and am meeting all my developmental milestones. 

For the past three years, I have been taking hydroxyurea as my only medication. Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were recorded: my blood pressure was 125/84 mm Hg, my respiratory rate was 23 breaths per minute, my pulse was 87 beats per minute, and my temperature was 36.7°C (98.0°F). During the physical examination, I was in distress due to the severe pain, which I rated as an 8 out of 10. The pain intensified with gentle palpation of my right femoral head. The medical team began assessing my condition to determine the underlying cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Iliotibial band syndrome B. Osgood-Schlatter disease C. Legg-Calve-Perthes disease D. Posterior dislocation of the hip E. Developmental dysplasia of the hip

question:
Three days into my hospitalization for a fractured distal femur, I began to experience dyspnea and confusion. Prior to this, I had no history of any serious illness. During this episode, I found myself unable to answer questions or follow commands. Medical staff recorded my blood pressure at 145/90 mm Hg, my pulse at 120 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate at 36 breaths per minute. My temperature was measured at 36.7°C (98.1°F), and I had an oxygen saturation level of 90% while on 80% FiO2.

Upon examination, the medical team noted purpura on my anterior chest, head, and neck. They also detected inspiratory crackles in both lung fields. The clinical situation raised concerns, and further evaluations were conducted to understand the cause of these symptoms. The rapid onset of dyspnea, confusion, and the physical findings prompted a thorough investigation by the healthcare team.
options: A. Acute respiratory distress syndrome B. Fat embolism C. Hospital-acquired pneumonia D. Pulmonary contusion E. Pulmonary thromboembolism F. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura

question:
I am a 65-year-old man, and I found myself in the emergency department after experiencing a loss of consciousness about an hour prior. My wife was adjusting my necktie when I suddenly fainted. Fortunately, I regained consciousness within 30 seconds and felt fully alert and oriented afterwards. 

I have experienced two similar fainting episodes in the past year. I also deal with anxiety and take alprazolam as needed. Additionally, I smoke about half a pack of cigarettes daily and typically drink two glasses of wine with dinner each night. 

Upon arriving at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 37.2°C (98.9°F), my pulse was 70 beats per minute and regular, my respirations were 13 per minute, and my blood pressure was 130/82 mm Hg while lying down, dropping to 122/80 mm Hg when standing. 

A cardiopulmonary examination showed no abnormalities, and a neurological examination revealed no focal findings. A complete blood count also indicated no issues. Bedside cardiac monitoring revealed infrequent premature ventricular contractions and QRS voltage below 5 mm in leads II and III. 

The medical team is now assessing my situation to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Structural cardiac abnormality B. Orthostatic syncope C. Hypoglycemia D. Carotid sinus hypersensitivity E. Panic attack F. Cardiac arrhythmia

question:
I was 23 years old when I was brought to the emergency department by ambulance. I was found unconscious in my bedroom after attempting to take my own life by cutting my wrists with a kitchen knife. Upon arrival, I was unresponsive and appeared pale. My body temperature was low, and my blood pressure was extremely low at 70/35 mmHg. My pulse was rapid at 190 beats per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 92% while breathing room air.

Medical staff applied pressure to the lacerations on my wrists and conducted a full trauma assessment, finding no other injuries. I was given intravenous fluids and underwent a rapid transfusion sequence. They administered norepinephrine, and after some time, my blood pressure improved to 100/65 mmHg, and my pulse decreased to 100 beats per minute. I began to respond but felt mildly confused.

Thirty minutes later, my condition changed; my Glasgow Coma Scale score dropped to 11. I had a fever of 103°F, my blood pressure was 90/60 mmHg, my pulse was at 122 beats per minute, and I experienced flank pain. Medical tests were ordered to assess my situation further.
options: A. Non-cardiogenic acute lung injury B. Decreased IgA levels C. Major blood group incompatibility D. Minor blood group incompatibility E. Recipient antibody reaction against foreign leukocytes

question:
I am a 65-year-old woman who experienced severe abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea. My medical history includes a myocardial infarction that occurred six months ago. I have a significant smoking history, having smoked for 25 years, and I consume approximately 80 ounces of alcohol each week.

When I sought medical attention, the examination revealed that my abdomen was diffusely tender, and there were no bowel sounds present. A plain abdominal X-ray was performed, which showed no free air under the diaphragm. Despite these evaluations, my condition worsened rapidly, and I ultimately passed away.

In reflecting on my situation, I understand there may have been various underlying issues contributing to my symptoms and rapid decline.
options: A. Small bowel obstruction B. Small bowel ischemia C. Ulcerative colitis D. Perforated appendicitis E. Acute pancreatitis

question:
I brought my 2-year-old daughter to see the physician due to some concerning symptoms. For about a week, I had noticed that her abdomen was distended, and she was experiencing twitching in her feet. Additionally, she had been running a low-grade fever for the past five days. I was also worried because she hadn’t had a bowel movement in three days.

My daughter was born at term and had been generally healthy up until now. At her last check-up, she was in the 40th percentile for height and the 20th percentile for weight. During our visit, the doctor recorded her temperature at 38.1°C (100.6°F), her pulse at 128 beats per minute, and her blood pressure at 135/82 mm Hg. 

Upon examination, the doctor found an irregular palpable mass in her abdomen that crossed the midline. He also noted that her liver was palpable 3 cm below the right costal margin. There were erratic movements of her eyes that caught his attention. Following this, a 24-hour urine collection was performed, which indicated elevated levels of homovanillic acid and vanillylmandelic acid. The physician mentioned considering a diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Hodgkin lymphoma B. Pheochromocytoma C. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia D. Hepatoblastoma E. Nephroblastoma F. Neuroblastoma G. Rhabdomyosarcoma H. Mesoblastic nephroma

question:
I am a 75-year-old woman who has been experiencing episodic abdominal pain after meals for the past few years. Recently, these episodes have worsened over the past month. I have a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, which I was diagnosed with 30 years ago. I manage my diabetes with metformin. During my most recent check-up last month, my HbA1C level was recorded at 10%. 

When I visited the doctor, my vital signs were taken, revealing a blood pressure of 110/70 mm Hg, a pulse rate of 80 beats per minute, and a respiratory rate of 16 breaths per minute. The physical examination conducted by my physician did not indicate any abnormalities. 

I am seeking help to understand the cause of my worsening abdominal pain after meals, as it has become increasingly concerning for me.
options: A. Acute pancreatitis B. Hepatic infarction C. Chronic renal failure D. Mesenteric artery occlusion E. Ruptured aortic aneurysm

question:
I am a 68-year-old woman who was found unresponsive in my bedroom at the nursing home where I reside. I have a medical history of hypertension, which was diagnosed five years ago. For this condition, I have been prescribed a calcium channel blocker and a thiazide diuretic. 

When I was brought to the emergency department, my blood pressure was notably high at 200/116 mm Hg. My heart rate was measured at 70 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 15 breaths per minute. My body temperature was recorded at 36.5°C (97.7°F). 

During the examination, my doctors performed a cardiopulmonary assessment, which appeared mostly unremarkable aside from the detection of a fourth heart sound. A neurological evaluation indicated that I was stuporous, only responding to painful stimuli with eye movements and no verbal responses. My pupils were symmetric but reacted sluggishly to light. 

A noncontrast CT scan of my head was performed to further investigate my condition. The medical team is now considering the most likely etiology of my unresponsiveness.
options: A. Charcot-Bouchard aneurysm rupture B. Arteriovenous malformation rupture C. Dural arteriovenous fistula D. Venous sinus thrombosis E. Hemorrhagic transformation

question:
I am a 17-year-old who was previously healthy until I underwent elective wisdom teeth removal. My mother brought me to the emergency department for further evaluation after the procedure. During the surgery, I experienced persistent bleeding from the gums surrounding the teeth. Despite multiple gauze packs being applied, the bleeding continued with minimal effect.

I have a history of easy bruising, which I mentioned to the medical team. My mother noted that my uncle had similar issues when he had his wisdom teeth removed, and he also has a history of easy bruising and joint swelling. I do not take any medications.

Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was 37°C, my pulse was 90 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 108/74 mm Hg. The medical staff conducted various laboratory studies, although I did not receive specific results regarding them during my visit.

Overall, I was concerned about the bleeding and my family history of similar issues. The medical team worked to evaluate my condition further to determine the underlying cause of the bleeding after my dental procedure.
options: A. Von Willebrand disease B. Glanzmann thrombasthenia C. Immune thrombocytopenia D. Disseminated intravascular coagulation E. Hemophilia F. Bernard-Soulier syndrome

question:
I am a 63-year-old man who visited the emergency room due to worsening breathlessness that started overnight. I have a history of asthma, which I was diagnosed with three years ago, and I have been using albuterol and steroid inhalers for management. I do not have any prior history of cardiac disease or other respiratory conditions.

Upon arrival at the emergency room, my respiratory rate was 40 breaths per minute, my blood pressure was 130/90 mm Hg, my pulse rate was 110 beats per minute, and my temperature was normal at 37.0°C. During my physical examination, I was in severe respiratory distress and unable to lie down comfortably. The doctor noted widespread wheezing in my lungs and detected an S3 gallop rhythm during the chest auscultation.

I was admitted to the hospital, where laboratory investigations and imaging studies were ordered. My white blood cell count was elevated, and my eosinophil count was significantly high. Additional tests showed a positive result for anti-MPO (P-ANCA) antibodies, while other viral serological tests were negative. An ECG indicated regular sinus tachycardia, and a transthoracic echocardiogram revealed a dilated left ventricle with a reduced ejection fraction.
options: A. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA) B. Chagas disease C. Primary dilated cardiomyopathy D. Loeffler's endocarditis E. Extrinsic asthma

question:
I was brought to the emergency department 30 minutes after experiencing a sudden onset of severe chest pain that migrated across my anterior chest. Along with the pain, I felt short of breath and was sweating, even while at rest. I have a history of hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and type 2 diabetes, for which I take atorvastatin, hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril, and metformin. Additionally, I have been a smoker, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily for the past 25 years.

Upon arrival, I was in severe distress. The medical staff noted my pulse was elevated at 110 beats per minute, my respirations were at 20 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was recorded at 150 over 85 mm Hg. Despite these symptoms, my oxygen saturation was measured at 98% while I was breathing room air. During the cardiac examination, the physician detected a grade 3/6, high-pitched, blowing diastolic murmur, which was best heard over the right sternal border. My lung sounds were clear, but the femoral pulses were decreased on both sides. An ECG revealed sinus tachycardia and signs of left ventricular hypertrophy.
options: A. Pulmonary embolism B. Esophageal rupture C. Aortic dissection D. Spontaneous pneumothorax E. Papillary muscle rupture F. Myocardial infarction

question:
I am a 32-year-old man who recently experienced significant discomfort. Three days ago, I was bitten by a spider, and I didn't think much of it at the time. However, yesterday, I noticed that my left calf had become swollen, red, and extremely painful. The pain intensified to a point where it felt excruciating. 

I decided to go to the emergency department for evaluation. Upon arrival, I had a fever of 102.8°F, my heart rate was elevated at 112 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was measured at 134/76. During the examination, the doctor noted that my left leg was swollen, extremely tender to touch, and had a purplish, dusky appearance. There was also a noticeable crepitus when the area was palpated. 

Due to the concerning symptoms, a biopsy was performed to further investigate the issue. I am awaiting the results to understand what might be causing these symptoms.
options: A. Deep venous thrombosis B. Thrombophlebitis C. Venous insufficiency D. Necrotizing fasciitis E. Osteomyelitis

question:
Two days after my emergent laparotomy and splenectomy due to a grade IV splenic laceration from a motor vehicle collision, I noticed a significant decrease in my urinary output. Despite receiving aggressive fluid resuscitation, I was outputting less than 350 mL of urine per day. During the surgery, I required three units of packed red blood cells.

I have a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and manage my blood sugar with an insulin sliding scale. At the time, my vital signs were stable and within normal limits. Upon physical examination, the doctor noted that my surgical incision in the upper abdomen was healing, but I also had multiple large bruises on the superior right and left sides of my abdomen.

I was informed that my hematocrit level was at 28%, my platelet count was 400,000/mm3, and my serum creatinine level was 3.9 mg/dL, with a serum urea nitrogen concentration of 29 mg/dL. The urinalysis revealed brown granular casts. I was concerned about these findings and wanted to understand the potential underlying cause of my decreased urinary output and the other abnormalities noted.
options: A. Acute tubular necrosis B. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis C. Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis D. Allergic interstitial nephritis E. Myorenal syndrome F. Acute renal infarction

question:
I attended my annual check-up at the age of 70. Overall, I felt well, but I mentioned experiencing occasional abdominal pain. I would rate the intensity of this pain between 4 and 5 out of 10. It was localized around my belly button and the upper abdomen, sometimes radiating to my groin. This pain occurred about once or twice a month and would always resolve on its own.

I did not report any recent fever, chills, nausea, vomiting, or changes in my body weight or bowel and bladder habits. My medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and peripheral vascular disease, for which I take lisinopril and simvastatin. I have a 40-pack-year smoking history and consume 1 to 2 alcoholic drinks daily.

During the examination, my blood pressure was recorded as 150/100 mm Hg, and my pulse was 80 beats per minute. The physician noted that the peripheral pulses were strong and equal in both arms and legs. Upon abdominal examination, a bruit was detected in the epigastric region, along with mild tenderness but no rebound tenderness or guarding. A pulsatile mass was also felt during deep palpation in the area between my belly button and the pubic region. The remainder of the physical exam was normal, and no additional tests were conducted during this visit.
options: A. Abdominal aortic aneurysm B. Acute pancreatitis C. Mesenteric ischemia D. Acute gastritis E. Diverticulitis

question:
I am a 25-year-old woman who is currently 28 weeks pregnant. Recently, I experienced a headache, which prompted me to seek medical attention. My pregnancy has been monitored by a nurse practitioner. Upon examination, my temperature was recorded at 99.0°F, and my blood pressure was notably high at 164/104 mmHg. My pulse was measured at 100 beats per minute, my respirations were at 22 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air.

During the physical examination, I appeared comfortable, and my gravid uterus was assessed. Given my symptoms and vital signs, laboratory tests were ordered to further investigate my condition. The results indicated a hemoglobin level of 12 g/dL and a hematocrit of 36%. My leukocyte count was within normal limits at 6,700/mm³, but my platelet count was lower than expected at 100,500/mm³. 

In the serum tests, my sodium, chloride, potassium, bicarbonate, and glucose levels were within normal ranges, though my blood urea nitrogen (BUN) was slightly elevated at 21 mg/dL. Urinalysis revealed amber-colored urine with a positive protein result but no blood present. These findings were concerning, and it was clear that further evaluation would be necessary to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Acute fatty liver disease of pregnancy B. Eclampsia C. HELLP syndrome D. Preeclampsia E. Severe preeclampsia

question:
I took my 18-month-old son to see a pediatric hematologist, as he had been experiencing prolonged neutropenia. His father and I had noticed that his blood tests consistently showed a low neutrophil count, although his hemoglobin, hematocrit, and platelet counts were normal. 

My son was born at 39 weeks gestation through a spontaneous vaginal delivery and has been developing normally. He is up to date on all his vaccinations and is meeting all the expected developmental milestones for his age. 

During our visit, the doctor performed a complete blood count (CBC) with differential. The results indicated a hemoglobin level of 15.5 g/dL, a platelet count of 300,000 mm3, and neutrophils at 20%. Other values included bands at 2%, lymphocytes at 40%, and monocytes at 15%. 

The doctor also checked his vital signs — his heart rate was 90 beats per minute, respiratory rate 22 breaths per minute, blood pressure 110/65 mm Hg, and his temperature was 37.0°C (98.6°F). On physical examination, my son appeared healthy and was within the expected growth parameters for his age and sex. 

To further investigate, a bone marrow biopsy was performed, which showed normal bone marrow with 95% cellularity and trilineage maturation. Flow cytometry revealed no abnormal markers. I was left wondering about the most probable diagnosis for his condition.
options: A. Chronic benign neutropenia B. Chronic lymphoblastic leukemia C. Sepsis D. Aplastic anemia E. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia

question:
I am a 45-year-old woman who went to the emergency department due to severe menorrhagia that had persisted for three days. Along with the heavy bleeding, I experienced dizziness. I have a history of hypertension and take lisinopril for it. Upon arrival, I noted that I appeared pale. My vital signs indicated a temperature of 37.5˚C (99.5˚F), a pulse of 110 beats per minute, and a blood pressure reading of 100/60 mmHg. My oxygen saturation was measured at 98% while on room air.

During the pelvic examination, the doctor observed dark maroon blood and clots in the vaginal vault but found no active source of bleeding. A hemoglobin test revealed a concentration of 5.9 g/dL. I was given crystalloid fluids and received four units of crossmatched packed red blood cells.

About two hours later, I began to feel short of breath and experienced dull chest pressure. My temperature increased slightly to 37.6°C (99.7°F), my pulse was 105 beats per minute, and my blood pressure measured 170/90 mmHg. My oxygen saturation dropped to 92% on room air. The cardiac examination revealed an S3 gallop, and diffuse crackles were heard in my lower lung fields. A chest X-ray showed bilateral hazy opacities, while an ECG showed no abnormalities.
options: A. Type 1 hypersensitivity reaction B. Transfusion-related acute lung injury C. Acute pulmonary embolism D. Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction E. Acute kidney injury F. Hypertensive emergency G. Transfusion-associated circulatory overload H. Acute myocardial infarction

question:
I am a 9-year-old boy, and I was brought to the doctor by my mother because she noticed bruising on my torso and limbs. She mentioned that I have not had any other symptoms and that I am otherwise healthy. During the visit, the doctor examined me and found multiple petechiae and bruises on my torso and arms, which were present on both sides of my body. 

The doctor conducted a physical examination, which didn’t reveal any other issues. Afterward, I had some blood tests done. The results showed that my blood count was normal. The coagulation profile indicated that my prothrombin time was 12 seconds, but my activated partial thromboplastin time was 60 seconds. 

Despite the bruising, I felt fine and did not experience any pain or discomfort. My mother seemed concerned, but the doctor reassured us that they would investigate the cause of the bruising further.
options: A. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia B. Hemophilia B C. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura D. Von Willebrand disease E. Hemophilia A

question: I found myself in a busy intersection, feeling disoriented and detached from reality. I was jumping up and down on top of a car, completely naked, when the local police arrived and took me into custody. I hadn’t slept in two days, as I didn’t feel tired at all. During the interaction with the police, I began to hear voices, which was unsettling. This wasn’t the first time I had experienced such symptoms; I had been hospitalized a year ago due to similar issues, including auditory hallucinations and paranoia, although my mood had been normal at that time. My current state was alarming, and I felt a sense of confusion about what was happening to me.
options: A. Schizophrenia B. Schizotypal disorder C. Schizoaffective disorder D. Bipolar disorder E. Unipolar mania

question:
I was found unconscious on a park bench early in the morning in January. The temperature outside was about -4.0°C (25°F). At the time, I was barefoot and only wearing sweatpants, a tee-shirt, and a light coat. I do not have any recollection of how I ended up there. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were recorded: my heart rate was 45 beats per minute, my blood pressure was 100/70 mm Hg, and my respiratory rate was 10 breaths per minute. My core body temperature was noted to be 30.0°C (85.5°F). 

Medical staff observed that my feet and palms had clear blisters, and my skin appeared yellow with a waxy texture. Additionally, the tissues were swollen. Despite their attempts, I was unresponsive to auditory stimuli. The medical team was likely considering the nature of my condition and possible cold-associated injuries based on these findings.
options: A. Frostnip B. Pernio C. Immersion foot D. Frostbite E. Trench foot

question:
I am a 35-year-old who was involved in a bicycle accident with a motor vehicle. After the collision, I briefly lost consciousness from hitting the side of my head on the road. A few minutes later, I regained consciousness and attempted to continue riding my bicycle. However, I soon developed a severe headache accompanied by nausea and vomiting, which prompted me to call for emergency medical services.

Once I arrived at the hospital, I was confused and unable to provide a clear medical history. My condition worsened, and I quickly lost consciousness again. During my time in the hospital, a CT scan was performed to assess my injuries.
options: A. Subarachnoid hemorrhage B. Subdural hematoma C. Epidural hematoma D. Subgaleal hematoma E. Caput succedaneum

question:
I am an 11-year-old girl, and recently my parents brought me to the clinic because they were worried about my behavior. Over the past several months, I have been acting differently. I find myself spending hours combing the hair of my toy dolls and counting my steps as I move around the house. When my parents ask me about these activities, I often get very upset and start to cry.

I have no significant medical history, and my vital signs were reported as normal during the check-up. The doctor examined me and noted that I am a well-nourished girl and not in any acute distress. Although I occasionally experience some motor tics, the rest of the physical examination did not reveal any other issues. My mother mentioned that she has needed close medical follow-up in the past, but she chose not to provide more details. My parents are concerned, and I sense their distress about my recent behaviors.
options: A. Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) B. Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) C. Obsessive compulsive disorder (OCD) D. Tourette's syndrome E. Major depressive disorder (MDD)

question:
I am a 30-year-old man who recently emigrated from Southeast Asia. For the past six months, I have been experiencing heartburn and a persistent bad taste in my mouth. These symptoms have noticeably worsened at night. The pain I feel is moderate to severe, characterized by a burning sensation, and is localized to my epigastric region.

About a month ago, I underwent testing for Helicobacter pylori in my home country and completed a course of multiple antibiotics as a treatment. Unfortunately, despite this intervention, I have not seen any improvement in my symptoms. I find this ongoing discomfort quite troubling and am seeking further understanding of my condition.
options: A. Gastric MALT (mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue) lymphoma B. Gastric adenocarcinoma C. Duodenal ulcer disease D. Peptic ulcer disease E. Gastroesophageal reflux disease

question:
I am a 51-year-old man who recently experienced an episode of syncope while I was at a local farmer's market. While I was picking out produce, I suddenly fainted. Fortunately, I quickly regained my usual mental state and did not hit my head during the fall. 

I have a medical history that includes diabetes and hypertension, but I am not currently on any medications for these conditions. When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was 97.5°F, my blood pressure was recorded at 173/101 mmHg, my pulse was 82 beats per minute, my respirations were 14 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was measured at 98% while breathing room air.

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted that my breath sounds were clear and an S4 heart sound was present. Additionally, a rectal examination revealed a firm and nodular prostate, which was non-tender. A fecal occult sample was taken, and it tested negative for blood. 

I am now awaiting further evaluation to determine the cause of my syncope and the implications of my symptoms.
options: A. Benign prostatic hyperplasia B. Normal physical exam C. Prostate abscess D. Prostate cancer E. Prostatitis

question:
I was 19 years old when I was taken to the emergency department by ambulance due to unusual behavior that began three hours earlier at a party. I have a history of major depressive disorder and seasonal allergies, and my mother has a history of anxiety. On weekends, I typically drink about five beers. At the time, I was taking amitriptyline and diphenhydramine.

Upon arrival, I was not responding to questions and kept saying, "The government is following me everywhere." My vital signs showed a temperature of 37.9°C, a pulse of 115 beats per minute, respirations at 24 per minute, and a blood pressure of 160/89 mm Hg. I was sweating profusely and appeared disoriented, unable to recognize where I was or what time it was. During the neurologic examination, it was noted that my pupils were dilated, and I exhibited hyperreflexia. My feet felt cold, and the capillary refill time was noted to be three seconds.

At one point, I became agitated, screaming and attempting to bite the physician. A urine toxicology screening was conducted, which tested positive for ethyl glucuronide. This experience was distressing and confusing for me, and I was unable to understand what was happening.
options: A. Brief psychotic disorder B. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome C. Anticholinergic toxicity D. Delirium tremens E. Lysergic acid diethylamide intoxication F. Synthetic cathinone intoxication

question: Two days after I gave birth to my son at home, I noticed that he was experiencing bilious vomiting. He seemed unable to pass meconium, and I observed that his abdomen was distended. Concerned about his condition, I decided to take him to the pediatric emergency room for evaluation. The medical team conducted an endoscopic biopsy of his proximal colon. This procedure revealed an absence of Meissner’s and Auerbach’s plexi in the bowel wall. After the examination, I learned that this information would help in determining the most likely diagnosis for my son’s symptoms.
options: A. Hirschsprung’s disease B. Ileocecal intussusception C. Meckel’s diverticulum D. Juvenile polyposis syndrome E. Volvulus of the sigmoid colon

question:
I am a 24-year-old woman who went to the emergency department due to a severe headache. The pain was at an intensity of 10 out of 10 and became worse when I chewed. I described the sensation as a dull pain located on the sides of my head. 

I am generally healthy and am not currently taking any medications. During the examination, my temperature was recorded at 97.0°F, blood pressure was 111/74 mmHg, my pulse was 83 beats per minute, my respirations were 13 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air. 

The physical exam revealed pain and tenderness in the mandibular and temporal regions, which intensified when I opened and closed my mouth.
options: A. Migraine headache B. Subarachnoid hemorrhage C. Temporal arteritis D. Temporomandibular joint dysfunction E. Tension headache

question:
I am a 31-year-old woman, and I recently visited my gynecologist for a routine well-visit. During the appointment, I discussed my sexual activity, as I am currently active with multiple male partners. For contraception, I use an intrauterine device. 

I mentioned that my last menstrual period occurred two weeks ago, and I did not report any abnormal vaginal discharge or sensations of burning or itching. The pelvic exam conducted during the visit was normal. However, the routine Pap smear taken during this appointment indicated some abnormalities. 

My gynecologist noted the findings and mentioned that they would evaluate the results further to determine the most likely organism responsible for the abnormal Pap smear. I am awaiting additional information regarding the next steps in addressing the results.
options: A. Treponema pallidum B. Chlamydia trachomatis C. Herpes simplex virus 1 D. Human papillomavirus E. Trichomonas vaginalis

question:
I am a 60-year-old man with a history of osteoarthritis, and I have been waiting for hip replacement surgery for three years. During my recent annual physical, I discussed my ongoing struggles with pain management. Despite taking over-the-counter pain medications, I still experience constant pain that is not alleviated by any analgesics. 

As part of my examination, my doctor assessed my renal function, which has shown deterioration compared to my last visit two years ago. I learned that my serum creatinine level is at 2.0 mg/dL, and a urinalysis indicated 1+ proteinuria, though there were no abnormalities seen under microscopy of the urine. Following this, I underwent a renal biopsy, which revealed eosinophilic infiltration and diffuse parenchymal inflammation. 

I am aware that these findings suggest a significant issue with my renal function, and I am seeking to understand the most likely explanation for this deterioration.
options: A. Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis B. Ischemic acute tubular necrosis C. Nephrotoxic acute tubular necrosis D. Toxic tubulointerstitial nephritis E. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis

question:
I am a 54-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to abdominal distension that had persisted for the past three weeks. Along with the distension, I experienced generalized abdominal discomfort, nausea, and a decreased appetite. 

Three months ago, I had undergone an inguinal hernia repair, which did not result in any complications. My medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, congestive heart failure, and untreated hepatitis C. At the time of my visit, I was taking several medications, including aspirin, atorvastatin, metoprolol, lisinopril, and metformin. 

I have a family history of alcoholic liver disease, my father having been affected. I smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 30 years but quit five years ago. I also consumed 3 to 4 beers daily. During the examination, I appeared cachectic, but my vital signs were within normal limits. 

The physical examination revealed a distended abdomen with shifting dullness, yet there was no tenderness or palpable masses. There was a well-healed surgical scar from my previous procedure, and I had mild bilateral lower extremity nonpitting edema. Following this, a diagnostic paracentesis was performed to analyze the fluid. 

At this point, I await further results to determine the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Recent surgery B. Lymphoma C. Infection with M. tuberculosis D. Liver cirrhosis E. Infection with gram-positive bacteria F. Nephrotic syndrome G. Acute decompensated heart failure

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who recently visited my primary care provider for a checkup. Three months ago, blood work had shown that I had lymphocytosis. During this visit, I mentioned that I have been feeling a bit more tired than usual, although I did not report any other symptoms. My medical history includes hypertension and hyperlipidemia, for which I take lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide, and atorvastatin. Three years ago, I underwent a hip replacement due to osteoarthritis. 

I do not have any significant family history of medical issues, and I drink alcohol socially but do not smoke. During the examination, my heart rate was 95 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 17 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure measured 135 over 85 mm Hg. My temperature was within normal limits at 36.8°C (98.2°F). Overall, I appeared well during the physical exam. My heartbeat had a regular rate and rhythm, and my lungs were clear. However, there was mild lymphadenopathy noted in my cervical lymph nodes. 

A complete blood count was performed, and I was informed that a specimen would be sent for flow cytometry analysis, which revealed a certain population that was CD 5, 19, 20, and 23 positive.
options: A. Aplastic anemia B. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia C. Tuberculosis D. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia E. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura

question:
I am a 32-year-old woman, currently 35 weeks pregnant with my second child. I was admitted to the hospital about an hour after my membranes spontaneously ruptured. For the past day, I had been experiencing mild abdominal discomfort and nausea. My pregnancy has been complicated by gestational diabetes, which I manage with a strict diet.

I previously delivered my first child via a lower segment transverse cesarean section due to placental abruption. At the hospital, I was given iron and vitamin supplements, and I confirmed that my immunizations are current. Upon arrival, my temperature was recorded at 38.6°C, my pulse was 122 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/78 mm Hg. 

During the abdominal examination, I was found to have severe tenderness throughout my lower quadrants. A speculum examination confirmed the rupture of membranes, with a drainage of malodorous, blood-tinged fluid. An ultrasound showed that the fetus was in a cephalic presentation, with a fetal heart rate of 175 beats per minute, which was reactive and showed no decelerations. 

These findings were concerning and indicated that I was experiencing complications related to my pregnancy.
options:
A. Influenza B. Chorioamnionitis C. Acute appendicitis D. Normal labor E. Acute pyelonephritis F. Uterine rupture
"

question:
I am a 52-year-old man who recently experienced a concerning health issue. Five weeks ago, I noticed multiple ulcers developing on my left forearm and neck after returning from a two-month stay in rural Peru. At the time, I did not recall any trauma or insect bites that might have caused these lesions. 

Initially, the lesions appeared as non-itchy red papules, which gradually enlarged and ulcerated, eventually forming crusts. During this period, I did not experience any fever or abdominal pain. Since my marriage at 24, I have been sexually active with a single partner.

When I sought medical attention, a physical examination revealed the lesions to be erythematous, crusted plaques with central ulcerations and raised borders. There were no signs of fluctuance, drainage, or sporotrichoid spread. To better understand the condition, a punch biopsy was performed. The results indicated an ulcerated lesion with a mixed inflammatory infiltrate and showed amastigotes within dermal macrophages when stained with Giemsa. 

I am now awaiting further information regarding the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Histoplasmosis B. Cutaneous leishmaniasis C. Ecthyma D. Syphilis E. Cutaneous tuberculosis

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who recently found myself in the emergency department due to severe chest pain. For the past several days, I had been feeling unwell, experiencing lower back pain, chest pain, discomfort when swallowing, a persistent cough, and what I believed to be a fever. A few weeks prior, I had dental pain, which I had been managing by drinking alcohol.

Upon my arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 104°F, my blood pressure was 114/64 mmHg, my pulse was at 120 beats per minute, and my respirations were 22 per minute. My oxygen saturation level was 92% on room air. During the examination, the doctor noted erythema in my submandibular area and detected a coarse, rasping sound when listening to my heart.

I underwent a CT scan of my chest and an ECG to further investigate my symptoms. The medical team also took some blood tests to assess my condition. While I do not have specific lab results to share, I was informed that my health situation required careful attention and further evaluation.
options: A. Esophageal rupture B. Ludwig angina C. Mediastinitis D. Myocardial infarction E. Pulmonary embolism

question:
I am a 7-year-old girl who recently visited the emergency department with my mother due to swelling around my left eye. It all started yesterday morning when I woke up and noticed a painful, warm lump on my left eyelid. The lump felt soft to the touch, and although it was uncomfortable, moving my eye did not make the pain worse. 

During the examination, the doctor observed that my upper left eyelid was red and swollen, and it looked like the hair follicles in that area were affected. When the doctor gently pressed on the swollen area, some pus drained from it. The doctor mentioned they would consider what might be causing these symptoms.
options: A. Hordeolum B. Dacryocystitis C. Blepharitis D. Xanthelasma E. Chalazion

question: I am a 17-year-old African-American male, and I visited my family physician recently because I noticed red-tinged urine about a week ago. This change occurred while I was dealing with a cold. I mentioned to my doctor that I had experienced this issue before. My father accompanied me to the appointment, and he noted that he has had similar occurrences at times as well. During the visit, we discussed my symptoms and the history of this condition in our family.
options: A. Acute cystitis B. Acute interstitial nephritis C. Sickle cell trait D. Acute glomerulonephritis E. Hemophilia

question:
I recently visited the doctor because I had been experiencing extreme fatigue for the past two days. Additionally, I noticed that my skin appeared yellow, which concerned me. I didn’t have any other symptoms, as I did not experience fever or headache. I mentioned to the doctor that I had used illicit intravenous drugs in the past. 

I moved from Africa to the United States when I was 18, and I realized I did not have any immunization records. During the visit, my vital signs were taken: my heart rate was 72 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 14 breaths per minute, my temperature was 37.9°C (100.2°F), and my blood pressure was 100/74 mm Hg. The physical examination was mostly unremarkable, except for some mild diffuse tenderness in my abdomen.

The doctor ordered routine blood tests, which revealed significantly elevated alanine aminotransferase levels. Additionally, a hepatitis viral panel was conducted. The results indicated that I was positive for HBsAg and IgM anti-HBc, while the other tests for hepatitis A, C, and D were negative. Based on these findings, the doctor discussed the likely diagnosis with me.
options: A. Past hepatitis B infection B. Chronic hepatitis B C. Acute hepatitis A D. Acute hepatitis D superinfection E. Acute hepatitis B

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who was recently brought to the emergency department after experiencing syncope. It all started suddenly while I was carrying my groceries to the car; I felt palpitations and then lost consciousness. I don’t remember anything else from that moment. I did not experience any chest pain or dizziness prior to the event. 

My medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, gastroparesis, and osteoarthritis of the knees. I take several medications, including lisinopril, metformin, and ondansetron as needed for nausea. Additionally, I take methadone daily for chronic pain. 

Upon examination, I had an abrasion on my forehead, but otherwise, I appeared well. My temperature was measured at 37.2 °C (98.9 F), my heart rate was 104 beats per minute and regular, and my blood pressure was 135/70 mm Hg. While I was in the emergency department, I lost consciousness again. The telemetry monitoring showed I was experiencing polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with cyclic changes in the QRS axis, which resolved on its own after about 30 seconds. 

Blood tests, including a complete blood count, serum electrolytes, and thyroid studies, came back normal, as did my cardiac enzymes. I am now seeking to understand the likely underlying cause of my syncope.
options:
A. Prolonged QT interval B. Acute myocardial ischemia C. Shortened PR interval D. Fast accessory conduction pathway E. Prinzmetal angina F. Brugada syndrome G. Hypomagnesemia
"

question:
I am a 60-year-old female who recently went to the emergency department due to severe pain and vision loss in my left eye. The symptoms began suddenly while I was driving through a dark tunnel, which was an unusual experience for me. I had never encountered anything like this before and did not have any prior issues with my eyes. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, the medical staff assessed my left eye, which was poorly responsive to light and felt hard to the touch. The pain was intense and concerning, and I was anxious about the sudden changes in my vision. The situation was alarming, as I had no previous history of ophthalmologic problems. I hoped to find out what was causing these troubling symptoms and to receive the appropriate care.
options: A. Open angle glaucoma B. Closed angle glaucoma C. Cataract D. Central retinal artery occlusion E. Central retinal vein occlusion

question:
I am a 35-year-old woman who recently experienced an upper respiratory infection. I went to the emergency department due to a concerning set of symptoms. Initially, I felt a burning sensation in my toes, which was accompanied by numbness. Over the past few days, I noticed increasing weakness in my lower limbs, and this weakness began to extend to my arms and face. At this point, I find it difficult to get up from a chair without assistance.

When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F). My blood pressure was 145/89 mm Hg, my heart rate was 99 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 12 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation was at 95% while breathing room air. During the physical examination, the doctor noted diminished breath sounds in both lung fields and observed that my inspiratory effort was noticeably poor. Additionally, when my lower abdomen was palpated, they found a palpable bladder. In terms of strength, I was assessed to be 3 out of 5 in my lower extremities bilaterally, although my sensation remained intact.
options: A. Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis B. Adrenoleukodystrophy C. Guillain-Barré syndrome D. Multiple sclerosis E. Myasthenia Gravis

question:
I am an 82-year-old woman who recently sought treatment in the emergency department due to severe pain in my right flank and a fever that had persisted for the past two days. I was also experiencing difficulties with urination. My medical history has been generally unremarkable.

Upon my arrival, the medical team conducted a urinalysis, which indicated the presence of leukocytes and gram-negative bacilli. To further investigate the cause of my symptoms, I underwent a contrast computed tomography scan of my abdomen. The results revealed a large mass in the retroperitoneal area that was compressing my right ureter, leading to hydronephrosis in my right kidney.

Following this diagnosis, the medical team excised the mass. They then performed a histopathologic evaluation to determine its nature. The findings indicated that the mass was malignant. I am now awaiting further information about the diagnosis and the next steps in my treatment plan.
options: A. Liposarcoma B. Lipoma C. Rhabdomyosarcoma D. Teratoma E. Leiomyosarcoma

question:
I am a 22-year-old male who arrived at the emergency department after being involved in a motor vehicle accident. I was conscious and able to communicate with the hospital staff, although I was in significant pain and had various bruises and scrapes on my body. I had been driving when a head-on collision occurred.

Upon evaluation, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, with a pulse rate of 112 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 120/70 mmHg. My breathing rate was 18 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 99% while on room air. The medical team performed a full trauma assessment, during which they noted that I had no strength (0/5) in my right upper extremity, particularly in extending my wrist.

I was started on IV fluids and given morphine for pain relief. Radiography was ordered to further evaluate my condition. During the assessment, the medical team noted bilateral breath sounds, a normal heart rhythm, and no signs of jugular venous distension. Approximately 30 minutes later, my blood pressure was measured again and recorded at 122/70 mmHg.
options: A. Humeral neck B. Midshaft humerus C. Supracondylar D. Ulnar E. Radial

question:
I am a 4-year-old girl who was taken to the emergency department after experiencing persistent vomiting and abdominal pain. My parents discovered that I was unwell when they returned home to find me in this state while I had been under the care of a babysitter. I have been healthy overall, but my family has a history of various medical issues, including depression, diabetes, and cancer.

Upon arrival at the hospital, I was minimally responsive and confused. My temperature was recorded at 100°F, and my vital signs showed a pulse of 140 beats per minute and respirations at 22 breaths per minute. I was vomiting, and the contents were bloody. The medical staff conducted a physical examination and ordered laboratory studies to investigate my condition.

During the examination, the doctors noted that there were a few radiopaque objects visible in my stomach through radiography. I was undergoing further testing, including urine and serum toxicology, to determine the cause of my symptoms and any possible intoxication.
options: A. Acetaminophen B. Aspirin C. Iron D. Lead E. Nortriptyline

question:
I am a 45-year-old African-American woman who recently experienced some troubling symptoms. I noticed I had difficulty breathing, along with a persistent cough and chest pain that was non-radiating. The pain seemed to ease when I leaned forward, but it intensified when I leaned backward. During a medical examination, the doctor listened to my chest and noted a scratchy rub that was most prominent when I was leaning forward. 

The examination did not indicate any signs of Kussmaul's sign, pulsus paradoxus, or a pericardial knock, which are all terms I learned during the visit. Although I was unsure about what was happening, the doctor explained that my symptoms pointed towards a specific condition. I left the appointment with a better understanding of my situation and felt reassured that we were working toward a diagnosis.
options: A. Cardiac tamponade B. Constrictive pericarditis C. Acute pericarditis D. Libman-Sacks endocarditis E. Acute myocardial infarction

question:
I am a 65-year-old woman who recently visited the clinic for a routine checkup. During this visit, I mentioned that I had unintentionally lost 4.5 kg (9.9 lb) over the past month, although I did not report any other health complaints. 

The healthcare provider measured my vital signs: my pulse rate was 90 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 18 breaths per minute, my temperature was 37.0°C (98.6°F), and my blood pressure was 150/70 mm Hg. During the examination, they noted an irregularly irregular rhythm in my heart. 

Upon further examination of my neck, the provider observed that my thyroid was markedly enlarged, but there were no signs of lymphadenopathy or bruit. 

Based on these findings, the provider discussed the possibility of a thyroid condition, though specific laboratory tests, including thyroid-stimulating hormone levels and T4 levels, as well as imaging studies, would be needed for a definitive diagnosis. While I was not aware of the specific tests results or their implications at the time, I understood that my symptoms and examination findings were concerning enough to warrant further investigation.
options: A. Graves’ disease B. Hashimoto’s thyroiditis C. Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis D. Toxic adenoma E. Toxic multinodular goiter

question:
I am a 64-year-old male who recently visited my primary care physician due to pain in my left knee. The pain began suddenly last evening, and I also noticed redness in the skin around the joint. I did not experience any injury or engage in activities that might have caused this discomfort.

Two months prior, I had a similar episode with my right knee, but I chose not to seek medical treatment at that time. That pain resolved after about five days. During my recent examination, the doctor found that my left knee was warm to the touch, erythematous, and extremely tender when pressed. I experienced limited range of motion in both flexion and extension due to pain, and there was a noticeable crepitus with passive movement of the joint. 

My vital signs were within normal limits, and I was not running a fever. The doctor recommended aspiration of the left knee joint, which was scheduled for further evaluation.
options: A. Decreased serum calcium levels and elevated phosphate levels B. Autoimmune destruction of pancreatic islet cells and elevated blood glucose levels C. Insulin insensitivity and elevated blood glucose levels D. Bronzing of the skin and elevated blood glucose levels E. Kayser-Fleischer rings and decreased serum ceruloplasmin

question:
I am a 78-year-old man who began experiencing fatigue and shortness of breath during physical activities about four weeks ago. These symptoms gradually developed and have not improved since their onset. I have no previous history of anemia or nutritional deficiencies. 

Six months ago, I had a significant medical event—a ST-elevation myocardial infarction—after which I underwent coronary artery bypass graft surgery. This was complicated by recurrent episodes of unstable ventricular tachycardia. Currently, I take several medications, including rosuvastatin, aspirin, and amiodarone.

At my recent check-up, my blood pressure was measured at 100/70 mm Hg, my pulse was 71 beats per minute, and my temperature was 36.5°C (97.7°F). During the physical examination, I appeared lethargic and tired. My skin was noted to be dry and coarse, and there was noticeable generalized pitting edema.

Further evaluations indicated the presence of normochromic, normocytic anemia, along with decreased serum iron levels, decreased total iron-binding capacity, and increased serum ferritin levels. I am currently awaiting further assessment to determine the most likely cause of my anemia.
options: A. Iron deficiency anemia B. Hemolytic anemia C. Anemia of chronic disease D. Pernicious anemia E. Thalassemia

question:
I am a 45-year-old female who recently went to the emergency department because I was experiencing gross hematuria and acute, colicky flank pain. I had never had any prior episodes of hematuria. Over the past several weeks, I had been taking high doses of acetaminophen and aspirin to manage persistent upper back pain. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my blood pressure and temperature were within normal limits. However, during the examination, the doctors found that I had proteinuria. They conducted a physical examination, which did not reveal any palpable flank masses. 

At this point, I was uncertain about what was causing my symptoms, but I hoped to find answers and relief from the pain I was experiencing.
options: A. Diffuse cortical necrosis B. Chronic pyelonephritis C. Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease D. Papillary necrosis E. Acute Nephrolithiasis

question:
I was admitted to the hospital four days after undergoing coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG) due to a myocardial infarction (MI). I am 68 years old and have a history of insulin-controlled diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia. 

Initially, after the surgery, I experienced a resolution of my chest pain, which was a relief. However, I began to have chest pain again that felt different from what I had before. I noticed that the pain worsened when I took deep breaths but seemed to lessen when I leaned forward. In contrast, lying flat made the pain more uncomfortable.

During my examination, the medical team checked my vital signs, which were within normal limits. They also listened to my heart and found no murmurs. I was informed that my CK-mB levels came back normal, and a repeat electrocardiogram (ECG) was performed, the results of which were reviewed by the doctors.

I am awaiting further assessment to determine the cause of this new chest pain and what steps will be taken next in my treatment plan.
options: A. Ventricular aneurysm B. Ventricular septal rupture C. Papillary muscle rupture D. Acute pericarditis E. Dressler's syndrome

question:
I am a 35-year-old lawyer. Recently, I experienced a sudden onset of vision loss, which prompted my coworkers to bring me to the emergency department. This incident followed a challenging week in which I lost three cases. The day before my vision loss, I noticed weakness and paralysis in my left wrist, which was concerning to me.

In the emergency department, I underwent a physical examination. The doctors noted that my reflexes were somewhat diminished, rated at 2 out of 4, but my muscular strength in all extremities was normal, rated at 5 out of 5. During the evaluation, I felt indifferent to my situation and exhibited a flat affect. Fortunately, I did not experience slurring of my words.

To further investigate my condition, the medical team conducted a CT scan without contrast and an MRI of my brain. Both imaging results appeared unremarkable, leaving the doctors to consider potential diagnoses. At this point, I remain focused on understanding the cause of my symptoms and what steps may be necessary for my recovery.
options: A. Factitious disorder B. Transient ischemic attack C. Somatization disorder D. Major depressive disorder E. Conversion disorder

question:
I am a 53-year-old woman who recently experienced a sudden onset of respiratory distress that lasted for several hours. I have a medical history that includes a myocardial infarction two years ago. When I visited my physician, my vital signs were recorded: my blood pressure was 70/40 mm Hg, my pulse was 92 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 28 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation level was 92% while breathing room air.

During the physical examination, the doctor noted bilateral basal crepitations when listening to my lungs. An echocardiogram was performed, which showed that my ejection fraction was 34%. Following this evaluation, I was admitted to the medical floor and started on furosemide. Over the next 24 hours, I produced 400 mL of urine. 

Subsequent tests indicated that my blood urea nitrogen level was 45 mg/dL, and my serum creatinine level was 1.85 mg/dL. The fractional excretion of sodium was measured at 0.89%, and a urinalysis revealed muddy brown granular casts. I am now awaiting further evaluation of these findings and their implications for my condition.
options: A. Acute glomerulonephritis B. Chronic kidney disease C. Acute pyelonephritis D. Acute interstitial nephritis E. Acute tubular necrosis

question:
I am a 56-year-old man who recently visited my physician due to a worsening pain in my left buttock that has persisted for two months. The pain is a deep, dull ache, and I’ve noticed it intensifies at night. I haven't experienced any recent trauma that could explain the discomfort. 

I have a history of hyperlipidemia and have been a smoker for the past 30 years, consuming about one pack of cigarettes daily. I also drink one beer each night, but I do not use illicit drugs. My only medication is simvastatin. 

During my physical examination, the doctor noted tenderness in the left gluteal region, but the neurological assessment did not reveal any focal findings. An x-ray of my pelvis showed a 4-cm, poorly defined, osteolytic lesion in the left ilium, characterized by a moth-eaten pattern of bone destruction and multiple well-defined sclerotic lesions, along with an aggressive periosteal reaction. The rest of the physical examination, including a rectal exam, showed no abnormalities. Additionally, a chest x-ray and abdominal ultrasonography did not show any issues. Based on these findings, the physician is considering a likely diagnosis.
options: A. Osteosarcoma B. Giant cell tumor C. Fibrosarcoma D. Plasmacytoma E. Ewing sarcoma F. Osteochondroma G. Chondrosarcoma

question:
I am 21 years old and recently my roommate brought me to the emergency department because she was concerned about my behavior over the past 10 days. She noticed I had been acting strangely, moving and talking on the phone at all hours of the night. I was only sleeping about one to two hours each night, and I spent hours pacing up and down our apartment, often talking about my plans to "save the world." 

I was speaking very quickly, and when my roommate asked if I felt anything was wrong, I denied it. I mentioned that I had made great progress on my plans. I recalled experiencing similar feelings about two years ago, which led to a hospitalization for about two weeks. 

Although I have never been diagnosed with depression, I did have a period last year where I struggled with low energy and motivation, making it difficult for me to attend class or see friends. I do not hear voices or see visual hallucinations. My roommate's concern prompted this visit, and I am now evaluating my current state and its implications.
options: A. Schizoaffective disorder B. Major depressive disorder C. Bipolar I disorder D. Bipolar II disorder E. Dysthymic disorder

question:
I am a 40-year-old male who was involved in a motorcycle accident and subsequently presented to the emergency room. Upon my arrival, I experienced a significant drop in blood pressure, measured at 70/50 mmHg, and my heart rate was elevated at 130 bpm. During my hospitalization, I developed oliguria, which is a condition characterized by reduced urine output. 

Throughout my stay, medical staff conducted various urine studies to assess my kidney function. After receiving treatment, I was eventually discharged from the hospital with my renal function restored. The medical team identified the underlying issues that contributed to my kidney problems during my recovery.
options: A. Acute pyelonephritis B. Diabetic glomerulopathy C. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis D. Acute tubular necrosis E. Membranous glomerulonephritis

question:
I am a 17-year-old girl who visited the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain that had persisted for five days. The pain was cramping in nature, and I also experienced nausea and vomiting. Additionally, I felt discomfort while urinating. I am sexually active with one male partner, and we have not always used condoms consistently. Three days prior to my visit, I experienced a burning sensation during intercourse.

My menstrual cycle is regular, occurring every 28 days and lasting for five days. My last period started three weeks ago. During the examination, my temperature was recorded at 38.5°C (101.3°F), my pulse was 83 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/70 mm Hg. The physical examination revealed tenderness in my lower abdominal quadrants. A pelvic examination indicated cervical motion tenderness and a purulent discharge from the cervix.

These symptoms prompted the medical staff to consider potential diagnoses, given the combination of abdominal pain, urinary discomfort, and other findings.
options: A. Pyelonephritis B. Ectopic pregnancy C. Ovarian cyst rupture D. Appendicitis E. Vulvovaginitis F. Cystitis G. Pelvic inflammatory disease

question:
I am a 65-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department after experiencing distressing symptoms at my nursing home. I coughed up large amounts of blood-tinged sputum, which prompted immediate medical attention. Recently, I had been treated for an upper respiratory tract infection with antibiotics. My history includes a long-standing productive cough that has worsened since I had a stroke three years ago. 

Before my stroke, I was a daily smoker, consuming a pack of cigarettes for 40 years. I quit smoking after the stroke. Upon arrival at the emergency department, I felt short of breath and appeared visibly distressed. My vital signs indicated a temperature of 38°C (100.4°F), a pulse rate of 92 beats per minute, and a blood pressure reading of 145/85 mm Hg. A pulse oximetry test showed my oxygen saturation was at 92% while breathing room air. 

During the physical examination, the doctor noted digital clubbing and cyanosis of my lips. I was also found to have coarse crackles in my chest upon auscultation. An x-ray of my chest was performed, revealing increased translucency and tram-track opacities in the right lower lung field.
options:
A. Bronchiectasis B. Chronic bronchitis C. Aspiration pneumonia D. Emphysema E. Pulmonary embolism F. Lung cancer
"

question:
I am a 6-year-old boy who was taken to the physician because I had a headache, cough, runny nose, and a low-grade fever. These symptoms started when I woke up that morning.
