Until then, I had been healthy, except for a urinary tract infection that I had a week ago, which was treated with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and has since resolved. 

Both my parents have a history of allergic rhinitis, which might be relevant. When I arrived at the doctor’s office, my temperature was measured at 37.8°C (100°F). During the physical examination, the doctor noted that I had a runny nose and tenderness around my forehead and cheeks, indicating possible sinus involvement. Additionally, I had swollen lymph nodes in my neck. 

The doctor performed some laboratory studies, but I am not aware of the results. My symptoms and the findings led to a discussion about what could be causing my condition. The physician considered various possibilities based on my symptoms and medical history.
options: A. Primary autoimmune neutropenia B. Folate deficiency C. Medication side effect D. Acute lymphocytic leukemia E. CMV infection F. EBV infection G. Acute myelogenous leukemia

question:
I am a 45-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to a painful mass on the right side of my neck. This mass has been present for about a week and has gradually increased in size, becoming more painful when I touch it. Along with the mass, I have experienced night sweats, unintentional weight loss, and episodes of diarrhea. 

A few weeks prior, I had a minor cold, but since then, I haven’t noticed any other significant symptoms. During my visit, the medical staff recorded my temperature, which was 100°F, and my blood pressure was measured at 122/80 mmHg. My pulse was notably elevated at 160 beats per minute, while my respirations were 19 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was stable at 100% on room air.

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted that my thyroid was diffusely enlarged and tender to the touch. An ECG was performed as part of the assessment. I am awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely cause of these symptoms and the appropriate diagnosis.
options: A. Graves disease B. Hashimoto thyroiditis C. Riedel thyroiditis D. Silent thyroiditis E. Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis

question:
I am 23 years old and have one child. Recently, I went to the emergency department due to severe lower abdominal pain that began several hours earlier. Over the past two days, I had been experiencing fever, malaise, and nausea. My last menstrual period was three weeks ago, and my medical history is otherwise unremarkable. 

In the past month, I had three sexual partners and have been using oral contraception. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 38.8°C (101.8°F), and my blood pressure was 120/75 mm Hg. During the physical examination, the doctor noted tenderness in my lower abdominal quadrants, as well as uterine and adnexal tenderness. 

A urine test showed that I was not pregnant. During a speculum examination, the doctor observed inflammation of the cervix, along with motion tenderness and a yellow-white purulent discharge. Based on these findings, I understand that there is a concern for a specific diagnosis related to my symptoms.
options: A. Vaginitis B. Cervicitis C. Pelvic inflammatory disease D. Ruptured ectopic pregnancy E. Urinary tract infection

question:
I am a 21-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency room due to pain in my right arm and limited range of motion. I couldn't recall any specific trauma to the arm that might have caused the pain. Alongside this discomfort, I experienced diarrhea and nausea. 

In addition to these symptoms, I have been sexually active with one male partner and noticed that I experience pain during intercourse. During the examination, the doctor found vague tenderness when palpating my abdomen in all four quadrants, but there was no redness or swelling in my right arm. 

I also underwent a fecal occult test, which came back negative. It's worth mentioning that I have been to the emergency room seven times in the past year with similar symptoms, which has been a concerning pattern for me.
options: A. Ulcerative colitis B. Illness anxiety disorder C. Somatization disorder D. Somatoform pain disorder E. Conversion disorder

question:
I am a 33-year-old female who recently experienced painful urination accompanied by a fever and right flank pain. These symptoms started suddenly and became quite uncomfortable. Concerned about my health, I decided to seek medical attention.

During the evaluation, I underwent a urinary sediment analysis, which revealed the presence of white blood cell casts and Gram-negative bacteria. I have not started any new medications that might have contributed to these symptoms. 

Given the combination of my symptoms and the findings from the analysis, I am now awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Pelvic Inflammatory Disease B. Acute Interstitial Nephritis C. Pyelonephritis D. Cystitis E. Appendicitis

question:
I am a 74-year-old woman who was brought to the emergency department due to a two-week history of increasing weakness and chills. For the past three days, I have also been experiencing difficulty breathing. Eight weeks ago, I underwent a left hemicolectomy for adenocarcinoma of the colon. Following that surgery, I developed a severe urinary tract infection, which required a four-day stay in the intensive care unit. I was discharged from the hospital three weeks ago.

I have a medical history that includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, osteoporosis with lumbar pain, hypertension, and atrial fibrillation. I have been a smoker for 50 years, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily, and I do not drink alcohol or use illicit drugs. My current medications include warfarin, metformin, lisinopril, and aspirin. 

Upon examination, I appeared lethargic and had a large conjunctival hemorrhage in my left eye. My vital signs indicated a temperature of 39.3°C (102.7°F), a pulse of 112 beats per minute, and respirations at 25 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was recorded at 126/79 mm Hg. The cardiac examination revealed a new holosystolic murmur over the apex, and my abdominal examination showed mild tenderness throughout the upper quadrants, along with a well-healed 12-cm paramedian scar. Additionally, there were multiple tender nodules on the palmar surfaces of my fingertips, and a funduscopic examination revealed retinal hemorrhages. An ECG indicated atrial fibrillation and right bundle branch block.
options: A. Pulmonary metastases B. Streptococcus sanguinis infection C. Cardiobacterium hominis infection D. Nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis E. Aspergillus fumigatus infection F. Enterococcus faecalis infection

question:
I am a 58-year-old man with type 2 diabetes mellitus. Recently, I visited the emergency department due to experiencing difficulty swallowing and swelling in my neck and lower jaw for the past two days. Over the previous week, I had been dealing with tooth pain on the left side, which significantly affected my sleep.

About four weeks ago, I had a brief episode of flu-like symptoms, including a sore throat, which resolved without any treatment. I also have a history of hypertension and currently take metformin and lisinopril. 

Upon my arrival at the emergency department, I felt quite distressed. I am 180 cm tall and weigh 100 kg, giving me a BMI of 31.6. My temperature was recorded at 38.4°C, my pulse was 90 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/80 mm Hg.

During the oral examination, the physician noted a decayed lower left third molar with pus drainage. There was tenderness and swelling in my submandibular area and the anterior neck. A fingerstick test indicated my blood glucose concentration was at 250 mg/dL.
options:
A. Angioedema B. Lymphadenitis C. Peritonsillar abscess D. Sublingual hematoma E. Ludwig angina
"

question: I am a 48-year-old man who experienced a stab wound to my chest, which required treatment in the emergency department. After receiving care, I noticed that three months later, a firm nodular mass developed over the site of the original wound. This mass measured approximately 4 x 3 cm and had intact epithelium. When I examined the scar, it felt firm and non-tender, and I observed that there was no redness or swelling in the surrounding area. Concerned about the mass, I decided to have it excised. Following the surgery, a microscopic examination was performed, which revealed the presence of fibroblasts and a significant amount of collagen within the tissue.
options: A. Foreign body response from suturing B. Poor wound healing from diabetes mellitus C. Keloid scar formation D. Staphylococcal wound infection E. Development of a fibrosarcoma

question:
I am a 20-year-old man who was previously healthy, but recently I experienced a series of troubling symptoms. Over the past week, my family noticed that my skin and eyes had developed a yellowish tint. I started feeling increasingly agitated, especially during the last 24 hours, which prompted my family to take me to the emergency department.

I occasionally use cocaine and ecstasy and drink alcohol on weekends, about 20 grams. I also acknowledge engaging in high-risk sexual behavior without using protection. Upon arrival at the hospital, the medical team conducted a physical examination. My heart rate was recorded at 94 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 13 breaths per minute. My temperature was normal at 37.0°C (98.6°F), and my blood pressure was 110/60 mm Hg.

During the examination, I exhibited signs of psychomotor agitation and was not oriented to time and space. The doctors noted asterixis, jaundice in my skin and mucous membranes, and some bleeding from my nose (epistaxis). The rest of the examination appeared normal. 

I am awaiting further evaluation to understand the underlying cause of my symptoms and to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Hemolytic uremic syndrome B. Alcoholic hepatitis C. Fulminant hepatic failure D. Ecstasy intoxication E. Cocaine-abstinence syndrome

question:
I am a 19-year-old woman who recently underwent a laparoscopic appendectomy due to acute appendicitis. During the surgery, the medical team observed that my liver appeared black and discolored. Aside from the appendicitis, I have had no significant health issues, do not take any medications, and I have no known medication allergies. I do not consume alcohol or use illicit drugs.

After the procedure, my recovery went smoothly without any complications. When I returned for a follow-up appointment three weeks later, my vital signs were normal. However, during the examination, the doctor noted that I had scleral icterus, which I mentioned has been present for many years, although I had not sought medical attention for it before. 

The abdominal examination revealed healing scars from the surgery, and there were no signs of drainage or redness. The healthcare team conducted some serum studies to assess my liver function and bilirubin levels. While I do not have the specific results, I recall that the tests indicated elevated bilirubin levels. This situation raises questions about my liver health, and I am eager to understand the implications of the findings and what might be the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Type II Crigler-Najjar syndrome B. Dubin-Johnson syndrome C. Gilbert syndrome D. Rotor syndrome E. Wilson disease

question:
I am a 22-year-old student who recently visited the college health clinic due to a week-long experience of fever, sore throat, nausea, and fatigue. This morning, I found it difficult to get out of bed. I do not have any pets at home. I also acknowledged having had unprotected sex recently.

During my visit, the medical staff took my vital signs, which indicated a temperature of 38.3°C (101.0°F), a pulse rate of 72 beats per minute, a blood pressure reading of 118/63 mm Hg, and a respiratory rate of 15 breaths per minute. The physical examination revealed bilateral posterior cervical lymphadenopathy and exudates on the palatine tonsils, accompanied by petechiae on the soft palate. Additionally, I had an erythematous macular rash on my trunk and arms, along with mild enlargement of the liver and spleen.

Given these symptoms and findings, I am seeking clarity on what might be the most likely diagnosis for my condition.
options: A. Rubella B. Acute HIV infection C. Toxoplasma infection D. Infectious mononucleosis E. Streptococcal pharyngitis

question:
I am a 42-year-old female who recently visited the emergency department due to experiencing severe abdominal pain and a fever for the past two days. I have a history of gallstones and was scheduled to undergo a cholecystectomy in two weeks. Upon arrival at the hospital, the medical staff conducted a physical examination, during which they noted tenderness in my abdomen, particularly in the epigastric region. However, there was no rebound tenderness or guarding observed. 

Additionally, I noticed that my skin appeared yellow, which I later learned is referred to as jaundice. The healthcare team performed various tests to assess my condition. They informed me that my white blood cell count was elevated, and my total bilirubin level was significantly high. The combination of my symptoms and examination findings led the medical team to consider a diagnosis related to my gallbladder issues.
options: A. Acute cholecystitis B. Acute pancreatitis C. Chronic pancreatitis D. Acute cholangitis E. Primary sclerosing cholangitis

question:
I am a 14-year-old boy who visited the office for a routine checkup. During the appointment, I was assessed for my overall health and development, and I was pleased to find that I am well-nourished and meeting all my developmental milestones. I had no complaints to report, and I received some counseling on various adolescent issues.

During the examination, the healthcare provider noted that I appeared to be a normal, healthy teenager. However, they observed bilateral swelling of my tibial tuberosities. When asked about this swelling, I explained that I had not experienced any trauma. I mentioned that the area feels sore, particularly when I run or squat. This discomfort has been a concern for me, but I had not associated it with any specific injury. Overall, the visit was informative, and I appreciated the opportunity to discuss my health.
options: A. Osteopetrosis B. Osteitis fibrosa cystica C. Paget disease D. Ewing sarcoma E. Osgood-Schlatter disease

question:
I am a 12-year-old boy who has been experiencing recurrent joint pain that moves from one joint to another over the past several weeks. Alongside this pain, I have had intermittent fevers. I noticed that my appetite has decreased, and I have been losing weight during this time. 

During a recent examination, I was found to be afebrile, and my vital signs were reported as normal. However, the examination revealed that I appeared pale and had diffuse petechial bleeding and bruises on my legs. Additionally, when my abdomen was examined, it was noted that I had hepatosplenomegaly, which means my liver and spleen were enlarged. 

An ultrasound of my abdomen confirmed the enlargement of my liver and spleen and showed multiple enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes. A complete blood count indicated that I was suffering from severe anemia and thrombocytopenia, along with leukocytosis. 

Given these symptoms and findings, my healthcare team is working to determine the most likely diagnosis to address my condition effectively.
options: A. Acute leukemia B. Tuberculosis of the bone marrow C. Aplastic anemia D. Immunologic thrombocytopenic purpura E. Chronic leukemia

question: During my second trimester of pregnancy, I underwent a routine quad-screen test. The results indicated decreased levels of alpha-fetoprotein, increased levels of Beta-hCG, decreased levels of estriol, and increased levels of inhibin A. Based on these findings, my healthcare provider made a presumptive diagnosis, which was later confirmed through genetic testing. After the birth of my child, I learned that there was a heightened risk for certain hematologic malignancies associated with the results of the quad-screen. This information was concerning, and I was advised to stay informed about the potential health implications for my child.
options: A. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia B. Hairy cell leukemia C. Acute promyelocytic leukemia D. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia E. Chronic myelogenous leukemia

question:
I am a 74-year-old woman who was brought by ambulance to the emergency department after experiencing excruciating chest pain. The pain began about 45 minutes prior while I was sitting in my garden. Initially, I felt discomfort in my upper abdomen, but it soon intensified and localized beneath my sternum and into my left shoulder. I attempted to alleviate the pain with milk of magnesia and aspirin, but neither provided relief.

In the past, I had experienced episodes of chest pain, though they were less severe and typically lasted no longer than ten minutes. I have a history of diabetes, hypertension, and rheumatoid arthritis. Upon examination in the emergency department, I was breathless and sweating profusely. 

My vital signs indicated a blood pressure of 140/90 mm Hg and a heart rate of 118 beats per minute. I was admitted for treatment, which included analgesia and reperfusion therapy. Initially, I showed signs of recovery. However, on the sixth day of my hospitalization, I began to vomit and felt dizzy. At that time, my heart rate was 110 beats per minute, my temperature was 37.7°C (99.9°F), and my blood pressure had dropped to 90/60 mm Hg. A harsh pansystolic murmur was noted at the left lower sternal border, and my ECG showed sinus tachycardia and ST-segment elevation.
options: A. A new myocardial infarction (re-infarction) B. Acute pericarditis complicating myocardial infarction C. Acute ventricular septal rupture complicating myocardial infarction D. Aortic dissection complicating myocardial infarction E. Cardiac tamponade complicating myocardial infarction

question:
I am a 74-year-old man who recently sought medical attention due to persistent back pain. Over the past several months, I have experienced significant fatigue and noticed an unintentional weight loss of about 20 pounds. During my visit, the doctor conducted some tests, and I learned that my creatinine levels had increased from my usual baseline. Additionally, my serum calcium level was measured at 11.5 mg/dL, which raised some concern.

Following this, I was referred to a nephrologist for further evaluation of my kidney function. As part of my assessment, a renal biopsy was performed, and I was informed that the microscopic examination of my urine showed the presence of eosinophilic casts. I am awaiting further discussion with my healthcare team to understand the implications of these findings and the most likely explanations for my renal condition.
options: A. Monoclonal protein overproduction B. Ischemic tubular injury C. Acute pyelonephritis D. Diabetic nephropathy E. Nephritic syndrome

question:
I am a 67-year-old man with a history of sleep apnea. Recently, I experienced severe respiratory distress and was taken to the emergency room. Upon my arrival, the medical team assessed my condition. They recorded my blood pressure at 135/75 mmHg, my heart rate at 110 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate at 34 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation level was measured at 73% while I was on room air.

Due to the severity of my situation, I was intubated and admitted to the intensive care unit for closer monitoring and treatment. After some time, I underwent a tracheostomy tube insertion to help manage my breathing. 

Despite the surgery, I continued to have episodes of apnea while sleeping. This ongoing issue prompted the medical staff to consider the underlying causes of my apnea.
options: A. Incorrect ventilator settings B. Central sleep apnea C. Obstructive sleep apnea D. Angioedema E. Heart failure

question:
I am a 58-year-old male, and I recently visited my primary care doctor because I noticed changes in my vision over the past several months. This issue has been concerning for me, as I have been managing my health conditions for quite some time. 

My medical history includes schizophrenia, which has been well-controlled for the last 25 years with the medication chlorpromazine. Despite my stable mental health, the new vision changes prompted me to seek medical advice. During the appointment, I discussed my symptoms and concerns with my doctor, who examined my eyes. I understand that an ophthalmoscopy was performed to assess my eye health and determine the underlying cause of my vision issues.

While I am still awaiting further information about what may be observed during that examination, I remain hopeful for a clear understanding of my condition. The changes in my vision have been a source of worry, and I look forward to addressing these concerns with my healthcare provider.
options: A. Retinitis pigmentosa B. Macular degeneration C. Glaucoma D. Retinal hemorrhage E. Corneal deposits

question:
I am a 3-year-old girl who was brought to the doctor’s office by my mother. For the past two days, I had been crying and pulling at my right ear. My mother noticed that I had a fever for the last 24 hours, which seemed to make me more uncomfortable. 

Prior to this, I had been healthy and did not have any significant medical issues. About a week ago, I had a common cold, but it resolved on its own without needing any treatment. On the day we visited the doctor, my temperature was taken, and it measured 101.6 degrees Fahrenheit. My blood pressure was recorded at 100/70 mmHg, my pulse was 120 beats per minute, and my breathing rate was 22 breaths per minute. 

During the visit, the doctor performed an otoscopic exam, examining my ears closely. My mother and I were both anxious to understand what was causing my discomfort and how we could make it better.
options: A. Otosclerosis B. Malignant otitis externa C. Acute otitis externa D. Acute otitis media E. Otitis media with effusion

question:
I am a 12-year-old boy who recently began experiencing pain in my left knee that started about six days ago. The pain has gradually worsened, particularly when I move or kneel, but I do not feel any pain when I am at rest. I haven’t had any recent injuries to my knee, which is concerning me, especially since my soccer tryouts are in a few days.

When I visited the physician, my vital signs were normal. During the examination, the doctor noted mild swelling and tenderness in the area near the superior part of my left tibia. I experienced pain when the doctor tested the extension of my knee against resistance, and I found that I couldn’t flex my knee fully due to the pain. There were no signs of redness or excess fluid in my knee, which the doctor also checked.

As I think about what might be causing my symptoms, I am focused on understanding what could be happening with my knee, especially since I want to be ready for my tryouts.
options: A. Impingement of the infrapatellar fat pad B. Septic arthritis of the knee C. Stress fracture of the tibial tuberosity D. Inflammation of the infrapatellar bursa E. Osteoid osteoma of the tibia F. Chondromalacia patella G. Traction apophysitis of the tibial tubercle H. Osteochondritis dissecans of the knee I. Iliotibial band syndrome J. Avulsion fracture of the proximal tibia

question:
I am a 47-year-old male with a medical history that includes hypertension, recurrent urinary tract infections, mitral valve prolapse, and diverticulosis. One evening, while watching television on my couch, I suddenly experienced a severe headache. It felt as if someone had shot me in the back of my head. Concerned, I called 911 for assistance.

The paramedics arrived promptly and assessed my condition. I reported the intensity and nature of the headache to them. Once they evaluated me, I was transported to the emergency room for further examination. In the hospital, the medical team noted that I had no focal neurological deficits, but I exhibited significant nuchal rigidity and photophobia. These symptoms contributed to their assessment of my condition.
options: A. Migraine B. Brain Tumor C. Temporal Arteritis D. Subarachnoid Hemorrhage E. Carotid Dissection

question:
Three days after being admitted to the intensive care unit for septic shock and bacteremia caused by a urinary tract infection, I experienced persistent hypotension. My blood cultures confirmed the presence of Escherichia coli, and I had been receiving appropriate antibiotics since my admission. I do not have any history of serious illness or use of illicit drugs. 

During my treatment, I was administered norepinephrine, ceftriaxone, and acetaminophen. I felt well overall, although my vital signs indicated some concerns: my temperature was recorded at 37.5°C (99.5°F), my heart rate was 96 beats per minute, and my blood pressure measured 85/55 mm Hg. 

The examination revealed costovertebral tenderness bilaterally in my back, but the thyroid gland showed no abnormalities. On the first hospital day, my leukocyte count was 18,500/mm³, which decreased to 10,300/mm³ by day three. My hemoglobin levels had slightly dropped from 14.1 mg/dL to 13.4 mg/dL, and my serum creatinine levels improved from 1.4 mg/dL to 0.9 mg/dL. My fasting glucose was measured at 95 mg/dL on the first day and increased to 100 mg/dL by the third day. 

Repeat blood cultures returned negative, and a chest x-ray showed no abnormalities.
options: A. Medication toxicity B. Sick euthyroid syndrome C. Fibrous thyroiditis D. Pituitary apoplexy E. Chronic autoimmune thyroiditis F. De Quervain's thyroiditis G. Subclinical hypothyrodism

question:
I am a 27-year-old female who was brought to the Emergency Department by Fire Rescue after being involved in a physical altercation with several commuters on the subway. Upon arrival, I was experiencing hallucinations and was sweating profusely. My body felt unusually warm, and I noticed my heart racing. The medical staff took my vital signs, which indicated an elevated temperature and heart rate, as well as high blood pressure. 

I have a history of a previous visit to the Emergency Department due to agitation related to phencyclidine use. The experience was disorienting, and I was unsure of my surroundings. The medical team assessed my condition carefully, looking for signs that might indicate a similar diagnosis to my past experience. I found myself reflecting on the events that led to this moment and the challenges I faced in managing my mental health.
options: A. Prominent vertical nystagmus B. Constricted but responsive pupils C. Dilated, minimally responsive pupils D. Conjunctival injection E. Conjunctival pallor

question:
I am a 24-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle collision while seated in the passenger seat, properly restrained. After the impact, I was brought to the emergency department. Upon arrival, I felt pale and in moderate distress, experiencing a sharp pain in the back of my left shoulder. 

The medical team began their assessment. My temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F). They took my blood pressure in both arms; the right arm read 94/63 mm Hg and the left arm was 90/61 mm Hg. My pulse was elevated at 122 beats per minute, and my breathing rate was 24 breaths per minute. During the examination, the doctors noted that my heart sounds were normal and my lungs were clear. They also observed several large bruises on my chest and abdomen, consistent with a seatbelt pattern. 

My abdomen was tender to touch, with some mild rebound tenderness and rigidity. However, my range of motion was normal, and I exhibited full motor strength in all my limbs, with no signs of wrist drop. A Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) scan was ordered to further evaluate my condition.
options: A. Aorta B. Pancreas C. Humerus D. Heart E. Spleen F. Gallbladder G. Appendix

question:
I am a 75-year-old man who underwent a bilateral lung transplant 11 months ago. Following the transplant, I was placed on immunosuppressive treatment to prevent organ rejection. However, for reasons I do not fully understand, I stopped taking the voriconazole that had been prescribed to prevent fungal infections.

Recently, I presented to the emergency room with symptoms of fever and chills. Upon arrival, I was found to be hypoxemic, which raised concerns about my lung health. Imaging was conducted, revealing pulmonary nodules, and a transbronchial biopsy was performed for further evaluation.

The biopsy results showed no signs of acute organ rejection, adenovirus, cytomegalovirus, or acid-fast bacilli. Additionally, slides prepared from my specimen revealed large, round structures. To investigate further, my specimen was sent to the microbiology laboratory for fungal culture. The culture grew a fuzzy mold on Sabouraud agar at a temperature of 30°C.

This sequence of events has been concerning, and I am now awaiting further information regarding the specific organism that has infected me.
options: A. Coccidioides species B. Blastomyces dermatitidis C. Cryptococcus neoformans D. Histoplasma capsulatum E. Malbranchea species

question:
I was brought into the emergency department after being found by the police in extremely cold weather, around 5 degrees Celsius. I have a history of heroin use and am currently homeless. When the medical team assessed me, my vital signs showed a body temperature of 95.3°F, a heart rate of 80 beats per minute, and blood pressure of 150/90, with a respiratory rate of 10 breaths per minute. 

After being warmed, it became apparent that my left lower leg was significantly larger than my right leg. Upon examination, I realized that I had lost sensation in my left lower extremity. The medical staff noted a faint pulse at my dorsalis pedis artery but could not detect a pulse at the posterior tibial artery. I was unresponsive to normal commands, but when they performed a passive stretch of my left lower leg, I reacted by shrieking in pain. This series of events led the medical team to consider the most probable cause of my condition.
options: A. Cellulitis B. Necrotizing fasciitis C. Embolized clot D. Reperfusion associated edema E. Diabetes

question:
I was admitted to the hospital at the age of 58 due to severe abdominal pain and confusion. I have a history of alcohol use disorder, which has led to several previous admissions for intoxication. Twelve hours after my admission, I began experiencing worsening shortness of breath. During this time, my temperature was recorded at 38.3°C (100.9°F), my pulse was 120 beats per minute, my respirations were 30 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was noted at 100/60 mm Hg. 

Despite receiving oxygen, my oxygen saturation was only 85%. Due to the severity of my symptoms, I was intubated and placed on mechanical ventilation with an FiO2 of 40%. A physical examination revealed diffuse lung crackles and marked tenderness in my epigastric area, along with a periumbilical hematoma. The cardiac examination showed no abnormalities, and there was no jugular venous distension.

I underwent further assessments, including a chest X-ray, which indicated bilateral opacities in the lower lung fields. The clinical team was working to determine the most likely cause of my respiratory symptoms, considering the overall situation and my medical history.
options: A. Pulmonary embolism B. Aspiration pneumonia C. Hospital-acquired pneumonia D. Acute respiratory distress syndrome E. Congestive heart failure F. Hepatic hydrothorax

question:
I am a 35-year-old woman who, along with my 37-year-old husband, has been trying to conceive for the past four years. After numerous visits to a fertility clinic, I finally became pregnant. Although I missed most of my antenatal visits, my pregnancy was generally uneventful. I gave birth to a baby girl at 38 weeks of gestation. 

After her birth, I noticed that she had some abnormalities. She had a flat face with upward-slanting eyes and a short neck. Additionally, her tongue appeared to be protruding from her small mouth. I observed that she had poor muscle tone and excessive joint laxity. 

Concerned about her condition, the pediatrician ordered a karyotype analysis to examine her chromosomes. I was left wondering about the implications of these findings for her future health and development.
options: A. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia B. Chronic myelogenous leukemia C. Immotile cilia syndrome D. Macroorchidism E. Red blood cell sickling

question:
I am a 52-year-old man who recently experienced persistent headaches, vertigo, and notable changes in my personality over the past few weeks. I was diagnosed with HIV 14 years ago and have been on antiretroviral therapy since then. However, my medical records indicate that I had been inconsistent with my medication schedule about a month ago. Since that time, I have made a conscious effort to adhere to my antiretroviral medications and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole.

When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were within normal limits. During the neurological examination, the doctor noted that I exhibited ataxia and apathy. To assess my cognitive function, I underwent a Mini-Mental State Examination, where I scored 15 out of 30.

Subsequent imaging, an MRI of my brain with contrast, revealed a solitary ring-enhancing lesion in the corpus callosum, measuring 4.5 cm in diameter. A lumbar puncture was performed, and the analysis of my cerebrospinal fluid indicated slight pleocytosis, with a positive PCR for Epstein-Barr virus DNA. Given these findings, the healthcare team is considering my diagnosis based on this information.
options:
A. AIDS dementia B. CNS lymphoma C. Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy D. Bacterial brain abscess E. Toxoplasmosis F. Glioblastoma
"

question:
I am a 54-year-old female who recently went to the emergency department due to experiencing shortness of breath. I do not speak English, and my medical history was not available at the time. Upon arrival, my temperature was recorded at 100.1°F (37.8°C), my blood pressure was 130/85 mmHg, my pulse was 105 beats per minute, and my respirations were 24 breaths per minute.

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted bilateral rales in my lungs and dullness to percussion at the lung bases, which was more pronounced on the left side. Additionally, the examination revealed hepatosplenomegaly. A chest radiograph was performed to further assess my condition. I underwent a thoracentesis and a hematologic analysis as part of my evaluation. 

I was informed that various tests were conducted, including measurements of pleural and serum lactate dehydrogenase, as well as protein levels in both pleural fluid and serum. These findings were key in guiding my diagnosis and treatment plan.
options: A. Pulmonary embolism B. Cirrhosis C. Nephrotic syndrome D. Protein losing enteropathy E. Congestive heart failure

question:
I am a 70-year-old male with a history of obesity and type II diabetes. Recently, I experienced sudden shortness of breath and a cough while I was sleeping, which prompted me to seek help at the emergency department. During my visit, the medical team noted that I had bipedal edema and jugular venous distention.

I am currently taking lisinopril, metformin, insulin, and fish oil to manage my diabetes. After a physical examination, the doctors conducted an EKG and chest radiographs to assess my condition. They initiated treatment with BIPAP and other medical therapies, and I noticed a rapid improvement in my symptoms.

The medical staff was attentive and thorough in their evaluation, and I am grateful for the care I received. My symptoms have significantly decreased since the start of treatment, allowing me to breathe more comfortably. While I was unaware of the underlying causes at the time, I felt relieved to be in the hands of professionals who could provide the necessary care for my sudden health issue.
options: A. Furosemide B. Hydrochlorothiazide C. Renal tubular acidosis type I D. Renal tubular acidosis type II E. Renal tubular acidosis type IV

question:
I am a 36-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department after experiencing multiple episodes of nonbilious vomiting for the past three days. The vomit consisted of undigested food, and I had dark brown vomit twice today. During this time, I also noticed that I felt full after eating only a small amount of food. For the past week, I have been suffering from severe episodic pain in my upper abdomen, along with dyspepsia. The pain is somewhat relieved by eating or taking over-the-counter antacids, but it worsens at night and several hours after meals. 

Interestingly, I have gained about 2 kilograms (4.4 pounds) during this period. My medical history includes a family history of colon cancer; my father had surgery for it three years ago. I have been smoking one pack of cigarettes daily for the last 15 years and typically consume two to three beers each day.

Upon examination in the emergency department, I had dry mucous membranes and mild tenderness in my left upper abdomen. The doctors noted a tympanitic mass in the epigastric area, and I could hear a splash sound when they moved me. My bowel sounds were reduced, and a rectal examination was unremarkable. They also found a positive test for occult blood in my stool. The rest of the examination was normal.
options: A. Inflammation and edema B. Narrowing of aortomesenteric angle C. Abnormal gastric rotation D. Neoplastic growth E. Gallstone obstruction F. Scarring and fibrosis G. Walled-off pancreatic fluid collection

question: I am a 7-year-old girl who went to the emergency department because of swelling around my eye. This has happened to me before, but this time it was much worse. A few days ago, I noticed a small lesion that has since become increasingly red and painful. When the doctor examined me, they found that the area was tender when they touched it. They checked my cranial nerves, and everything seemed to be intact. I did not feel any pain when I moved my eyes in different directions. The doctors were trying to determine what might be causing this swelling and discomfort.
options: A. Chalazion B. Dacryocystitis C. Hordeolum D. Orbital cellulitis E. Periorbital cellulitis

question:
I am a 48-year-old female who recently went to the emergency room due to changes in my mental status. I was feeling disoriented and confused, which prompted the visit. Upon arrival, I underwent a series of tests to assess my condition.

The medical team conducted a laboratory analysis of my serum, which revealed several electrolyte levels. My sodium level was notably low, while my potassium, bicarbonate, blood urea nitrogen, creatinine, calcium, and glucose levels fell within normal ranges. Additionally, a urinalysis was performed, showing my urine osmolality and sodium levels.

Throughout the process, I felt anxious about my mental clarity and what might be causing these changes. The healthcare professionals were attentive and explained the tests they were conducting. I awaited their findings and potential diagnosis, hoping for clarity regarding my condition and the next steps for treatment.
options: A. Aspirin overdose B. Diarrhea C. Diabetes insipidus D. Primary polydipsia E. Lung cancer

question:
I visited the physician with my 4-year-old daughter, who had been experiencing pallor and a rash for the past two days. Prior to this, she had a 4-day period of diarrhea and vomiting that resolved two days ago. About a month earlier, she had a 3-day episode of high fever, followed by a rash that caused bright red discoloration on her cheeks, which also subsided without any treatment.

At the appointment, the physician noted that she appeared pale and irritable, but her vital signs were within normal limits. Upon examination, the doctor found petechiae on her trunk and extremities. The examination of her abdomen revealed diffuse tenderness and hyperactive bowel sounds, while the rest of the examination showed no abnormalities.

We were informed that her medical history included up-to-date vaccinations. The physician recommended laboratory studies to investigate further. During this time, I remained concerned about her overall condition and the recent symptoms she had been experiencing.
options: A. Escherichia coli infection B. Acute lymphocytic leukemia C. Parvovirus B19 infection D. Disseminated intravascular coagulation E. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura F. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura

question:
I am a 17-year-old male who experienced a motor vehicle accident where I was driving without a seatbelt. It was a head-on collision, and I was taken to the emergency department afterward. I have a medical history that includes asthma, depression, and anxiety, but I was not taking any medications at the time of the accident.

When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, and my blood pressure was 90/60 mmHg. My pulse was 115 beats per minute, and I was breathing at a rate of 22 breaths per minute, with an oxygen saturation of 99% while on room air. The doctors conducted a cardiopulmonary examination, which they found to be normal. I was able to breathe independently and had strong pulses in my extremities. After being evaluated, I was discharged without any significant fractures or injuries, along with follow-up instructions.

Four months later, I returned to my primary care doctor, reporting weakness. During the examination, I was found to have significantly reduced strength in my upper extremities at 1/5, while my lower extremities displayed full strength at 5/5. Sensation in my upper extremities was also diminished, though it remained intact in my lower extremities. My doctor ordered a chest radiograph and some basic lab tests for further evaluation.
options: A. Cervical spine fracture B. Intracranial hemorrhage C. Syringomyelia D. Brachial plexopathy E. Conversion disorder

question:
I am a 31-year-old woman, currently in my 38th week of pregnancy and a first-time mother. I have a history of hypertension. This morning, while riding my bike to work, I fell and began to experience painful contractions. Shortly after the fall, I noticed some vaginal bleeding and felt lower abdominal and pelvic pain between the contractions.

Concerned about my symptoms, I went to the emergency department, believing that I might be in labor. Upon arrival, my vital signs were taken: my temperature was 97.6°F, my blood pressure was notably high at 177/99 mmHg, my pulse was 100 beats per minute, my respirations were 20 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% on room air.

During the physical examination, the doctor noted that my uterus was gravid and hypertonic, and there was moderate blood present in the vaginal vault. An ultrasound was performed, but it did not reveal any abnormalities. Given these circumstances, I was left awaiting a diagnosis regarding my condition and the implications for my pregnancy.
options: A. Abruptio placentae B. Normal labor C. Placenta previa D. Uterine rupture E. Vasa previa

question:
Three days after I underwent cardiac catheterization and coronary angioplasty due to an acute myocardial infarction, I began to experience shortness of breath, even while at rest. I am 70 years old and have a medical history that includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. At the time, I was taking several medications, including aspirin, clopidogrel, atorvastatin, sublingual nitroglycerin, metoprolol, and insulin.

During this episode, I noticed that I was sweating more than usual. My temperature was normal, but my pulse was elevated at 120 beats per minute, and I was breathing rapidly at 22 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 100 over 55 mm Hg. 

I also observed that there were crackles heard at both bases of my lungs during the examination. A cardiac assessment revealed a new grade 3/6 holosystolic murmur, which was most prominent at the apex of my heart. An ECG showed that I was in sinus rhythm, but there was T wave inversion noted in specific leads.

These symptoms prompted further evaluation to determine the underlying cause of my condition.
options: A. Left ventricular aneurysm B. Early infarct-associated pericarditis C. Ventricular septal rupture D. Postmyocardial infarction syndrome E. Coronary artery dissection F. Ventricular free wall rupture G. Papillary muscle rupture

question:
I am an 8-year-old girl who recently visited the emergency department due to a persistent cough, fever, and a runny nose. Having immigrated from Lebanon, I have never seen a doctor before this visit. My medical history includes receiving antibiotics every few months for similar symptoms, which have been frequent since I was a child. I also have seasonal allergies that contribute to my overall health challenges.

During my examination, my temperature was measured at 101°F, and my blood pressure was recorded as 100/64 mmHg. My pulse was 89 beats per minute, my respirations were 18 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was at 96% while breathing room air. The doctor noted bilateral coarse breath sounds during the physical exam but said I appeared well otherwise. 

To further investigate my symptoms, a chest radiograph was performed. The results of this imaging would help determine the most likely diagnosis for my condition.
options: A. Abnormal cilia motility B. Adenosine deaminase deficiency C. Chloride channel defect D. Decrease in all immunoglobulin levels E. Tyrosine kinase abnormality

question:
I am a 35-year-old woman, currently 39 weeks pregnant with my third child. Recently, I was a passenger in a motor vehicle accident where my car hit a tree. I was wearing my seat belt, and the airbag deployed upon impact. Shortly after the accident, I began to experience painful vaginal bleeding and decided to go to the emergency department for evaluation.

I have a history of smoking cigarettes and my prenatal check-ups have been normal, except for a previous pregnancy where I had one episode of chorioamnionitis that was treated successfully with antibiotics. Upon arrival at the hospital, my vital signs were taken; my temperature was 98.6°F, blood pressure was 90/60 mmHg, my pulse was 130 beats per minute, and my respirations were 20 breaths per minute. The fetal heart rate was recorded at 110 beats per minute. The medical staff noted that my uterus was tender and firm, but the rest of my physical examination was unremarkable. I am now awaiting further evaluation to understand the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Preeclampsia B. Preterm labor C. Vasa previa D. Placental abruption E. Eclampsia

question:
I am a 36-year-old man who recently went to the emergency room due to a subacute worsening of my chronic chest pain and shortness of breath that occurs with exertion. Generally, I consider myself healthy; I lift weights regularly and do not smoke.

Upon arrival at the emergency room, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was recorded at 97.8°F, my blood pressure was 122/83 mm Hg, my pulse was 80 beats per minute, my respirations were 13 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air.

During the cardiac examination, the doctor noted a crescendo-decrescendo murmur located to the right of my upper sternal border, which radiated into my carotids. An electrocardiogram (ECG) showed left axis deviation and indicated criteria consistent with left ventricular hypertrophy. Additionally, an initial troponin test returned a value of less than 0.01 ng/mL.

These findings prompted further investigation into my symptoms, and I was informed that they would need to determine the most likely diagnosis based on the clinical presentation and test results.
options: A. Bacterial endocarditis B. Bicuspid aortic valve C. Cardiac myxoma D. Mitral insufficiency E. Senile calcific changes

question:
I arrived at the emergency room feeling unwell, experiencing a fever and sharp pain in my chest, particularly when I coughed or inhaled. Prior to this visit, three weeks earlier, I had seen my rheumatologist due to a butterfly rash on my face, along with joint pain and fatigue. During that appointment, I was diagnosed with systemic lupus erythematosus. 

When I was examined in the ER, the doctors noted a friction rub, which I learned can indicate certain complications related to my condition. The combination of my symptoms and my recent diagnosis raised concerns for the medical team. They were focused on understanding what might be happening to me, given the context of my lupus diagnosis and my current presentation. I felt anxious but was hopeful that they would determine the best course of action for my care.
options: A. Pulmonary hypertension B. Interstitial lung disease C. Acute myocardial infarction D. Pericarditis E. Pericardial tamponade

question:
I am a 27-year-old woman who recently experienced a fall from my bicycle while on my way to work. Approximately an hour ago, I lost my balance and fell, hitting my head on the sidewalk. After the fall, I lost consciousness for a couple of minutes. Currently, I am feeling nauseous and have a headache. In the last 30 minutes, I vomited twice.

I do not have a history of serious illness, and I do not smoke, drink alcohol, or use illicit drugs. I take no medications. When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was normal, but my pulse was low at 50 beats per minute, and my respirations were at 10 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 160/90 mm Hg. I was oriented to person, place, and time, and my lungs were clear upon examination. 

There was a bruise noted on the right side of my head, and during the physical exam, I experienced a seizure. I was administered intravenous lorazepam and subsequently admitted to the intensive care unit for further observation and care.
options: A. Ischemic stroke B. Subdural hematoma C. Intracerebral hemorrhage D. Subarachnoidal hemorrhage E. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension F. Epidural hematoma

question:
I am a 42-year-old Caucasian woman who recently visited the emergency department due to several concerning symptoms. Over the past few months, I have experienced progressive weight loss, dizziness, nausea, and vomiting. Six months ago, I returned from a two-week international business trip where I fell ill with a fever, diarrhea, and a cough.

Upon arriving at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was recorded at 97.7°F, my blood pressure was 114/64 mmHg, my pulse was elevated at 105 beats per minute, my respirations were at 72 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 99% while on room air. The physical examination revealed significant findings that were documented. 

Due to my symptoms and medical history, initial laboratory studies were ordered to help determine the underlying cause of my condition. I am now awaiting further evaluation and diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Aldosteronoma B. Autoimmune adrenalitis C. SIADH D. Tuberculosis E. Viral gastroenteritis

question:
I am a 2-year-old male who was brought to the emergency department by my mother after experiencing a seizure. Prior to this event, I had been running a fever for three days. The seizure occurred while I was watching TV. After arriving at the hospital, I was admitted for further evaluation and observation.

Three days later, my medical team noticed that I had developed a papular rash on my back, which was not confluent and extended upwards towards the nape of my neck. Additional observations were made regarding my abdomen and chest, which were documented by the healthcare providers.
options: A. Roseola B. Variola C. Rubeola D. Rubella E. Mumps

question:
I was brought to the physician by my wife because I had become increasingly restless and anxious. For the past four months, I had been feeling sad and irritable. I lost my job as a store clerk, primarily because I often lied to avoid work. Instead, I spent most of my days on the phone, placing bets on football games. I began to avoid family-related events since I had borrowed money from many of my relatives. I held onto the hope that my situation would improve once I could win some of my money back.

I had been a smoker, using 8 to 10 cigarettes daily, but I quit a month ago. I typically drank beer on the weekends. During my examination, I was uncooperative and dismissive, and I noticed I was mildly tremulous. However, I was oriented to person, place, and time, and the neurologic examination did not reveal any abnormalities.
options: A. Major depressive disorder B. Nicotine withdrawal C. Gambling disorder D. Opioid withdrawal E. Acute stress disorder F. Alcohol withdrawal G. Bipolar II disorder H. Adjustment disorder

question:
I am a 68-year-old male with a medical history that includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). I arrived at the emergency department experiencing severe substernal chest pain. During the examination, I was sweating profusely and felt significant distress. An electrocardiogram (EKG) was performed, and I started receiving treatment for my condition. Following this, I was admitted to the cardiac intensive care unit (CICU).

Initially, my condition seemed to improve while I was in the CICU. However, on the fifth day of my hospitalization, I began to experience severe shortness of breath and chest pain once again. The medical staff noted my vital signs: my temperature was 36 degrees Celsius, my heart rate was 130 beats per minute, my blood pressure was 65/40 mmHg, my respiratory rate was 12 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98%. It was clear that I was in distress, and the healthcare team observed elevated jugular venous pressure (JVP). During this time, I was informed that a biopsy of my myocardium might be necessary to further investigate my condition.
options: A. Figure A B. Figure B C. Figure C D. Figure D E. Figure E

question:
I am a 60-year-old woman who went to the emergency department because I was experiencing dizziness. This dizziness began that morning when I woke up and was severe enough to cause me to vomit. Fortunately, the episode resolved after about a minute. 

I have a medical history that includes hypertension, diabetes, obesity, and atrial fibrillation, which I manage with warfarin and metoprolol. A few days prior, I had recovered from a cold. Upon arrival at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 99.0°F, my blood pressure was 174/99 mmHg, my pulse was 115 beats per minute, my respirations were 12 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air. 

During the physical examination, I appeared well despite my symptoms. The neurological exam, which included checking my cranial nerves and gait, showed normal results. However, when I was laid flat in bed, I experienced another episode of dizziness accompanied by noticeable nystagmus and vomiting, which again improved after about a minute. 

The medical team noted my symptoms and assessed my condition to determine the underlying cause.
options: A. Canalithiasis B. Increased endolymph production C. Inflammation of the vestibular apparatus D. Inflammation of the vestibulocochlear apparatus E. Vertebrobasilar insufficiency

question:
I was taken to the emergency department by my parents after experiencing swelling in my right knee. This occurred after I had been playing in the park, and there was no obvious injury that they could identify. My mother mentioned that an uncle of hers had faced similar issues in the past.

Upon arrival, my vital signs were assessed. My heart rate was 146 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 26 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 37.1°C (98.8°F). My blood pressure was recorded at 90/52 mm Hg. During the physical examination, the swelling in my right knee was clearly noticeable, while the rest of the examination showed no significant findings.

An ultrasound was performed, which indicated that I had hemarthrosis in my right knee. While I did not receive detailed information about my blood test results, my parents were informed about my hemoglobin levels and other blood components. The doctors also conducted coagulation tests, which were part of the evaluation process.

Overall, my situation involved a sudden swelling in my knee, and the medical team was working to determine the most likely diagnosis based on the findings from the ultrasound and blood tests.
options: A. Marfan syndrome B. Von Willebrand disease C. Ehler-Danlos disease D. Hemophilia A E. Bernard-Soulier disease

question:
I am a 61-year-old male who recently visited my primary care physician due to worsening shortness of breath that I had been experiencing for several months. I have a medical history that includes essential hypertension and rheumatoid arthritis, but I have chosen not to take medication for either condition. I do not use alcohol, tobacco, or any other drugs.

During the physical examination, my doctor noted that I had bilateral end-inspiratory rales at the bases of my lungs. This examination, along with my symptoms, prompted further discussion about my condition. I was informed that my chest radiograph, which was taken during the visit, would be reviewed to help identify the underlying cause of my dyspnea. 

The focus of our conversation centered on understanding what might be contributing to my respiratory issues, given my existing health problems and the refusal of medication. I left the appointment with a better understanding of my symptoms and the next steps in the evaluation process.
options: A. Chronic bronchitis B. Tension pneumothorax C. Pulmonary embolism D. Pulmonary fibrosis E. Mitral stenosis

question:
I am a 58-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to severe chest pain and a feeling of uneasiness. The symptoms started suddenly about half an hour before I arrived, while I was watching television. I would rate the pain as 8 out of 10 in intensity; it was sharp, located in the center of my chest, and radiated to my back and shoulders. I noticed some nausea but did not experience any vomiting. 

There was no change in the pain with breathing or body position, and I had no recent history of fever, chills, or chronic cough. My medical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and diabetes, for which I take lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide, simvastatin, and metformin. I have a 30-pack-year smoking history and typically consume 1-2 alcoholic drinks on weekends. 

My family history includes hypertension and hyperlipidemia, as well as an ST elevation myocardial infarction in both my father and paternal uncle. Upon examination, my blood pressure was recorded at 220/110 mm Hg in my right arm and 180/100 mm Hg in my left. I was diaphoretic, and the cardiac exam revealed a grade 2/6 diastolic murmur. The rest of the examination was normal. They performed a chest radiograph and an electrocardiogram, which indicated some abnormalities. I was given intravenous morphine and beta-blockers during my treatment.
options: A. Aortic dissection B. Pulmonary embolism C. Acute myocardial infarction D. Myocarditis E. Aortic regurgitation

question:
I was brought to the emergency department after experiencing a fall. Upon arrival, I was seen by a triage nurse, but I hadn’t yet been evaluated by a physician. I found myself yelling down the hallway, requesting to speak to “whoever is in charge.” I refused to talk to the emergency resident, insisting instead on speaking with the attending physician, even though I was informed that the attending was occupied resuscitating another patient who had been in a car accident.

I expressed my frustration, stating that I deserved better treatment due to my numerous contributions to the field of medicine. When asked about my work, I mentioned that I had been a medical device salesman. My wife was with me and seemed embarrassed by my behavior; she even apologized for my actions, indicating that I often make a scene.

During the mental status examination, I was oriented to person, place, and time, but I felt agitated and spoke in short, pressured sentences. I was aware of my surroundings and did not exhibit any disorder of thought process or content.
options: A. Acute stress disorder B. Antisocial personality disorder C. Obsessive compulsive personality disorder D. Borderline personality disorder E. Histrionic personality disorder F. Intermittent explosive disorder G. Bipolar disorder H. Narcissistic personality disorder

question:
I went to the emergency room because I had been experiencing left chest pain and a productive cough with purulent sputum for the past week. Alongside these symptoms, I also had shortness of breath. I remembered that I had been previously diagnosed with influenza, but I hadn’t followed the doctor’s instructions regarding my treatment.

Upon arrival, the medical staff took my vital signs. My heart rate was 70 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 22 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 38.7°C (101.7°F). My blood pressure was recorded at 120/60 mm Hg, and my oxygen saturation level was 80%. 

The doctors performed some tests, including a hemogram and a chest X-ray. I learned that my hemoglobin level was 14 mg/dL, my hematocrit was 45%, and my leukocyte count showed 12,000/mm3, with a high percentage of neutrophils. The chest X-ray revealed alveolar infiltrates in the left base along with air bronchograms. 

I was unsure what the diagnosis would be, but the medical team began discussing possible conditions based on my symptoms and test results.
options: A. Sarcoidosis B. Pneumonia C. Histoplasmosis D. Lung cancer E. Tuberculosis

question:
I am a 27-year-old woman who recently visited my doctor due to some concerning symptoms. I have been experiencing difficulty swallowing, which feels like there is something stuck in the back of my throat. Alongside this, I have developed an achy pain in my chest that has been progressively worsening over the past few weeks. 

I do not have any accompanying symptoms such as fever, shortness of breath, cough, abdominal pain, heartburn, nausea, or vomiting. My medical history includes a wrist fracture from childhood, a history of migraines, and a recent diagnosis of myasthenia gravis. Given my symptoms and medical background, I sought professional advice to understand the underlying cause of my condition.
options: A. Benign tumor of the thymus B. Superior vena cava syndrome C. Anaplastic thyroid cancer D. Mediastinitis E. Thyroglossal duct cyst

question:
I am a 6-year-old girl who recently visited my pediatrician due to some concerning symptoms. I had developed a rash on my skin and was experiencing intermittent abdominal pain. Additionally, my arms and legs were swelling, which was quite uncomfortable. I also began to feel pain in my knees and hands, even though I had not experienced any trauma.

During the visit, my temperature was measured at 97.6°F, and my blood pressure was recorded as 100/80 mmHg. My pulse was 89 beats per minute, with respirations at 18 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air. The doctor conducted a physical examination and noted the rash and swelling in my joints, particularly in my upper extremities. 

While my abdomen was examined, it was found to be nontender and not painful. The doctor mentioned that laboratory studies were pending, and I learned that a urinalysis showed positive blood and protein in my urine. I am now waiting for the results to understand what might be causing these symptoms and what the most likely diagnosis could be.
options: A. Hemorrhagic adrenalitis B. Henoch-Schonlein purpura C. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura D. Kawasaki disease E. Rubella

question:
I am a 51-year-old woman who recently visited my physician due to experiencing significant daytime sleepiness and a persistent dry mouth for the past month. I believe my sleepiness stems from waking up several times each night to urinate. Additionally, I have noticed an increase in my thirst over the last month, leading me to drink up to 20 cups of water daily. I do not experience a sudden urge to urinate, nor have I had any pain during urination.

My medical history includes multiple urinary tract infections, and I suffered head trauma after a suicide attempt three months ago. I also have a diagnosis of bipolar I disorder and hypertension. For the past 25 years, I have been smoking about a pack of cigarettes daily.

During my examination, the physician noted that my skin turgor was poor, and my mucous membranes appeared dry. I was also found to have expiratory wheezes in both lung fields, although there was no tenderness in my suprapubic area. I described my mood as "good," and my affect seemed appropriate. The neurologic examination revealed a tremor in both of my hands.
options: A. Hypothalamic injury B. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome C. Paraneoplastic syndrome D. Pituitary neoplasm E. Hyperthyroidism F. Psychogenic polydipsia G. Primary hyperaldosteronism H. History of urinary tract infections I. Mood stabilizer intake

question:
I was involved in a high-speed motor vehicle collision and was brought to the emergency department 35 minutes later. Upon arrival, I was alert but experiencing mild chest pain and minimal shortness of breath. During my time in the hospital, I had one episode of vomiting. My temperature was recorded at 37.3°C, my pulse was 108 beats per minute, and my respirations were 23 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 90/70 mm Hg, and my oxygen saturation on room air was 92%.

The medical team examined me and noted multiple abrasions on my trunk and right upper extremity. They detected coarse breath sounds over the base of my right lung. Fortunately, my cardiac exam showed no murmurs, rubs, or gallops. An infusion of 0.9% saline was started to address my condition. However, I began to experience increasing shortness of breath.

Subsequent arterial blood gas analysis while on 60% oxygen indicated a pH of 7.36, a pCO2 of 39 mm Hg, and a pO2 of 68 mm Hg, with an O2 saturation of 81%. A chest X-ray was performed and revealed patchy, irregular infiltrates in my right lung fields. The medical team was evaluating my symptoms and imaging to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options: A. Pneumothorax B. Tracheobronchial injury C. Pulmonary contusion D. Pulmonary embolism E. Aspiration pneumonia F. Hemothorax G. Acute respiratory distress syndrome

question:
I am a 60-year-old woman who was brought to the emergency department after experiencing an altered mental status for about two hours. While my husband and I were at the grocery store, I suddenly found myself unable to remember why we were there or how we had arrived. I have no history of head trauma, but I do have a background of depression and migraines. I do not smoke and typically enjoy a glass of wine with dinner each night. I take fluoxetine daily to manage my depression.

Upon arrival at the emergency department, I felt distressed and anxious. My vital signs were reported as normal. Although I was fully alert and oriented to myself and my surroundings, I struggled with understanding the time, repeatedly asking how I had come to be in the emergency department. I was able to follow commands and sustain my attention during the examination. I could recall three objects immediately but failed to recall any at the five-minute mark. The remainder of the neurological exam did not show any abnormalities.
options: A. Transient global amnesia B. Hypoglycemia C. Depersonalization/derealization disorder D. Seizure E. Delirium F. Dissociative amnesia G. Alzheimer's disease H. Migraine

question:
I am a 40-year-old man who visited the doctor due to experiencing fever and abdominal pain for the past six days. I was also concerned about my recent weight loss, having lost 3.6 kg (8 lb) over the last two months. I have a history of being hospitalized for recurrent cholangitis, which adds to my worries.

During my visit, the healthcare provider checked my vital signs. My heart rate was 97 beats per minute, respiratory rate was 17 breaths per minute, my temperature was 39.0°C (102.2°F), and my blood pressure measured 114/70 mm Hg. They conducted a physical examination and found tenderness when palpating my right upper quadrant.

The doctor ordered a series of laboratory tests. While I do not have the specific results, I understand they were looking for indicators of infection and liver function. An ultrasound was also performed to get a clearer picture of my condition. I am awaiting a diagnosis based on these evaluations and hope to understand the cause of my symptoms soon.
options: A. Hepatocarcinoma B. Liver abscess C. Hepatitis B D. Acute cholecystitis E. Cholangitis

question:
I am a 55-year-old African American male who recently visited my primary care physician due to persistent back pain and fatigue that I have been experiencing for the past 12 months. During my appointment, my blood pressure was measured at 190/150 mm Hg, which was significantly high. 

The doctor conducted further evaluations, and I learned that I have hyperlipidemia. Additionally, a test revealed that my serum creatinine level was 3.0 mg/dL, indicating some level of kidney impairment. I also underwent a 24-hour urine collection, which showed that I was excreting 4.5 grams of protein.

To further investigate my kidney condition, I had a renal biopsy. The results indicated the presence of eosinophilic, acellular material in the glomerular tuft, and the capillary walls displayed apple green-colored birefringence when examined under polarized light after being stained with Congo red. 

These findings have raised concerns about my health, and I am now focused on understanding my condition and discussing potential treatment options with my healthcare provider.
options: A. Membranous nephropathy B. Focal segmental glomerular sclerosis C. Drug-induced acute tubular necrosis D. Multiple myeloma E. Malignant hypertension

question:
I am a 75-year-old woman who experienced a sudden onset of weakness and difficulty walking about an hour ago while I was working in my garden. Along with these symptoms, I felt nauseous and had palpitations. Despite being in an air-conditioned emergency room, I felt unusually warm.

My medical history includes major depressive disorder, which was diagnosed five years ago, as well as hypertension and osteoporosis. I am currently taking several medications: aspirin, lisinopril, alendronate, calcium, venlafaxine, and a vitamin D supplement.

Upon evaluation, my pulse was recorded at 110 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 22 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was 160 over 100 mm Hg. The physical examination did not reveal any significant abnormalities. I underwent a noncontrast CT scan of my head, an electrocardiogram, and routine laboratory tests, all of which returned normal results.

I am left wondering what could be causing these sudden symptoms, as they have had a considerable impact on my ability to function.
options: A. Ischemic stroke B. Dehydration due to physical activity C. Aspirin overdose D. Missed dose of venlafaxine E. Missed dose of lisinopril

question:
I am a 37-year-old woman who recently delivered a male infant weighing 9 pounds 6 ounces via C-section. My delivery was necessary due to preeclampsia with severe features. Prior to this pregnancy, I had a history of type II diabetes, and at my first obstetric visit, my hemoglobin A1c was noted to be 12.8%. I had been taking metformin before becoming pregnant, but during the pregnancy, I was started on insulin. Throughout my routine visits, my glucose logs showed elevated fasting levels above 120 mg/dL and postprandial values exceeding 180 mg/dL. 

During my third trimester, I tested positive for group B Streptococcus. At 38 weeks and 4 days of gestation, I experienced a routine visit where my blood pressure was recorded at 176/103 mmHg, and I reported a severe headache. I did not experience any rupture of membranes or vaginal bleeding. My physician referred me to the obstetric triage unit, where several intravenous doses of labetalol failed to lower my blood pressure or relieve my headache, leading to the decision for a C-section, which was performed without complications. 

After the birth, my infant's Apgar scores were 7 at one minute and 10 at five minutes. However, one hour later, he appeared jittery, had a low body temperature, and during his first feeding attempt, he did not latch and began to shake before becoming lethargic.
options: A. Transplacental action of maternal insulin B. ß-cell hyperplasia C. Neonatal sepsis D. Inborn error of metabolism E. Neonatal encephalopathy

question:
I am a 47-year-old woman who went to the emergency department due to a fever and headache that started yesterday. Initially, I was managing my symptoms with acetaminophen, but they quickly worsened. I began experiencing blurry vision, chills, nausea, and vomiting. 

I have a medical history that includes diabetes and hypertension, for which I take insulin, metformin, lisinopril, and oral contraceptive pills. When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 104°F, and my blood pressure was 157/93 mmHg. My pulse was elevated at 120 beats per minute, while my respirations were 15 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% on room air.

During the examination, the doctor noted exophthalmos in my right eye, and my extraocular movements were limited. There was a noticeable decrease in sensation around the affected eye in the areas supplied by the V1 and V2 branches of the trigeminal nerve. As I waited for a CT scan, I began to feel lethargic and experienced a sudden change in my mental status.
options: A. Acute closed angle glaucoma B. Brain abscess C. Cavernous sinus thrombosis D. Periorbital cellulitis E. Intracranial hemorrhage
